ANSWERS["1"]="<h3>CONCEPT: Myasthenia Gravis</h3><div class=\"hl hl-purple\"><span class=\"hl-icon\"></span><div class=\"hl-body\"><div class=\"hl-title\">Pathophysiology</div><p>MG = <strong>autoimmune destruction of post-synaptic nicotinic AChRs</strong> at NMJ. Anti-AChR Ab in 85%, anti-MuSK in 10%. Thymic abnormality in ~80%. Thymectomy \u2192 remission in 30-40%, improvement in 70-80%.</p></div></div><div class=\"mech-box\"><span class=\"ht\">MG NMJ:</span> Anti-AChR Ab destroys receptors <span class=\"ar\">\u2500\u2500\u25b6</span> Fewer functional AChRs <span class=\"ar\">\u2500\u2500\u25b6</span> Failed end-plate potential <span class=\"ar\">\u2500\u2500\u25b6</span> <span style=\"color:#F43F5E;font-weight:700\">FATIGABLE WEAKNESS</span><br><span class=\"ht\">WHY THYMECTOMY?</span> Thymus drives autoreactive T-cell sensitization. Removal \u2192 remission in 30-40%</div><p><strong>Osserman:</strong> I(Ocular)\u2192IIa(Mild)\u2192IIb(Moderate/bulbar)\u2192III(Acute severe)\u2192IV(Late severe)\u2192V(Intubated)</p><hr class=\"divider-ans\"><h3>A. PREOPERATIVE [3 marks]</h3><h4>1. Respiratory Assessment</h4><ul><li><strong>Spirometry:</strong> FVC, FEV1 \u2014 FVC &lt;2.9 L = high post-op ventilation risk</li><li><strong>Vital Capacity:</strong> &lt;40 mL/kg = high risk; <strong>NIF:</strong> worse than -25 cmH2O = ventilator dependent</li><li><strong>ABG:</strong> CO2 retention = severe disease; <strong>CT chest:</strong> thymoma size, tracheal deviation</li></ul><div class=\"hl hl-warn\"><span class=\"hl-icon\">\u26a0\ufe0f</span><div class=\"hl-body\"><div class=\"hl-title\">Leventhal's Criteria \u2014 Predicting Post-op Ventilation</div><p><strong>1.</strong> Duration of MG >6 years &nbsp;<strong>2.</strong> Chronic respiratory disease &nbsp;<strong>3.</strong> Pyridostigmine dose >750 mg/day &nbsp;<strong>4.</strong> Vital Capacity &lt;2.9 L<br><em>\u22653 criteria \u2192 Plan for post-operative mechanical ventilation. Counsel patient preoperatively.</em></p></div></div><h4>2. Drug Management</h4><ul><li><strong>Continue pyridostigmine</strong> morning of surgery. Abrupt withdrawal \u2192 myasthenic crisis</li><li><strong>Stress dose steroids:</strong> Hydrocortisone 100 mg IV at induction</li><li><strong>Plasmapheresis (3-5 sessions)</strong> or <strong>IVIG 2 g/kg</strong> if poorly controlled</li></ul><div class=\"hl hl-danger\"><span class=\"hl-icon\"></span><div class=\"hl-body\"><div class=\"hl-title\">Drugs to AVOID in MG</div><p>Aminoglycosides, fluoroquinolones, beta-blockers, magnesium sulphate, quinidine, procainamide, D-penicillamine, phenytoin</p></div></div><hr class=\"divider-ans\"><h3>B. INTRAOPERATIVE [4 marks]</h3><h4>1. Monitoring \u2014 TOF is KING</h4><div class=\"drug-grid\"><div class=\"drug-card dc-indigo\"><div class=\"drug-name\">TOF Monitor</div><div class=\"drug-dose\">Train-of-Four ratio</div><div class=\"drug-note\">MOST IMPORTANT. Continuous. Never extubate TOF &lt;0.9</div></div><div class=\"drug-card dc-teal\"><div class=\"drug-name\">BIS Monitor</div><div class=\"drug-dose\">Target 40-60</div><div class=\"drug-note\">Essential with TIVA. Prevents awareness</div></div><div class=\"drug-card dc-amber\"><div class=\"drug-name\">Arterial Line</div><div class=\"drug-dose\">Beat-to-beat BP</div><div class=\"drug-note\">Serial ABG mandatory for sternotomy</div></div><div class=\"drug-card dc-green\"><div class=\"drug-name\">Temperature</div><div class=\"drug-dose\">Keep \u226536\u00b0C</div><div class=\"drug-note\">Hypothermia prolongs NMJ block</div></div></div><h4>2. Induction \u2014 Prefer TIVA Without NMB</h4><div class=\"hl hl-teal\"><span class=\"hl-icon\">\u2b50</span><div class=\"hl-body\"><div class=\"hl-title\">Gold Standard: Propofol + Remifentanil Without NMB</div><p><strong>Propofol 1.5-2.5 mg/kg IV</strong> + <strong>Remifentanil 2-4 mcg/kg IV</strong> \u2192 excellent intubating conditions WITHOUT any NMB. No residual block, predictable recovery.</p></div></div><h4>3. NMB Pharmacology \u2014 Critical</h4><div class=\"hl hl-danger\"><span class=\"hl-icon\"></span><div class=\"hl-body\"><div class=\"hl-title\">Core Rule: NDMR Hypersensitive, Succinylcholine Resistant</div><p>MG = fewer AChRs \u2192 NDMR blocks with <strong>1/10th dose</strong>. Succinylcholine: resistance (fewer receptors to depolarize) \u2192 need higher dose \u2192 Phase II block risk.<br><strong>AVOID succinylcholine. If NDMR needed: Rocuronium 0.1-0.15 mg/kg (NOT 0.6 mg/kg)</strong></p></div></div><table><thead><tr><th>Drug</th><th>MG Dose</th><th>Verdict</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><strong>Succinylcholine</strong></td><td>Unpredictable</td><td style=\"color:var(--rose)\">AVOID \u2014 Phase II block</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Rocuronium</strong></td><td>0.1-0.15 mg/kg</td><td style=\"color:var(--green)\">PREFERRED NDMR</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Atracurium</strong></td><td>0.1-0.2 mg/kg</td><td style=\"color:var(--amber)\">Acceptable</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Mivacurium</strong></td><td>Avoid</td><td style=\"color:var(--rose)\">Pyridostigmine inhibits plasma ChE \u2192 unpredictable</td></tr></tbody></table><h4>4. Maintenance</h4><ul><li><strong>TIVA:</strong> Propofol 4-10 mg/kg/hr + Remifentanil 0.05-0.2 mcg/kg/min</li><li>If volatile: <strong>Sevoflurane preferred</strong> (least NMJ potentiation vs isoflurane/desflurane)</li><li>Normocarbia \u2014 avoid alkalosis \u2192 hypokalaemia \u2192 worsens NMJ block</li><li>For VATS: <strong>OLV with DLT</strong> \u2014 TV 4-6 mL/kg, PEEP 5 cmH2O, I:E 1:2</li><li><strong>Thoracic epidural T4-T6</strong> for open / <strong>Paravertebral block</strong> for VATS \u2014 opioid-sparing</li></ul><h4>5. Reversal \u2014 Sugammadex is Gold Standard</h4><div class=\"hl hl-success\"><span class=\"hl-icon\">\u2705</span><div class=\"hl-body\"><div class=\"hl-title\">Sugammadex 2-4 mg/kg \u2014 Always Over Neostigmine</div><p>Neostigmine inhibits AChE \u2192 \u2191ACh everywhere \u2192 <strong>cholinergic crisis risk</strong> on top of pyridostigmine. Sugammadex encapsulates rocuronium directly \u2014 zero cholinergic effects. TOF must be \u22650.9 before extubation.</p></div></div><hr class=\"divider-ans\"><h3>C. POSTOPERATIVE [3 marks]</h3><table><thead><tr><th>Extubation Criterion</th><th>Target</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>TOF ratio</td><td><strong>&gt;0.9</strong></td></tr><tr><td>Vital Capacity</td><td><strong>&gt;15 mL/kg</strong></td></tr><tr><td>NIF</td><td><strong>Better than -25 cmH2O</strong></td></tr><tr><td>SpO2</td><td><strong>&gt;95%</strong> on FiO2 \u22640.5</td></tr><tr><td>Head lift sustained</td><td><strong>\u22655 seconds</strong></td></tr></tbody></table><h4>ICU Care</h4><ul><li>ICU/HDU mandatory 24-48 hours minimum</li><li>Resume pyridostigmine at 50-75% pre-op dose when oral intake established</li><li>Multimodal opioid-sparing analgesia: paracetamol + NSAIDs + epidural infusion</li><li>Chest physio, incentive spirometry every 4 hours</li></ul><h4>Crisis Recognition</h4><table><thead><tr><th>Feature</th><th>Myasthenic Crisis</th><th>Cholinergic Crisis</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><strong>Cause</strong></td><td>Under-treatment</td><td>Excess anticholinesterase</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Pupils</strong></td><td>Normal/dilated</td><td><strong>Miosis</strong></td></tr><tr><td><strong>Secretions</strong></td><td>Dry</td><td><strong>SLUDGE \u2014 excessive</strong></td></tr><tr><td><strong>Tensilon test</strong></td><td>Improves</td><td>Worsens</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Management</strong></td><td>Intubate + IVIG/plasmapheresis</td><td>Intubate + Atropine + Stop pyridostigmine</td></tr></tbody></table><div class=\"hl hl-danger\"><span class=\"hl-icon\"></span><div class=\"hl-body\"><div class=\"hl-title\">SECURE AIRWAY FIRST \u2014 Differentiate After</div><p>Never give Tensilon test to unintubated patient in respiratory distress. Intubate first, then differentiate.</p></div></div><div class=\"viva-box\"><div class=\"viva-head\"> Viva Corner</div><div class=\"viva-item\"><div class=\"viva-q\">Why avoid succinylcholine in MG?</div><div class=\"viva-a\">Fewer AChRs \u2192 resistance \u2192 need higher dose \u2192 <strong>Phase II block</strong> + pyridostigmine inhibits plasma ChE \u2192 prolonged paralysis</div></div><div class=\"viva-item\"><div class=\"viva-q\">Why Sugammadex over Neostigmine?</div><div class=\"viva-a\">Neostigmine \u2191ACh everywhere \u2192 <strong>cholinergic crisis</strong> risk in patient on pyridostigmine. Sugammadex <strong>encapsulates rocuronium</strong> \u2014 no cholinergic effects</div></div><div class=\"viva-item\"><div class=\"viva-q\">What is Leventhal's criteria?</div><div class=\"viva-a\">4 criteria predicting post-op ventilation: MG >6 yr, chronic respiratory disease, pyridostigmine >750 mg/day, VC &lt;2.9 L. <strong>\u22653 \u2192 plan mechanical ventilation</strong></div></div></div><div class=\"pearl\"><div class=\"pearl-head\">\u2b50 Examiner's Pearl</div><p>Three things that secure full marks: <strong>(1)</strong> Leventhal's criteria \u2014 show you know HOW to predict post-op ventilation. <strong>(2)</strong> TIVA without NMB as preferred induction. <strong>(3)</strong> Sugammadex over neostigmine with cholinergic crisis explanation.</p></div>";
ANSWERS["2"]="<h3>Sitting Position \u2014 Complications Under Anaesthesia</h3><div class=\"hl hl-info\"><span class=\"hl-icon\"></span><div class=\"hl-body\"><div class=\"hl-title\">Positions Used</div><p>Beach chair (shoulder arthroscopy), Fowler's (posterior fossa neurosurgery), semi-recumbent (ICU). Trunk upright 45-90\u00b0, head secured. Creates unique cardiovascular and neurological challenges.</p></div></div><h4>A. Cardiovascular Complications</h4><ul><li><strong>Hypotension (most common):</strong> Venous pooling in lower limbs \u2192 \u2193 venous return \u2192 \u2193 CO \u2192 MAP falls. Brain is ABOVE heart level \u2192 CPP = MAP(at brain) = MAP(arm) \u2212 (height \u00d7 0.77 mmHg/cm). Must measure and maintain CPP \u226570 mmHg at brain level. Rx: vasopressors (phenylephrine, noradrenaline), IV fluids, graduated compression</li><li><strong>Venous Air Embolism (VAE) \u2014 Most Feared:</strong> Open venous sinuses (dural sinuses, diploic veins, epidural veins) at negative pressure \u2192 air enters \u2192 right heart \u2192 pulmonary embolism. Incidence: 25-40% in posterior fossa surgery. Paradoxical Air Embolism (PAE): if PFO present \u2192 air crosses to left heart \u2192 stroke, MI, coronary air embolism</li></ul><div class=\"hl hl-danger\"><span class=\"hl-icon\"></span><div class=\"hl-body\"><div class=\"hl-title\">VAE Monitoring (Sensitivity Order)</div><p>1. <strong>Precordial Doppler</strong> (most sensitive \u2014 detects 0.05 mL/kg air) \u2192 \"mill-wheel\" murmur<br>2. <strong>TEE</strong> (most specific, also detects PAE through PFO)<br>3. <strong>EtCO2 sudden fall</strong> (air dead space \u2192 \u2193 CO2 elimination)<br>4. <strong>ETCO2-PaCO2 gradient widens</strong><br>5. N2 in expired gas (nitrogen monitor)<br>6. CVP rise, BP fall, dysrhythmia</p></div></div><div class=\"hl hl-warn\"><span class=\"hl-icon\">\u26a1</span><div class=\"hl-body\"><div class=\"hl-title\">VAE Treatment \u2014 Act Fast</div><p><strong>1.</strong> Flood surgical field with saline (prevent more air entry)<br><strong>2.</strong> Compress both jugular veins (increase venous pressure at head)<br><strong>3.</strong> Lower head immediately<br><strong>4.</strong> Aspirate air via multi-orifice CVP catheter (placed in right atrium)<br><strong>5.</strong> FiO2 1.0 (avoid N2O \u2014 expands air emboli 2x)<br><strong>6.</strong> Durant's manoeuvre: left lateral decubitus + head down (air moves to RV apex)<br><strong>7.</strong> CPR if cardiac arrest</p></div></div><h4>B. Neurological Complications</h4><ul><li><strong>Cerebral ischaemia:</strong> CPP inadequate if hypotension + sitting. Always calculate MAP at brain level. Keep CPP \u226570 mmHg. Monitor SSEPs/MEPs</li><li><strong>Quadriplegia/tetraplegia:</strong> Extreme neck flexion \u2192 cervical cord ischaemia (stretching + vascular compromise). Pre-existing cervical stenosis = extreme risk. Rule: minimum <strong>2-finger breadth chin-sternum distance</strong></li><li><strong>Cranial nerve injuries:</strong> Excessive neck rotation \u2192 CN VI (abducens), CN XII (hypoglossal) palsy</li></ul><h4>C. Airway Complications</h4><ul><li><strong>Macroglossia/tongue swelling:</strong> Venous/lymphatic obstruction from neck flexion \u2192 massive tongue oedema \u2192 extubation impossible. Check 2-finger chin-chest before positioning</li><li><strong>ETT displacement:</strong> Neck flexion pulls ETT cephalad by 1-2 cm \u2192 risk of endobronchial intubation or extubation. Recheck tube position after positioning. Auscultate both sides</li><li><strong>Difficult extubation:</strong> Oedema of supraglottic structures after prolonged surgery</li></ul><h4>D. Other Complications</h4><ul><li><strong>Pneumocephalus:</strong> Intracranial air \u2192 headache, confusion, meningism, seizures post-op. Avoid N2O (expands intracranial air)</li><li><strong>Pressure injuries:</strong> Sciatic nerve at ischial tuberosities, heel, sacrum \u2014 pad all</li><li><strong>DVT/PE:</strong> Venous stasis in lower limbs \u2192 thrombus \u2192 PE</li><li><strong>Subcutaneous emphysema:</strong> Air tracking along fascial planes</li></ul><table><thead><tr><th>Complication</th><th>Monitor</th><th>Prevention</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>VAE</td><td>Precordial Doppler, EtCO2, TEE</td><td>PEEP 5, avoid N2O, CVP catheter ready</td></tr><tr><td>Hypotension/\u2193CPP</td><td>Invasive arterial (radial), calculate CPP at brain</td><td>Vasopressors, compression stockings</td></tr><tr><td>Cervical cord injury</td><td>SSEPs, MEPs</td><td>2-finger chin-chest, avoid extreme flexion</td></tr><tr><td>Macroglossia</td><td>Clinical inspection post-op</td><td>Avoid excessive neck flexion, reduce duration</td></tr><tr><td>Pneumocephalus</td><td>CT post-op if symptoms</td><td>Avoid N2O, 100% O2 at end</td></tr></tbody></table><div class=\"pearl\"><div class=\"pearl-head\">\u2b50 Examiner's Pearl</div><p><strong>Two facts that always fetch marks:</strong> (1) Precordial Doppler is most SENSITIVE for VAE (not EtCO2 drop). (2) Calculate CPP at <strong>brain level</strong>, not arm level \u2014 subtract 0.77 mmHg per cm height above the heart. These two lines show you understand the physiology, not just facts.</p></div>";
ANSWERS["3"]="<h3>Positioning-Related Nerve Injuries Under Anaesthesia</h3><div class=\"hl hl-purple\"><span class=\"hl-icon\"></span><div class=\"hl-body\"><div class=\"hl-title\">Three Mechanisms of Injury</div><p><strong>1. Compression</strong> \u2014 direct pressure against bony prominence, compresses nerve and its blood supply<br><strong>2. Stretch</strong> \u2014 excessive elongation; nerve tolerates &lt;15% stretch before ischaemia; beyond \u2192 injury<br><strong>3. Ischaemia</strong> \u2014 vasa nervorum compromise from sustained pressure or hypotension</p></div></div><h4>Most Common Nerve Injuries by Position</h4><table><thead><tr><th>Nerve</th><th>Position</th><th>Mechanism</th><th>Clinical Deficit</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><strong>Ulnar nerve (most common overall)</strong></td><td>Supine, lateral</td><td>Compression at medial epicondyle (cubital tunnel). Especially if forearm pronated</td><td>Clawing ring/little fingers, weak intrinsics, sensory loss ulnar 1.5 digits</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Brachial plexus</strong></td><td>Supine, lateral, Trendelenburg</td><td>Stretch (arm abduction >90\u00b0), shoulder braces in Trendelenburg, lateral position without axillary roll</td><td>Upper plexus (Erb's): weak shoulder abduction, wrist drop. Lower plexus (Klumpke's): hand intrinsics</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Radial nerve</strong></td><td>Lateral, prone</td><td>Compression in spiral groove of humerus</td><td>Wrist drop, loss of wrist/finger extension, sensory loss dorsal hand</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Common peroneal nerve (most common leg)</strong></td><td>Lithotomy, lateral</td><td>Compression at fibular head \u2014 especially in candy-cane stirrups</td><td>Foot drop, loss of dorsiflexion and eversion, sensory loss dorsum of foot</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Femoral nerve</strong></td><td>Lithotomy, prone</td><td>Compression by inguinal ligament with excessive hip flexion, retractor pressure</td><td>Weak hip flexion, \u2193 knee reflex, sensory loss anteromedial thigh</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Sciatic nerve</strong></td><td>Lithotomy</td><td>Stretch from external rotation combined with knee extension in stirrups</td><td>Mixed motor/sensory deficit below knee \u2014 foot drop + sensory loss</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Obturator nerve</strong></td><td>Lithotomy</td><td>Excessive hip flexion + medial thigh compression</td><td>Weak hip adduction, sensory loss medial thigh</td></tr></tbody></table><h4>Prevention \u2014 Position-Specific Rules</h4><ul><li><strong>Supine:</strong> Arm abduction &lt;90\u00b0, forearm supinated or neutral, pad medial epicondyle, no pressure on ulnar groove at elbow</li><li><strong>Lateral:</strong> Axillary roll under dependent chest (not axilla), avoid arm abduction >90\u00b0, pad fibular head</li><li><strong>Lithotomy:</strong> Both legs raised/lowered simultaneously, pad popliteal fossa, limit time &lt;2 hours, avoid excessive hip flexion, abduction, external rotation</li><li><strong>Prone:</strong> Arms &lt;90\u00b0 abduction, neutral head position (not extreme rotation), pad iliac crests, avoid pressure on eyes and nose</li><li>Document positioning, pad ALL bony prominences, check periodically during long cases</li></ul><h4>Diagnosis & Management</h4><ul><li><strong>Clinical assessment</strong> immediately post-op \u2014 document deficit (motor and sensory distribution)</li><li><strong>EMG/NCS at 3-4 weeks</strong> (not immediately \u2014 denervation changes take time to appear on EMG)</li><li>Classification: <strong>Neuropraxia</strong> (demyelination, intact axon \u2192 full recovery days-weeks), <strong>Axonotmesis</strong> (axon disrupted, endoneurium intact \u2192 recovery 1-3 mm/day), <strong>Neurotmesis</strong> (complete division \u2192 surgical repair needed)</li><li>Conservative: physiotherapy, splinting to prevent contracture, neuropathic pain = gabapentin 300 mg TDS + amitriptyline</li><li>Surgical: neurotmesis or no recovery after 3-6 months \u2192 nerve repair/grafting</li></ul><div class=\"pearl\"><div class=\"pearl-head\">\u2b50 Examiner's Pearl</div><p><strong>Ulnar nerve</strong> = most common perioperative nerve injury. <strong>Brachial plexus</strong> = most common cause of anaesthesia-related litigation. EMG must be done at <strong>3-4 weeks</strong> not immediately. Neuropraxia \u2192 full recovery; neurotmesis \u2192 surgery. Say the word <strong>neuropraxia, axonotmesis, neurotmesis</strong> \u2014 it shows classification knowledge.</p></div>";
ANSWERS["4"]="<h3>Gas Laws and Anaesthesia</h3><div class='mech-box'><span class='ht'>BOYLE'S LAW:</span>  P\u00d7V = constant  <span class='ar'>\u2500\u2500\u25b6</span> Cylinders, pneumothorax, altitude\n<span class='ht'>CHARLES' LAW:</span>  V/T = constant  <span class='ar'>\u2500\u2500\u25b6</span> Flowmeters, gas volumes at body temp\n<span class='ht'>GAY-LUSSAC:</span>   P/T = constant  <span class='ar'>\u2500\u2500\u25b6</span> Hot cylinder = dangerous pressure rise\n<span class='ht'>DALTON'S LAW:</span>  Ptotal = \u03a3P(each gas) <span class='ar'>\u2500\u2500\u25b6</span> Alveolar gas equation, O2/N2O mixtures\n<span class='ht'>HENRY'S LAW:</span>  [dissolved] \u221d Pgas <span class='ar'>\u2500\u2500\u25b6</span> N2O in body cavities, decompression sickness\n<span class='ht'>GRAHAM'S LAW:</span> Diffusion \u221d 1/\u221aMW <span class='ar'>\u2500\u2500\u25b6</span> O2 vs CO2 diffusion across alveolar membrane</div><table><thead><tr><th>Law</th><th>Statement</th><th>Anaesthetic Application</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><strong>Boyle's</strong></td><td>P\u00d7V = k (constant T)</td><td>\u2022 Air spaces expand at altitude (ETT cuff, pneumothorax, bowel loops, air emboli)<br>\u2022 O2 cylinder pressure falls proportionally as gas used<br>\u2022 N2O cylinder: liquid phase until 25% remaining \u2014 pressure stays constant \u2234 weigh to measure contents</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Charles'</strong></td><td>V/T = k (constant P)</td><td>\u2022 Flowmeters calibrated at room temperature \u2014 hot gas = actual flow higher than indicated<br>\u2022 Tidal volume increases when gas warms to body temperature (BTPS correction)</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Gay-Lussac</strong></td><td>P/T = k (constant V)</td><td>\u2022 Store cylinders in cool area \u2014 heat causes dangerous pressure rise \u2192 explosion risk<br>\u2022 Never apply heat to cylinders</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Dalton's</strong></td><td>P(total) = \u03a3P(individual)</td><td>\u2022 Alveolar gas equation: PAO2 = FiO2(Patm\u2212PH2O) \u2212 PaCO2/RQ<br>\u2022 Hypoxic guard: ensures minimum 25% O2 in any mixture<br>\u2022 Calculating O2 partial pressure at altitude</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Henry's</strong></td><td>[gas dissolved] \u221d partial pressure</td><td>\u2022 N2O (34\u00d7 more soluble than N2) diffuses into closed gas spaces \u2192 pneumothorax, bowel, air emboli expand up to 3\u00d7<br>\u2022 Blood:gas partition coefficient determines speed of induction (desflurane 0.45, sevoflurane 0.65, isoflurane 1.4)<br>\u2022 Decompression sickness: N2 dissolves under pressure, bubbles on ascent</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Graham's</strong></td><td>Diffusion rate \u221d 1/\u221aMW</td><td>\u2022 CO2 diffuses 20\u00d7 faster than O2 across alveolar membrane (solubility effect dominates)<br>\u2022 Diffusion hypoxia (Fink effect): N2O leaves blood faster than N2 enters \u2192 dilutes alveolar O2 \u2192 give 100% O2 for 5 min at end of N2O anaesthesia</td></tr></tbody></table><div class='hl hl-danger'><span class='hl-icon'></span><div class='hl-body'><div class='hl-title'>N2O \u2014 Contraindicated with Closed Gas Spaces (Henry's + Boyle's)</div><p>N2O is 34\u00d7 more soluble than N2. Diffuses INTO gas spaces faster than N2 exits \u2192 spaces expand. <strong>Absolute contraindications:</strong> Pneumothorax, air embolism, bowel obstruction, middle ear surgery, retinal gas injection (SF6, C3F8), pneumocephalus post craniotomy</p></div></div><div class='hl hl-teal'><span class='hl-icon'></span><div class='hl-body'><div class='hl-title'>Why Weigh N2O Cylinders \u2014 Not Read Gauge?</div><p>N2O is a liquid under pressure at room temperature. The cylinder contains liquid N2O + saturated vapour. Vapour pressure stays constant (~750 kPa) regardless of how much liquid remains \u2014 until the last ~25%. Therefore, <strong>pressure gauge is useless until nearly empty. Weight is the only reliable measure of N2O content.</strong></p></div></div><div class='viva-box'><div class='viva-head'> Viva Corner</div><div class='viva-item'><div class='viva-q'>Why does N2O expand closed gas spaces?</div><div class='viva-a'>Henry's Law: N2O is 34\u00d7 more soluble than N2. It diffuses into N2-containing spaces faster than N2 can exit \u2192 net volume increases. At 50% N2O, pneumothorax can double in 10 minutes</div></div><div class='viva-item'><div class='viva-q'>What is diffusion hypoxia and how do you prevent it?</div><div class='viva-a'>At end of N2O anaesthesia, large volume of N2O leaves blood into alveoli rapidly \u2192 dilutes alveolar O2 \u2192 hypoxia. Prevent by giving <strong>100% O2 for 5 minutes</strong> before removing mask</div></div><div class='viva-item'><div class='viva-q'>What is BTPS and why does it matter?</div><div class='viva-a'>Body Temperature Pressure Saturated \u2014 gas volumes must be corrected to 37\u00b0C and 100% humidity when measured at body conditions. Tidal volume delivered to patient is larger than measured at room temperature (Charles' Law)</div></div></div><div class='pearl'><div class='pearl-head'>\u2b50 Examiner's Pearl</div><p>Two questions always asked: <strong>(1)</strong> Why weigh N2O cylinder \u2014 answer uses liquid phase + Henry's Law. <strong>(2)</strong> N2O contraindications list \u2014 pneumothorax, air embolism, bowel obstruction, middle ear, retinal gas, pneumocephalus. Say all six and you've secured the question.</p></div>";
ANSWERS["5"]="<h3>Bain's Coaxial Circuit</h3><div class='hl hl-info'><span class='hl-icon'></span><div class='hl-body'><div class='hl-title'>Classification</div><p>Bain's circuit = <strong>Coaxial modification of Mapleson D</strong>. Inner tube carries fresh gas to patient end; outer corrugated tube carries expired gas back. Introduced by Bain and Spoerel in 1972.</p></div></div><div class='mech-box'><span class='ht'>STRUCTURE (coaxial = tube within tube):</span>\n  Fresh gas \u2500\u2500\u25b6 [inner narrow tube] \u2500\u2500\u25b6 PATIENT END\n  Expired gas \u2500\u2500\u25b6 [outer corrugated tube] \u2500\u2500\u25b6 Bag + APL valve (MACHINE END)\n\n<span class='ht'>KEY POINT:</span> Both reservoir bag and APL valve are at the MACHINE END\n<span class='ht'>HEAT EXCHANGE:</span> Expired gas in outer tube warms incoming fresh gas in inner tube</div><h4>Fresh Gas Flow Requirements</h4><table><thead><tr><th>Mode</th><th>FGF Required</th><th>Rationale</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><strong>Spontaneous ventilation</strong></td><td><strong>2-3\u00d7 minute volume</strong> (200-300 mL/kg/min)</td><td>High flow needed to wash out CO2 \u2014 least efficient mode</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Controlled ventilation (adult)</strong></td><td><strong>70 mL/kg/min</strong> (minimum 4.5 L/min)</td><td>Active expiration aids CO2 washout \u2014 far more efficient</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Paediatric (Rees' modification)</strong></td><td><strong>1000 mL + 100 mL/kg/min</strong></td><td>T-piece modification for children; no bag/APL valve at patient end</td></tr></tbody></table><h4>Advantages</h4><ul><li>Lightweight (180 g) \u2014 minimal drag on mask or ETT during remote anaesthesia</li><li>Low dead space and resistance \u2014 suitable for both spontaneous and controlled ventilation</li><li>Partial humidification \u2014 expired gas in outer tube warms inner fresh gas</li><li>Long tubing (180 cm) \u2014 useful in MRI suites, remote locations, neurosurgery (head away from machine)</li><li>Easy to scavenge expired gases from APL valve at machine end</li></ul><h4>Disadvantages</h4><ul><li><strong>High FGF for spontaneous ventilation</strong> \u2014 expensive, environmental pollution</li><li><strong>Inner tube disconnection/kinking is dangerous and hard to detect:</strong> If inner tube disconnects from machine end, fresh gas no longer reaches patient \u2014 patient rebreathes expired gas through outer tube \u2014 hypercapnia develops undetected as circuit appears to function normally</li><li>Difficult to use for IPPV in neonates (need Rees' modification)</li></ul><div class='hl hl-danger'><span class='hl-icon'></span><div class='hl-body'><div class='hl-title'>Most Dangerous Fault \u2014 Inner Tube Disconnection</div><p>If the inner tube (carrying fresh gas) disconnects at the machine end, the circuit still looks like it is working \u2014 bag moves, EtCO2 shows a trace initially. But patient is rebreathing expired gas \u2192 <strong>progressive hypercapnia without any alarm</strong>. Always check inner tube before use.</p></div></div><h4>Pethick's Test \u2014 Checking Inner Tube Integrity</h4><ul><li>Occlude the patient end of the circuit</li><li>Fill the circuit using the O2 flush (high-flow O2 enters outer tube)</li><li>Release the patient end while still flushing</li><li>If inner tube is intact: Venturi effect at patient end draws gas IN \u2192 bag deflates \u2713</li><li>If inner tube is disconnected: no Venturi effect \u2192 bag stays inflated \u2717</li></ul><div class='viva-box'><div class='viva-head'> Viva Corner</div><div class='viva-item'><div class='viva-q'>What Mapleson classification is Bain's circuit?</div><div class='viva-a'>Mapleson <strong>D</strong> \u2014 most efficient for controlled ventilation among Mapleson systems. Fresh gas at patient end (inner tube), expiratory valve at machine end.</div></div><div class='viva-item'><div class='viva-q'>Why is FGF lower in controlled vs spontaneous ventilation?</div><div class='viva-a'>In controlled ventilation, active inflation forces gas toward patient end and active expiration helps flush CO2. In spontaneous breathing, there is no active flushing mechanism \u2014 need 2-3\u00d7 minute volume to prevent rebreathing</div></div><div class='viva-item'><div class='viva-q'>How do you detect inner tube disconnection clinically?</div><div class='viva-a'>Perform <strong>Pethick's test</strong> before use. During use: progressive \u2191 EtCO2 despite apparently normal circuit, patient shows signs of hypercapnia (tachycardia, hypertension, sweating)</div></div></div><div class='pearl'><div class='pearl-head'>\u2b50 Examiner's Pearl</div><p>Always state four things: <strong>(1)</strong> Mapleson D modification. <strong>(2)</strong> FGF controlled = 70 mL/kg/min; spontaneous = 2-3\u00d7 MV. <strong>(3)</strong> Pethick's test \u2014 how and what it detects. <strong>(4)</strong> Inner tube disconnection is the most dangerous undetected fault. These four points = full marks.</p></div>";
ANSWERS["6"]="<h3>Neonatal Gastroschisis \u2014 Perioperative Management (2 kg, Day 1)</h3><div class='hl hl-purple'><span class='hl-icon'></span><div class='hl-body'><div class='hl-title'>Gastroschisis vs Omphalocele \u2014 Quick Distinction</div><p><strong>Gastroschisis:</strong> Right of umbilicus, NO sac (bare bowel exposed), no chromosomal anomalies, emergency surgery.<br><strong>Omphalocele:</strong> Central/through umbilicus, sac PRESENT, 50% chromosomal anomalies (Trisomy 13/18), cardiac defects common \u2014 semi-elective.</p></div></div><h4>A. Preoperative \u2014 Immediate Stabilisation</h4><ul><li><strong>Bowel protection:</strong> Wrap eviscerated bowel in warm moist saline gauze then transparent cling film \u2014 prevents evaporative loss, maintains temperature, prevents desiccation</li><li><strong>Positioning:</strong> Right lateral decubitus \u2014 prevents bowel kinking and vascular compromise</li><li><strong>NG tube:</strong> Decompress stomach and bowel \u2014 reduces distension, aids reduction</li><li><strong>Temperature:</strong> Radiant warmer + warm fluids \u2014 neonates lose heat rapidly (large surface area:volume ratio)</li><li><strong>IV access:</strong> 2 IV cannulae or umbilical venous catheter (UVC)</li><li><strong>Fluid resuscitation:</strong> Normal saline 10-20 mL/kg bolus \u2014 massive evaporative and third-space losses (up to 200 mL/kg/day from exposed bowel)</li><li><strong>Investigations:</strong> ABG, blood glucose (keep 4-7 mmol/L), FBC, coagulation, crossmatch blood</li><li><strong>Antibiotics:</strong> Ampicillin + gentamicin prophylaxis \u2014 bowel exposed to environment</li></ul><table><thead><tr><th>Target Parameter</th><th>Value</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Temperature</td><td>36.5\u201337.5\u00b0C</td></tr><tr><td>Blood glucose</td><td>4\u20137 mmol/L</td></tr><tr><td>Haemoglobin</td><td>&gt;10 g/dL</td></tr><tr><td>pH</td><td>7.35\u20137.45</td></tr><tr><td>Urine output</td><td>1\u20132 mL/kg/hr</td></tr></tbody></table><h4>B. Intraoperative</h4><div class='hl hl-danger'><span class='hl-icon'></span><div class='hl-body'><div class='hl-title'>RSI Mandatory \u2014 Full Stomach + Bowel Distension</div><p>Neonate = full stomach risk. Pre-oxygenate 2-3 min (neonates desaturate in &lt;30 sec). <strong>Atropine 20 mcg/kg IV \u2192 Fentanyl 2-3 mcg/kg \u2192 Propofol 2 mg/kg or Ketamine 1-2 mg/kg \u2192 Succinylcholine 2 mg/kg \u2192 intubate.</strong> Have suction ready at bedside.</p></div></div><div class='drug-grid'><div class='drug-card dc-teal'><div class='drug-name'>Pre-ductal SpO2</div><div class='drug-dose'>Right hand</div><div class='drug-note'>Detects PPHN \u2014 right-to-left shunt across PDA. Target 95-99%</div></div><div class='drug-card dc-indigo'><div class='drug-name'>Post-ductal SpO2</div><div class='drug-dose'>Right foot</div><div class='drug-note'>Compare with pre-ductal. Gap &gt;5% = significant R\u2192L shunting</div></div><div class='drug-card dc-amber'><div class='drug-name'>Arterial Line</div><div class='drug-dose'>Right radial</div><div class='drug-note'>Beat-to-beat BP + serial ABG every 30-60 min</div></div><div class='drug-card dc-green'><div class='drug-name'>Temperature Probe</div><div class='drug-dose'>Rectal or axillary</div><div class='drug-note'>Active warming: warm OT (26-28\u00b0C), warm fluids, warming mattress</div></div></div><h4>Maintenance</h4><ul><li>Sevoflurane in O2/air (FiO2 titrated to SpO2 94-98% \u2014 avoid hyperoxia \u2192 retinopathy of prematurity)</li><li><strong>AVOID N2O</strong> \u2014 expands bowel gas \u2192 impossible to reduce bowel into abdomen \u2192 surgical catastrophe</li><li>Vecuronium 0.1 mg/kg or rocuronium 0.6 mg/kg for relaxation (aids bowel reduction)</li><li>Fentanyl 1-3 mcg/kg/hr infusion</li><li>Fluid: 0.9% NaCl + 10% dextrose at 4 mL/kg/hr baseline; replace third-space losses with NS 10-20 mL/kg/hr during bowel reduction</li><li>Blood transfuse if Hb &lt;10 g/dL \u2014 10 mL/kg packed red cells</li></ul><h4>Primary Closure vs Staged Silo \u2014 Key Decision</h4><div class='hl hl-warn'><span class='hl-icon'>\u26a0\ufe0f</span><div class='hl-body'><div class='hl-title'>Intraabdominal Pressure (IAP) Determines Approach</div><p><strong>Primary closure</strong> if: IAP (intragastric pressure via NG tube manometer) &lt;20 cmH2O after reduction + SpO2 maintained + UO adequate + haemodynamics stable.<br><strong>Staged silo</strong> if: bowel too oedematous, IAP &gt;20 cmH2O \u2014 place bowel in silastic silo, reduce gradually over 5-7 days, return for definitive closure.</p></div></div><h4>C. Postoperative</h4><ul><li><strong>Planned ventilation:</strong> All neonates need ICU + mechanical ventilation 24-72 hours (elevated IAP \u2192 diaphragm splinting \u2192 \u2193 FRC)</li><li>Ventilator: TV 4-6 mL/kg, PEEP 4-5 cmH2O, RR 40-60/min, FiO2 titrated</li><li>Analgesia: Morphine 0.01-0.05 mg/kg/hr + Paracetamol 7.5 mg/kg IV 8-hourly</li><li><strong>Nutrition:</strong> TPN immediately \u2014 bowel recovery delayed weeks in gastroschisis (bowel peel/damage). Start trophic enteral feeds only when bowel sounds return</li><li>Watch for: abdominal compartment syndrome, NEC, short bowel syndrome, wound infection</li></ul><div class='viva-box'><div class='viva-head'> Viva Corner</div><div class='viva-item'><div class='viva-q'>Why is N2O absolutely contraindicated in gastroschisis repair?</div><div class='viva-a'>N2O is 34\u00d7 more soluble than N2 \u2192 rapidly enters gas-filled bowel loops \u2192 <strong>bowel expands massively</strong> \u2192 cannot reduce into abdomen \u2192 bowel ischaemia \u2192 surgical catastrophe. Avoid throughout entire case.</div></div><div class='viva-item'><div class='viva-q'>How do you decide primary closure vs silo?</div><div class='viva-a'>Measure intragastric pressure via NG tube after attempted reduction. If IAP <strong>&lt;20 cmH2O</strong> + SpO2 maintained + urine output adequate \u2192 primary closure safe. Otherwise \u2192 silo.</div></div><div class='viva-item'><div class='viva-q'>Why monitor both pre-ductal and post-ductal SpO2?</div><div class='viva-a'>Neonates with abdominal wall defects have risk of <strong>Persistent Pulmonary Hypertension of Newborn (PPHN)</strong> \u2192 R\u2192L shunting across patent ductus arteriosus. Pre-ductal (right hand) reflects cerebral/coronary O2 delivery. Gap &gt;5% between pre and post-ductal = significant shunting.</div></div></div><div class='pearl'><div class='pearl-head'>\u2b50 Examiner's Pearl</div><p>Three critical points: <strong>(1)</strong> No N2O \u2014 ever \u2014 reason must be stated. <strong>(2)</strong> IAP &lt;20 cmH2O for primary closure \u2014 show you know how to measure it. <strong>(3)</strong> Pre-ductal + post-ductal SpO2 monitoring \u2014 shows PPHN awareness. These three lines alone demonstrate clinical depth.</p></div>";
ANSWERS["7"]="<h3>Part A: CSF Circulation [5 marks]</h3><div class='mech-box'><span class='ht'>CSF PRODUCTION:</span> Choroid plexus (70%) + ependymal cells (30%) = 500 mL/day (0.35 mL/min)\nTotal CSF volume: 150 mL adult / 50 mL neonate. Pressure: 10-15 mmHg lateral recumbent\n\n<span class='ht'>FLOW PATHWAY:</span>\nLateral Ventricles (choroid plexus \u2014 main production site)\n    <span class='ar'>\u2193</span>  Foramen of Monro (Interventricular foramina)\nThird Ventricle\n    <span class='ar'>\u2193</span>  Aqueduct of Sylvius \u2190 MOST COMMON SITE OF OBSTRUCTION\nFourth Ventricle\n    <span class='ar'>\u2193</span>  Foramen of Magendie (median) + Foramina of Luschka (lateral \u00d72)\nSubarachnoid space \u2192 Cisterna magna \u2192 Basal cisterns\n    <span class='ar'>\u2193</span>  Flows over cerebral convexities\nArachnoid granulations (Pacchionian bodies) \u2192 Superior Sagittal Sinus \u2192 Venous blood\n\n<span class='ht'>HYDROCEPHALUS:</span>\nObstructive (non-communicating): Block WITHIN ventricular system (aqueduct most common)\nCommunicating: Block at arachnoid granulations \u2014 CSF in subarachnoid but not absorbed\nNPH: Normal pressure triad = Gait apraxia + Dementia + Urinary incontinence</div><table><thead><tr><th>CSF Property</th><th>Value</th><th>Clinical Note</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Production rate</td><td>0.35 mL/min (500 mL/day)</td><td>Relatively constant; not affected by ICP</td></tr><tr><td>Total volume</td><td>150 mL (adult)</td><td>Replaced ~3-4\u00d7 per day</td></tr><tr><td>Normal ICP</td><td>10-15 mmHg (supine)</td><td>&gt;20 mmHg = raised ICP</td></tr><tr><td>Protein</td><td>15-45 mg/dL</td><td>Raised in meningitis, GBS, tumours</td></tr><tr><td>Glucose</td><td>60-70% of plasma glucose</td><td>Low in bacterial meningitis (&lt;45 mg/dL)</td></tr><tr><td>Cells</td><td>&lt;5 WBC/mm\u00b3</td><td>Raised in infection, SAH</td></tr></tbody></table><hr class='divider-ans'><h3>Part B: Anaesthetic Management \u2014 VP Shunt in 3-year-old [5 marks]</h3><div class='hl hl-warn'><span class='hl-icon'>\u26a0\ufe0f</span><div class='hl-body'><div class='hl-title'>Key Challenges</div><p><strong>1.</strong> Child with raised ICP \u2014 induction carries herniation risk<br><strong>2.</strong> Paediatric airway, drug doses, temperature regulation<br><strong>3.</strong> Two surgical sites \u2014 head + abdomen \u2014 position changes mid-surgery<br><strong>4.</strong> Must avoid anything that further \u2191 ICP during induction (coughing, straining, hypercapnia)</p></div></div><h4>Preoperative Assessment</h4><ul><li>Signs of raised ICP: Bulging fontanelle, sunset sign, papilloedema, vomiting (especially morning), irritability, Cushing's triad (bradycardia + hypertension + irregular breathing = late, ominous sign)</li><li>Airway: Macrocephaly may make positioning difficult \u2014 pad under shoulders to align airway</li><li>Fasting: 2-4-6 rule (2 hr clear fluids, 4 hr breast milk, 6 hr solids)</li><li>ETT size: (Age/4) + 3.5 for cuffed = (3/4) + 3.5 \u2248 4.25 \u2192 use size 4 cuffed ETT</li></ul><h4>Induction</h4><ul><li><strong>If IV access available (preferred with raised ICP):</strong> Propofol 2-3 mg/kg + Fentanyl 1-2 mcg/kg \u2192 Rocuronium 0.6 mg/kg \u2192 intubate smoothly. Avoid coughing or straining on ETT</li><li><strong>If no IV access:</strong> Inhalational induction with Sevoflurane (smooth, causes least \u2191 CBF at &lt;1 MAC). Avoid desflurane (airway irritant) and high-dose isoflurane (\u2191 CBF)</li><li>Atropine 20 mcg/kg IV pre-induction \u2014 prevent bradycardia</li><li>Head 15-20\u00b0 elevation throughout \u2014 promotes venous drainage, \u2193 ICP</li><li>Avoid ketamine traditionally (\u2191 CMRO2 and ICP \u2014 though recent evidence less clear)</li></ul><h4>Maintenance</h4><ul><li>TIVA with propofol preferred (\u2193 CBF, \u2193 CMRO2, antiemetic properties)</li><li>Or sevoflurane &lt;1 MAC with moderate hyperventilation (PaCO2 30-35 mmHg if brain tight)</li><li>Normoventilation as default (PaCO2 35-40 mmHg)</li><li>Avoid glucose-containing hypotonic fluids in large volume \u2014 worsen cerebral oedema</li><li>Antibiotics at induction: Cefazolin 25 mg/kg IV \u2014 shunt infection prevention</li><li>PONV prophylaxis: Ondansetron 0.1 mg/kg IV \u2014 vomiting raises ICP sharply</li></ul><h4>Specific VP Shunt Considerations</h4><ul><li>Two surgical positions \u2014 head repositioned, then abdomen accessed \u2014 check ETT position each time</li><li>Surgeon tunnels shunt subcutaneously from head to abdomen \u2014 brief but stimulating</li><li>Mannitol 0.25-0.5 g/kg IV if brain bulging at craniotomy</li><li>Watch for sudden bradycardia during abdominal access \u2014 vagal stimulation</li><li>VAE risk during head end with sitting position \u2014 if used</li></ul><h4>Postoperative</h4><ul><li>Extubate awake \u2014 protective reflexes fully returned</li><li>PACU 2 hours, then ward/HDU depending on pre-op status</li><li>Analgesia: Paracetamol 15 mg/kg IV 6-hourly + surgeon's local infiltration</li><li>Watch for: shunt malfunction (\u2191 ICP post-op), haemorrhage, shunt infection, over-drainage (subdural haematoma)</li></ul><div class='pearl'><div class='pearl-head'>\u2b50 Examiner's Pearl</div><p>In CSF section: always name <strong>Aqueduct of Sylvius</strong> as the most common obstruction site and <strong>Arachnoid granulations</strong> as absorption site \u2014 examiners check these specific names. In anaesthesia section: mention BOTH induction scenarios (IV vs inhalational) and always explain HOW you prevent ICP rise during induction \u2014 this shows clinical maturity.</p></div>";
ANSWERS["8"]="<h3>Bronchial Blockers</h3><div class='hl hl-info'><span class='hl-icon'></span><div class='hl-body'><div class='hl-title'>Concept</div><p>Bronchial blockers are devices inserted through or alongside a standard single-lumen ETT to selectively occlude a mainstem bronchus and achieve one-lung ventilation (OLV) \u2014 without using a double-lumen tube (DLT). Placement requires fibreoptic bronchoscope (FOB) guidance.</p></div></div><table><thead><tr><th>Device</th><th>Key Feature</th><th>Sizes</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><strong>Arndt Wire-Guided</strong></td><td>Loop at tip couples to FOB; guided by wire. Most widely used</td><td>5F, 7F, 9F</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Cohen Flex-Tip</strong></td><td>Steerable wheel mechanism; directed without wire loop</td><td>9F</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Univent Tube</strong></td><td>Built-in blocker channel within single-lumen ETT; integral design</td><td>Various</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Fuji Uniblocker</strong></td><td>Fixed curve; simple, no wire needed</td><td>5F, 9F</td></tr><tr><td><strong>EZ-Blocker</strong></td><td>Bifurcated Y-tip rests at carina; can block either side without repositioning</td><td>7F</td></tr></tbody></table><h4>Technique (Arndt Blocker Example)</h4><ul><li>Intubate with appropriate size single-lumen ETT (at least 8.0 mm for adult to pass FOB + blocker)</li><li>Attach multiport adaptor \u2014 allows FOB + blocker simultaneously without circuit disconnect</li><li>Pass FOB through ETT, identify carina and target bronchus</li><li>Thread wire loop of Arndt blocker over FOB \u2192 advance together into target bronchus</li><li>Inflate blocker cuff (5-8 mL air); verify position with FOB \u2014 cuff should be just below carina in target bronchus</li><li>Disconnect wire loop; FOB can be removed</li><li>Clamp or open inner lumen of blocker to allow lung collapse</li></ul><h4>When to Prefer Bronchial Blocker Over DLT</h4><ul><li><strong>Difficult airway</strong> \u2014 DLT is large (35-41 Fr), rigid, requires large glottic opening; single-lumen ETT easier to place first</li><li><strong>Tracheostomy patients</strong> \u2014 DLT cannot be inserted through stoma</li><li><strong>Paediatric patients</strong> \u2014 DLT available only from ~35 Fr (approx 8-9 years); younger children need blocker through age-appropriate ETT</li><li><strong>Selective lobar blockade</strong> \u2014 can block a single lobe (e.g., upper lobe only) which DLT cannot achieve</li><li><strong>ICU patients already intubated</strong> \u2014 blocker passed through existing ETT without re-intubation</li><li><strong>Post-op ventilation needed</strong> \u2014 leave single-lumen ETT in place; remove blocker</li></ul><h4>Bronchial Blocker vs DLT \u2014 Comparison</h4><table><thead><tr><th>Feature</th><th>Bronchial Blocker</th><th>DLT</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Airway trauma</td><td style='color:var(--green)'>Less \u2014 smaller tube</td><td style='color:var(--rose)'>More \u2014 large rigid tube</td></tr><tr><td>Difficult airway</td><td style='color:var(--green)'>Excellent</td><td style='color:var(--rose)'>Challenging</td></tr><tr><td>Paediatrics</td><td style='color:var(--green)'>Yes</td><td style='color:var(--rose)'>Limited (>8 yr only)</td></tr><tr><td>Tracheostomy</td><td style='color:var(--green)'>Yes</td><td style='color:var(--rose)'>No</td></tr><tr><td>Suction collapsed lung</td><td style='color:var(--rose)'>Poor (small lumen)</td><td style='color:var(--green)'>Excellent</td></tr><tr><td>CPAP to collapsed lung</td><td style='color:var(--rose)'>Difficult</td><td style='color:var(--green)'>Easy</td></tr><tr><td>Lobar blockade</td><td style='color:var(--green)'>Yes</td><td style='color:var(--rose)'>No</td></tr><tr><td>Speed of OLV</td><td style='color:var(--rose)'>Slower to set up</td><td style='color:var(--green)'>Faster</td></tr><tr><td>Post-op ventilation</td><td style='color:var(--green)'>Easy (remove blocker)</td><td style='color:var(--rose)'>Must change to SLT</td></tr></tbody></table><h4>Complications</h4><ul><li><strong>Displacement</strong> (most common) \u2014 blocker migrates proximally into trachea \u2192 bilateral ventilation resumes. Confirm position with FOB after any position change</li><li>Overinflation of cuff \u2192 bronchial rupture</li><li>Incomplete lung collapse \u2192 poor surgical exposure</li><li>Hypoxia during OLV \u2014 manage with CPAP 2-5 cmH2O to collapsed lung; if persistent, intermittent reinflation</li></ul><div class='pearl'><div class='pearl-head'>\u2b50 Examiner's Pearl</div><p>Three specific points: <strong>(1)</strong> Arndt is the most commonly used bronchial blocker \u2014 name it specifically. <strong>(2)</strong> Bronchial blocker preferred over DLT in difficult airway, paediatrics, and tracheostomy \u2014 know WHY. <strong>(3)</strong> Biggest disadvantage vs DLT: cannot effectively suction or apply CPAP to collapsed lung. These three points = full marks in a 5-mark question.</p></div>";
ANSWERS["9"]="<h3>Post-Exposure Prophylaxis (PEP) \u2014 Needle Stick from HIV+ Patient</h3><div class='hl hl-danger'><span class='hl-icon'></span><div class='hl-body'><div class='hl-title'>TIME IS CRITICAL \u2014 Start Within 2 Hours, Maximum 72 Hours</div><p>Risk of HIV transmission from hollow-bore needle stick with HIV+ source: <strong>~0.3%</strong> (solid needle: 0.1%). PEP reduces this risk by ~81%. Beyond 72 hours PEP is not started \u2014 ineffective. Ideal start: within 2 hours.</p></div></div><h4>Step 1 \u2014 Immediate First Aid (First 5 Minutes)</h4><ul><li>Remove gloves immediately</li><li>Wash wound with soap and water for 5 minutes under running water</li><li><strong>Do NOT squeeze, suck, or scrub the wound</strong> \u2014 increases local trauma and infection risk</li><li>Allow wound to bleed freely under water (do not use tourniquet)</li><li>Apply antiseptic: 70% ethanol, 0.5% chlorhexidine, or 10% povidone-iodine</li><li>Eye/mucous membrane splash: irrigate with copious normal saline or water for 10-15 minutes</li></ul><h4>Step 2 \u2014 Risk Assessment</h4><table><thead><tr><th>Factor</th><th>Higher Risk</th><th>Lower Risk</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Source HIV viral load</td><td>Detectable / high VL (&gt;1000 copies/mL)</td><td>Undetectable (&lt;200 copies/mL on ART)</td></tr><tr><td>Needle/device type</td><td>Hollow-bore blood-filled needle</td><td>Solid suture needle, lancet</td></tr><tr><td>Depth of injury</td><td>Deep puncture wound</td><td>Superficial scratch</td></tr><tr><td>Blood visible on device</td><td>Yes</td><td>No</td></tr><tr><td>Source disease stage</td><td>AIDS or acute seroconversion</td><td>Asymptomatic, well-controlled on ART</td></tr></tbody></table><h4>Step 3 \u2014 Report and Document</h4><ul><li>Report immediately to occupational health / infection control officer / senior</li><li>Document: exact time, date, mechanism, body part, source patient details, first aid given</li><li>Baseline bloods from exposed healthcare worker: HIV ELISA (4th generation), HBsAg, anti-HBs titre, anti-HCV, LFT, RFT, FBC</li><li>Consent source patient for HIV, HBV, HCV testing if possible</li></ul><h4>Step 4 \u2014 PEP Drug Regimen (WHO 2021 / NACO Guidelines)</h4><div class='hl hl-teal'><span class='hl-icon'></span><div class='hl-body'><div class='hl-title'>Preferred First-Line PEP Regimen \u2014 28 Days</div><p><strong>TDF (Tenofovir 300 mg) + 3TC (Lamivudine 300 mg) once daily PLUS DTG (Dolutegravir 50 mg) once daily</strong><br>Duration: Exactly <strong>28 days</strong>. Must complete full course \u2014 partial course = no benefit.</p></div></div><h4>Alternative Regimens (if DTG unavailable/contraindicated)</h4><ul><li>TDF + 3TC + Raltegravir 400 mg BD (alternative integrase inhibitor)</li><li>TDF + FTC (Emtricitabine) + Lopinavir/ritonavir 400/100 mg BD (more GI side effects)</li><li>Older regimen: AZT + 3TC + LPV/r (more anaemia risk \u2014 avoid if possible)</li></ul><h4>Step 5 \u2014 Follow-Up Schedule</h4><table><thead><tr><th>Timepoint</th><th>Tests Required</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Baseline (day 0)</td><td>HIV ELISA, LFT, RFT, FBC, HBV, HCV</td></tr><tr><td>2 weeks</td><td>LFT, RFT, FBC \u2014 monitor drug toxicity</td></tr><tr><td>6 weeks</td><td>HIV ELISA \u2014 early seroconversion</td></tr><tr><td>3 months</td><td>HIV ELISA, HCV RNA</td></tr><tr><td>6 months</td><td><strong>Final HIV ELISA (4th generation)</strong> \u2014 window period ends here; confirms seroconversion or clearance</td></tr></tbody></table><h4>Concurrent HBV Prophylaxis</h4><ul><li>If HCW vaccinated + anti-HBs titre &gt;10 mIU/mL \u2192 no further action</li><li>If unvaccinated \u2192 HBIG 0.06 mL/kg IM + initiate HBV vaccination series immediately</li><li>If vaccine status unknown \u2192 check anti-HBs; if inadequate \u2192 HBIG + booster dose</li></ul><h4>Counselling</h4><ul><li>PEP is not 100% protective \u2014 continue safe practices throughout</li><li>Use barrier contraception until 6-month follow-up complete</li><li>Do not donate blood, organs, or sperm during this period</li><li>Report side effects (nausea, fatigue, rash, renal symptoms) promptly</li><li>Provide psychological support \u2014 needle-stick exposures cause significant anxiety</li></ul><div class='pearl'><div class='pearl-head'>\u2b50 Examiner's Pearl</div><p>Three facts always checked: <strong>(1)</strong> PEP must start within <strong>72 hours</strong> (ideally 2 hours) \u2014 beyond this, don't start. <strong>(2)</strong> Preferred regimen: <strong>TDF + 3TC + DTG \u00d7 28 days</strong> \u2014 name all three drugs. <strong>(3)</strong> Final HIV test at <strong>6 months</strong> (4th generation assay \u2014 covers window period). Transmission risk = 0.3% \u2014 state this number.</p></div>";
ANSWERS["10"]="<h3>Perioperative Management: COPD Exacerbation + Radical Cholecystectomy (60M, Smoker)</h3><div class='hl hl-danger'><span class='hl-icon'></span><div class='hl-body'><div class='hl-title'>Critical First Decision \u2014 Should Surgery Proceed During Active Exacerbation?</div><p>Active COPD exacerbation = pulmonary complication rate \u00d73 higher. Radical cholecystectomy for cancer = semi-urgent. <strong>Optimise COPD maximally before proceeding.</strong> Target: febrile settled, PEF within 80% of personal best, clear sputum, SpO2 at patient's baseline.</p></div></div><h4>A. Preoperative Assessment</h4><h4>1. GOLD Classification</h4><table><thead><tr><th>GOLD Stage</th><th>FEV1 (% predicted)</th><th>Anaesthetic Risk</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>I Mild</td><td>\u226580%</td><td>Low</td></tr><tr><td>II Moderate</td><td>50-79%</td><td>Moderate</td></tr><tr><td>III Severe</td><td>30-49%</td><td>High \u2014 plan HDU/ICU</td></tr><tr><td>IV Very Severe</td><td>&lt;30%</td><td>Very High \u2014 plan post-op ventilation</td></tr></tbody></table><h4>2. Key Investigations</h4><ul><li><strong>Spirometry:</strong> FEV1, FVC, FEV1/FVC &lt;0.7 confirms COPD; FEV1 &lt;50% = significant risk</li><li><strong>ABG:</strong> PaO2, PaCO2 \u2014 chronic CO2 retention (PaCO2 &gt;45) = likely post-op ventilator dependence</li><li><strong>Chest X-ray:</strong> Hyperinflation, flattened diaphragm, bullae, new infiltrates (current exacerbation?)</li><li><strong>ECG:</strong> P pulmonale, right axis deviation, RBBB \u2014 cor pulmonale?</li><li><strong>Echo:</strong> RVSP, RV function if cor pulmonale suspected</li><li><strong>Sputum culture:</strong> Targeted antibiotics for infective exacerbation</li></ul><h4>3. Preoperative Optimisation</h4><ul><li><strong>Bronchodilators:</strong> Nebulised salbutamol 2.5 mg + ipratropium 0.5 mg every 4-6 hours. NEVER stop LABA/LAMA pre-op \u2014 continue all inhalers on day of surgery</li><li><strong>Antibiotics:</strong> If purulent sputum or fever \u2014 culture-guided; empirical: amoxicillin-clavulanate or doxycycline</li><li><strong>Steroids:</strong> Prednisolone 30-40 mg oral \u00d7 5 days for exacerbation; stress dose hydrocortisone 100 mg IV at induction if on long-term steroids</li><li><strong>Smoking cessation:</strong> Even 24-48 hrs: \u2193 carboxyhaemoglobin (improves O2 delivery). 4-6 weeks: \u2193 secretions. 8 weeks: significant \u2193 pulmonary complications. Counsel firmly</li><li><strong>Physiotherapy:</strong> Chest physio, incentive spirometry, postural drainage</li></ul><h4>B. Intraoperative Management</h4><div class='hl hl-teal'><span class='hl-icon'></span><div class='hl-body'><div class='hl-title'>Regional Anaesthesia = Superior Pulmonary Outcome</div><p>Where possible, prefer regional over GA \u2014 avoids intubation and positive pressure ventilation. For this case: <strong>Thoracic epidural T6-T8 + monitored sedation</strong> if cooperative. Otherwise: <strong>GA + thoracic epidural combined</strong> for superior post-op analgesia (single most effective intervention to reduce post-op pulmonary complications).</p></div></div><h4>Drug Selection</h4><table><thead><tr><th>Drug</th><th>Decision</th><th>Reason</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Ketamine</td><td style='color:var(--green)'>PREFER</td><td>\u03b2-sympathomimetic \u2192 bronchodilation; maintains airway reflexes</td></tr><tr><td>Propofol</td><td style='color:var(--green)'>USE</td><td>Bronchodilator properties; reduces airway reactivity at induction</td></tr><tr><td>Sevoflurane</td><td style='color:var(--green)'>USE</td><td>Bronchodilator volatile agent; smooth emergence</td></tr><tr><td>Cisatracurium</td><td style='color:var(--green)'>USE</td><td>No histamine release</td></tr><tr><td>Morphine</td><td style='color:var(--amber)'>CAUTION</td><td>Histamine release \u2192 bronchoconstriction; prefer fentanyl</td></tr><tr><td>Atracurium</td><td style='color:var(--rose)'>AVOID</td><td>Histamine release \u2192 bronchoconstriction</td></tr><tr><td>Desflurane</td><td style='color:var(--rose)'>AVOID on induction</td><td>Airway irritant; pungent \u2192 bronchospasm, coughing, laryngospasm</td></tr></tbody></table><h4>Ventilation Strategy \u2014 CRITICAL in COPD</h4><div class='hl hl-warn'><span class='hl-icon'>\u26a0\ufe0f</span><div class='hl-body'><div class='hl-title'>Prevent Auto-PEEP (Dynamic Hyperinflation)</div><p>COPD = small airway obstruction \u2192 incomplete expiration \u2192 gas trapping (Auto-PEEP). Can cause haemodynamic collapse (\u2193 venous return) and pneumothorax.<br><strong>Strategy: Low RR (10-12/min) + Long expiratory time (I:E = 1:3 to 1:4) + Low TV (6-8 mL/kg) + Minimal applied PEEP + Permissive hypercapnia (PaCO2 45-55 mmHg)</strong></p></div></div><ul><li>FiO2: Titrate to SpO2 <strong>94-96%</strong> \u2014 NOT 100% (abolishes hypoxic drive in CO2 retainers)</li><li>Detect auto-PEEP: Flow-time loop on ventilator \u2014 expiratory flow not returning to zero line before next breath</li><li>Invasive arterial line mandatory \u2014 serial ABG; capnography (note: ETCO2 underestimates PaCO2 in COPD)</li></ul><h4>C. Postoperative Management</h4><h4>Analgesia \u2014 Thoracic Epidural is Gold Standard</h4><div class='hl hl-success'><span class='hl-icon'>\u2b50</span><div class='hl-body'><div class='hl-title'>T6-T8 Epidural = Best Single Intervention for Post-op Pulmonary Recovery</div><p>Excellent analgesia \u2192 patient breathes deeply and coughs effectively \u2192 prevents atelectasis \u2192 prevents pneumonia. Infusion: Bupivacaine 0.1% + Fentanyl 2 mcg/mL at 4-8 mL/hr. This is the most important post-op intervention in COPD + upper abdominal surgery.</p></div></div><ul><li>Scheduled paracetamol 1g IV 6-hourly; NSAIDs carefully (check renal function)</li><li>Avoid high-dose opioids \u2014 \u2193 respiratory drive + \u2191 secretions</li><li>Nebulised bronchodilators every 4-6 hours post-op</li><li>Chest physiotherapy every 4 hours; incentive spirometry every 1-2 hours while awake</li><li>Early ambulation 24-48 hours post-op</li><li>SpO2 target 94-96% \u2014 not 100%</li><li>NIV (BiPAP) if respiratory deterioration \u2014 before considering reintubation</li><li>ICU/HDU if: GOLD III/IV, PaCO2 &gt;45 pre-op, prolonged surgery, or intraoperative complications</li></ul><div class='viva-box'><div class='viva-head'> Viva Corner</div><div class='viva-item'><div class='viva-q'>What is auto-PEEP and how do you prevent it?</div><div class='viva-a'>Auto-PEEP = intrinsic PEEP from incomplete expiration due to small airway obstruction. Gas traps \u2192 \u2191 FRC \u2192 \u2193 venous return \u2192 hypotension + risk of pneumothorax. Prevent: <strong>low RR, long expiratory phase (I:E 1:3-4), low TV, minimal extrinsic PEEP</strong>. Detect on flow-time loop.</div></div><div class='viva-item'><div class='viva-q'>Why target SpO2 94-96% and not 100% in COPD?</div><div class='viva-a'>Chronic CO2 retainers lose central chemoreceptor sensitivity to CO2 and rely on peripheral chemoreceptors' <strong>hypoxic drive</strong>. High FiO2 abolishes hypoxic drive \u2192 respiratory depression \u2192 worsening hypercapnia. SpO2 94-96% maintains drive without hypoxia.</div></div><div class='viva-item'><div class='viva-q'>How long should smoking cessation be before elective surgery for maximum benefit?</div><div class='viva-a'><strong>24-48 hours</strong>: \u2193 carboxyhaemoglobin. <strong>4-6 weeks</strong>: \u2193 bronchial secretions. <strong>8 weeks</strong>: significant \u2193 pulmonary complications. Advise 8 weeks minimum for elective surgery.</div></div></div><div class='pearl'><div class='pearl-head'>\u2b50 Examiner's Pearl</div><p>Three answers that distinguish excellent from average: <strong>(1)</strong> Active exacerbation \u2014 first optimise, state your targets. <strong>(2)</strong> Ventilation: low RR + long expiratory time + permissive hypercapnia \u2014 auto-PEEP prevention. <strong>(3)</strong> Thoracic epidural for post-op analgesia \u2014 state it as the single most effective pulmonary intervention. These three demonstrate you think like a consultant.</p></div>";
ANSWERS["11"]="<h3>Brain Death \u2014 Criteria and Confirmatory Tests</h3><div class='hl hl-purple'><span class='hl-icon'></span><div class='hl-body'><div class='hl-title'>Definition (India \u2014 THO Act 1994, amended 2011)</div><p>Brain death = <strong>irreversible cessation of all functions of the entire brain including the brainstem</strong>. It is equivalent to death under Indian law. Must be certified by a board of 4 doctors (including a neurologist/neurosurgeon and the treating doctor) before organ donation.</p></div></div><div class='mech-box'><span class='ht'>PREREQUISITES (must ALL be satisfied before testing):</span>\n1. Known cause of irreversible brain damage (trauma, SAH, anoxia, tumour)\n2. Core temperature \u226532\u00b0C (hypothermia mimics brain death)\n3. No drug intoxication \u2014 sedatives, opioids, NMBs, alcohol, barbiturates cleared\n4. No metabolic derangement \u2014 Na 125-160, glucose 3-20, PaCO2 35-45, PaO2 >60\n5. No circulatory shock \u2014 MAP \u226560 mmHg\n6. No neuromuscular blocking drugs on board</div><h4>A. Clinical Criteria (Brainstem Reflexes \u2014 All Must Be Absent)</h4><table><thead><tr><th>Test</th><th>Reflex/Response Tested</th><th>Brain Death = ABSENT</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><strong>Pupillary light reflex</strong></td><td>CN II (afferent) + CN III (efferent)</td><td>Fixed, dilated (4-9 mm), no response to bright light</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Corneal reflex</strong></td><td>CN V1 afferent + CN VII efferent</td><td>No blink on corneal touch with cotton wool</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Oculocephalic reflex</strong> (Doll's eye)</td><td>CN VIII + III, VI \u2014 MLF integrity</td><td>Eyes move with head (normal) \u2192 absent = brain dead (eyes stay midline)</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Oculovestibular reflex</strong> (Cold caloric)</td><td>CN VIII + III, VI</td><td>30 mL ice water \u2192 no eye deviation toward irrigated ear</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Gag reflex</strong></td><td>CN IX afferent + CN X efferent</td><td>Pharyngeal stimulation \u2192 no gag</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Cough reflex</strong></td><td>CN X \u2014 vagal</td><td>Deep tracheal suction \u2192 no cough</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Motor response to pain</strong></td><td>Cortical/brainstem</td><td>Supraorbital pressure/nail bed \u2192 no response (spinal reflexes may persist)</td></tr></tbody></table><div class='hl hl-warn'><span class='hl-icon'>\u26a0\ufe0f</span><div class='hl-body'><div class='hl-title'>Spinal Reflexes \u2260 Brain Death Disproof</div><p>Spinal cord reflexes (Babinski, limb withdrawal, Lazarus sign \u2014 arm flexion on head flexion) can persist in brain death as they are mediated by spinal cord, not brain. Their presence does NOT invalidate brain death diagnosis.</p></div></div><h4>B. Apnoea Test \u2014 Most Important Single Test</h4><ul><li>Pre-oxygenate with 100% O2 for 10 minutes \u2192 PaO2 &gt;200 mmHg</li><li>ABG baseline \u2014 PaCO2 must be 35-45 mmHg before starting</li><li>Disconnect ventilator; deliver passive O2 at 6 L/min via catheter into trachea</li><li>Observe for 8-10 minutes for any respiratory effort</li><li>Check ABG at end \u2014 PaCO2 must rise to <strong>\u226560 mmHg</strong> (or \u226520 mmHg above baseline)</li><li>No respiratory effort at PaCO2 \u226560 mmHg = <strong>positive apnoea test = brain dead</strong></li><li>Abort if: SpO2 &lt;85%, haemodynamic instability, arrhythmia</li></ul><h4>C. Confirmatory Tests (Ancillary \u2014 When Clinical Tests Cannot Be Completed)</h4><table><thead><tr><th>Test</th><th>Brain Death Finding</th><th>Use When</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><strong>EEG (electroencephalogram)</strong></td><td>Electrocerebral silence (isoelectric line &gt;30 min)</td><td>Most available; limitations: artefacts, drugs affect it</td></tr><tr><td><strong>CT Angiography (CTA)</strong></td><td>No cerebral blood flow (CBF) above skull base</td><td>Fast, widely available; preferred in many centres</td></tr><tr><td><strong>4-vessel cerebral angiography</strong></td><td>No intracranial filling beyond skull base</td><td>Gold standard for CBF absence; invasive</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Radionuclide scan (SPECT)</strong></td><td>Absent cerebral perfusion \u2014 'hollow skull' sign</td><td>Highly specific; not always available</td></tr><tr><td><strong>TCD (transcranial Doppler)</strong></td><td>Reverberating/oscillating flow pattern or absent flow</td><td>Bedside; operator-dependent; no bone window = limitation</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Brainstem evoked potentials (BAEP)</strong></td><td>Absent waves III-V bilaterally</td><td>Tests brainstem specifically</td></tr></tbody></table><h4>D. Legal Requirements in India (THO Act)</h4><ul><li>Two sets of tests by <strong>4-member board</strong>: treating doctor, intensivist/anaesthetist, neurologist or neurosurgeon, CMO/nominee of hospital</li><li>Interval between two sets: minimum <strong>6 hours</strong></li><li>Both sets must show all brainstem reflexes absent + apnoea test positive</li><li>All doctors must sign Form 8 (brain death certificate)</li><li>Family consent required for organ donation but not for brain death certification itself</li></ul><div class='pearl'><div class='pearl-head'>\u2b50 Examiner's Pearl</div><p>Three critical points: <strong>(1)</strong> Prerequisites must all be met BEFORE testing \u2014 especially rule out hypothermia and drug intoxication. <strong>(2)</strong> Apnoea test: PaCO2 must reach \u226560 mmHg before declaring positive. <strong>(3)</strong> India: THO Act \u2014 4-doctor board, 2 sets of tests, 6-hour interval, Form 8. Spinal reflexes do NOT disprove brain death \u2014 say this explicitly.</p></div>";
ANSWERS["12"]="<h3>Anaesthesia for Robotic-Assisted Radical Prostatectomy (RARP)</h3><div class='hl hl-info'><span class='hl-icon'></span><div class='hl-body'><div class='hl-title'>Unique Challenges of RARP</div><p>RARP combines THREE major anaesthetic challenges: <strong>(1)</strong> Steep Trendelenburg position (30-45\u00b0). <strong>(2)</strong> Prolonged pneumoperitoneum (CO2 insufflation, 12-15 mmHg). <strong>(3)</strong> No access to patient once robot is docked \u2014 any emergency requires robot undocking first.</p></div></div><h4>A. Preoperative Assessment</h4><ul><li>Typical patient: elderly male (60-75 yr) with prostate cancer \u2014 assess cardiovascular and pulmonary reserve thoroughly</li><li><strong>Cardiorespiratory fitness:</strong> Steep Trendelenburg + pneumoperitoneum \u2192 \u2191 preload, \u2191 afterload, \u2193 FRC, \u2193 compliance. Poor cardiac/pulmonary reserve = major risk</li><li>Screen for: glaucoma (IOP rises markedly in steep Trendelenburg), GORD (aspiration risk \u2014 head-down), obesity (FRC further reduced, access even worse), cervical spine disease (head flexed in positioning)</li><li>Discuss post-op pain plan; counsel on shoulder-tip pain (diaphragmatic irritation from CO2)</li></ul><h4>B. Intraoperative \u2014 Key Considerations</h4><h4>1. Airway and Ventilation</h4><ul><li>Cuffed ETT mandatory \u2014 LMA contraindicated (high airway pressures in steep Trendelenburg + pneumoperitoneum; aspiration risk)</li><li>Secure ETT meticulously \u2014 once robot docked, cannot reach patient's airway</li><li>Lung-protective ventilation: TV 6-8 mL/kg IBW, PEEP 5-8 cmH2O, RR adjusted to maintain EtCO2 35-40 mmHg (may need higher RR as CO2 absorbed)</li><li>Anticipate: peak airway pressure rises significantly (\u2193 chest wall compliance in Trendelenburg + pneumoperitoneum)</li></ul><h4>2. Cardiovascular Effects of Positioning + Pneumoperitoneum</h4><table><thead><tr><th>Effect</th><th>Mechanism</th><th>Clinical Consequence</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>\u2191 Venous return initially</td><td>Legs elevated + pneumoperitoneum squeezes splanchnic veins</td><td>\u2191 Preload \u2192 \u2191 CO initially</td></tr><tr><td>\u2191 Afterload</td><td>CO2 absorption \u2192 \u2191 PVR + SVR</td><td>\u2191 MAP, cardiac work</td></tr><tr><td>Bradycardia</td><td>Vagal stimulation from peritoneal insufflation</td><td>May need atropine</td></tr><tr><td>\u2191 ICP and IOP</td><td>Venous congestion + CO2 \u2192 cerebral vasodilation</td><td>Avoid in glaucoma, raised ICP</td></tr><tr><td>Facial/conjunctival oedema</td><td>Venous pooling in head-down position</td><td>Difficulty extubating? Check airway oedema</td></tr></tbody></table><div class='hl hl-danger'><span class='hl-icon'></span><div class='hl-body'><div class='hl-title'>Inability to Access Patient Once Robot Docked \u2014 Emergency Protocol</div><p>Any emergency (bronchospasm, arrhythmia, tube displacement, cardiac arrest) requires <strong>robot undocking first (takes 2-3 minutes minimum)</strong>. Emergency drugs and defibrillator must be immediately available. Anaesthetist must communicate clearly with surgeon if access needed.</p></div></div><h4>3. Monitoring</h4><ul><li>Invasive arterial line (radial) \u2014 beat-to-beat BP; serial ABG (PaCO2 often underestimated by EtCO2 due to increased dead space)</li><li>Two IV cannulae \u2014 arms tucked in, difficult access once docked. Consider antecubital or external jugular</li><li>Catheter for urine output (surgeon places urinary catheter as part of surgery)</li><li>BIS or entropy for depth of anaesthesia \u2014 TIVA preferred</li></ul><h4>4. Positioning \u2014 Steep Trendelenburg (30-45\u00b0)</h4><ul><li>Shoulder braces \u2014 risk of brachial plexus injury (stretch injury). Pad carefully, use non-slip mattress instead if possible</li><li>Arms tucked at sides with padding \u2014 risk of compartment syndrome in ulnar groove</li><li>Eye protection: tape eyelids, protective goggles \u2014 corneal abrasion and ischaemic optic neuropathy risk</li><li>Check ETT position after final positioning \u2014 head-down may advance ETT into right main bronchus</li></ul><h4>5. Fluid Management</h4><ul><li>Restrictive fluid strategy \u2014 excessive fluids worsen airway oedema in head-down position</li><li>Target: UO 0.5 mL/kg/hr; use vasopressors (phenylephrine/noradrenaline) for hypotension rather than large fluid boluses</li><li>Pneumoperitoneum itself increases BP \u2014 avoid over-treating with additional fluids</li></ul><h4>C. Postoperative</h4><ul><li>Extubation: Check for airway oedema (stridor, hoarse voice). If significant oedema \u2192 delay extubation or perform awake extubation over airway exchange catheter</li><li>Shoulder-tip pain (referred from CO2 irritating diaphragm) \u2014 pre-emptive NSAIDs + paracetamol. Usually self-limiting 24-48 hours</li><li>PONV prophylaxis: Ondansetron + dexamethasone (dual therapy) \u2014 PONV very common with steep Trendelenburg</li><li>DVT prophylaxis: Heparin, TED stockings \u2014 prolonged immobility + pelvic dissection = high VTE risk</li><li>Postoperative urinary catheter remains for 7-10 days \u2014 adequate analgesia essential</li></ul><div class='pearl'><div class='pearl-head'>\u2b50 Examiner's Pearl</div><p>Three points that show you understand RARP-specific risks: <strong>(1)</strong> Robot docking = no patient access \u2014 every emergency drug/equipment must be ready BEFORE docking. <strong>(2)</strong> ETT must be checked AGAIN after final steep Trendelenburg positioning \u2014 can advance into right main bronchus. <strong>(3)</strong> Restrictive fluids + vasopressors \u2014 not fluids \u2014 for haemodynamic management (excessive fluids worsen airway oedema).</p></div>";
ANSWERS["13"]="<h3>Difficult Airway &#x2014; Assessment and Management [4+6]</h3>\n\n<div class='hl hl-info'><span class='hl-icon'>&#x1F4CB;</span><div class='hl-body'><div class='hl-title'>Definition</div>\n<p>A <strong>difficult airway</strong> exists when a conventionally trained anaesthesiologist experiences difficulty with mask ventilation, laryngoscopy, intubation, or extubation. Incidence: difficult laryngoscopy 1-18%, failed intubation 1:1000-2000, cannot intubate cannot oxygenate (CICO) 1:10,000.</p></div></div>\n\n<h3>A. Airway Assessment Modalities [4 marks]</h3>\n\n<h4>1. History</h4>\n<ul>\n<li>Previous difficult intubation or airway problems</li>\n<li>Snoring, OSA, stridor</li>\n<li>Neck surgery, radiation, trauma</li>\n<li>Rheumatoid arthritis (cricoarytenoid involvement), ankylosing spondylitis</li>\n<li>Acromegaly, obesity, pregnancy</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h4>2. Bedside Predictive Tests</h4>\n<table><thead><tr><th>Test</th><th>Normal</th><th>Predicts Difficult If</th><th>Sensitivity</th></tr></thead>\n<tbody>\n<tr><td><strong>Mallampati Class</strong></td><td>Class I/II</td><td>Class III/IV</td><td>Moderate</td></tr>\n<tr><td><strong>Mouth Opening (IIG)</strong></td><td>&gt;4 cm (3 finger breadths)</td><td>&lt;3 cm</td><td>High</td></tr>\n<tr><td><strong>Thyromental Distance (TMD)</strong></td><td>&gt;6.5 cm</td><td>&lt;6 cm</td><td>Moderate</td></tr>\n<tr><td><strong>Sternomental Distance</strong></td><td>&gt;12.5 cm</td><td>&lt;12 cm</td><td>Moderate</td></tr>\n<tr><td><strong>Upper Lip Bite Test (ULBT)</strong></td><td>Class I</td><td>Class III</td><td>High</td></tr>\n<tr><td><strong>Neck Extension</strong></td><td>&gt;35 degrees</td><td>&lt;80% normal</td><td>Moderate</td></tr>\n<tr><td><strong>Head Extension (Prayer sign)</strong></td><td>Palms flat</td><td>Cannot approximate</td><td>Diabetic stiff joint</td></tr>\n<tr><td><strong>Wilson Score</strong></td><td>0</td><td>&gt;2</td><td>Composite score</td></tr>\n</tbody></table>\n\n<div class='hl hl-teal'><span class='hl-icon'>&#x1F4A1;</span><div class='hl-body'><div class='hl-title'>Mallampati Classification</div>\n<p><strong>Class I:</strong> Soft palate, uvula, fauces, pillars visible. <strong>Class II:</strong> Soft palate, uvula, fauces visible. <strong>Class III:</strong> Soft palate, base of uvula visible. <strong>Class IV:</strong> Only hard palate visible. Classes III and IV predict difficult laryngoscopy. Best assessed with patient sitting, mouth maximally open, tongue protruded, NO phonation.</p></div></div>\n\n<h4>3. Radiological Assessment</h4>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>X-ray neck/chest:</strong> Tracheal deviation, subglottic narrowing, mediastinal mass</li>\n<li><strong>CT scan:</strong> Exact level and degree of airway narrowing</li>\n<li><strong>MRI:</strong> Soft tissue masses, retropharyngeal abscess</li>\n<li><strong>Nasendoscopy:</strong> Awake assessment of supraglottic structures</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h4>4. Ultrasound Assessment of Airway</h4>\n<ul>\n<li>Identify cricothyroid membrane (CTM) location pre-operatively</li>\n<li>Predict difficult laryngoscopy: pre-epiglottic space &gt;2.5cm</li>\n<li>Confirm ETT position post-intubation</li>\n<li>Assess tongue base thickness in obese patients</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h4>LEMON Score (composite)</h4>\n<div class='mech-box'><span class='ht'>L</span> - Look externally (facial trauma, obesity, beard, buck teeth)\n<span class='ht'>E</span> - Evaluate 3-3-2 rule (mouth 3F, hyoid-chin 3F, thyroid-hyoid 2F)\n<span class='ht'>M</span> - Mallampati score (III/IV = difficult)\n<span class='ht'>O</span> - Obstruction (epiglottitis, abscess, tumour)\n<span class='ht'>N</span> - Neck mobility (limited extension = difficult)</div>\n\n<h3>B. Management of Difficult Airway [6 marks]</h3>\n\n<h4>DAS Guidelines 2015 / ASA Guidelines 2022</h4>\n\n<div class='hl hl-danger'><span class='hl-icon'>&#x1F6A8;</span><div class='hl-body'><div class='hl-title'>Core Principle</div>\n<p>The fundamental decision: <strong>Awake intubation vs Intubation after induction?</strong> If difficult airway is anticipated AND patient can cooperate AND is not an emergency = AWAKE intubation is safest. After induction, if cannot intubate = WAKE UP the patient (if possible). CICO = surgical airway immediately.</p></div></div>\n\n<h4>Plan A: Direct/Video Laryngoscopy</h4>\n<ul>\n<li>Optimise patient position: Ramped position (obese), sniffing position</li>\n<li>BURP manoeuvre (Backward Upward Rightward Pressure on thyroid)</li>\n<li>Maximum 3 attempts by most experienced operator</li>\n<li>Video laryngoscope (C-MAC, McGrath, Glidescope) as primary or backup</li>\n<li>Bougie use: increases first-pass success by 10-15%</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h4>Plan B: Supraglottic Airway (SGA)</h4>\n<ul>\n<li>i-gel or ProSeal LMA as rescue device</li>\n<li>Can use as conduit for intubation (Aintree catheter technique)</li>\n<li>2nd generation SGAs preferred (gastric channel for decompression)</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h4>Plan C: Face Mask Ventilation</h4>\n<ul>\n<li>Two-person technique with oral/nasal airway</li>\n<li>If cannot ventilate with SGA or mask = CICO situation</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h4>Plan D: Front of Neck Access (FONA) = CICO</h4>\n<div class='hl hl-danger'><span class='hl-icon'>&#x1F6A8;</span><div class='hl-body'><div class='hl-title'>CICO = Life-threatening Emergency</div>\n<p><strong>Cannot Intubate Cannot Oxygenate = Call for help + scalpel-bougie-tube technique IMMEDIATELY.</strong> Scalpel cricothyroidotomy: (1) Identify CTM. (2) Horizontal stab incision through CTM. (3) Caudal traction with hook/finger. (4) Bougie insertion. (5) Railroads 6.0 cuffed ETT. (6) Inflate, ventilate, confirm. Time to oxygenation must be &lt;2 minutes. Needle cricothyroidotomy buys time but is a bridge only.</p></div></div>\n\n<h4>Awake Intubation Technique</h4>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Indications:</strong> Anticipated difficult airway, full stomach with difficult airway, unstable cervical spine, severe OSA</li>\n<li><strong>Topicalisation:</strong> Lidocaine 4% spray to oropharynx, transtracheal injection 2-4mL 4% lidocaine, superior laryngeal nerve block</li>\n<li><strong>Sedation:</strong> Dexmedetomidine 0.7mcg/kg over 10 min OR remifentanil TCI OR midazolam + fentanyl</li>\n<li><strong>Technique:</strong> Flexible bronchoscope (FOB) most reliable. Video laryngoscope awake. Intubating LMA awake</li>\n<li><strong>Confirm:</strong> EtCO2 + bilateral air entry before inducing GA</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h4>Difficult Extubation</h4>\n<ul>\n<li>High risk: prolonged surgery, airway oedema, neck surgery, obesity</li>\n<li>Cuff leak test before extubation</li>\n<li>Airway exchange catheter (AEC) technique for high-risk extubation</li>\n<li>Nebulised adrenaline for post-extubation stridor</li>\n<li>Consider ICU admission and delayed extubation</li>\n</ul>\n\n<div class='drug-grid'>\n<div class='drug-card dc-teal'><div class='drug-name'>Lidocaine 4%</div><div class='drug-dose'>Max 9mg/kg for topicalisation</div><div class='drug-note'>Spray-as-you-go through bronchoscope. Do NOT exceed max dose</div></div>\n<div class='drug-card dc-indigo'><div class='drug-name'>Dexmedetomidine</div><div class='drug-dose'>0.7 mcg/kg over 10 min then 0.4-0.7 mcg/kg/hr</div><div class='drug-note'>Ideal for awake FOB - sedation with maintained airway tone and spontaneous breathing</div></div>\n<div class='drug-card dc-amber'><div class='drug-name'>Nebulised Adrenaline</div><div class='drug-dose'>0.5mL 1:1000 in 2.5mL NS</div><div class='drug-note'>Post-extubation stridor. Repeat every 20 min x3 if needed</div></div>\n<div class='drug-card dc-rose'><div class='drug-name'>Succinylcholine</div><div class='drug-dose'>1.5-2 mg/kg IV</div><div class='drug-note'>For CICO or rapid sequence - provides 8-10 min muscle relaxation then spontaneous breathing returns</div></div>\n</div>\n\n<div class='viva-box'><div class='viva-head'>Viva Corner</div>\n<div class='viva-item'><div class='viva-q'>What is the 3-3-2 rule in airway assessment?</div><div class='viva-a'>Three finger breadths for mouth opening (IIG), three finger breadths from chin to hyoid bone (adequate mandibular space for tongue displacement), two finger breadths from thyroid notch to hyoid bone (adequate laryngeal position). If any measurement is less than specified, difficult laryngoscopy is predicted. Part of the LEMON score.</div></div>\n<div class='viva-item'><div class='viva-q'>What is the scalpel-bougie-tube technique for cricothyroidotomy?</div><div class='viva-a'>DAS recommended technique for CICO: (1) Extend neck, identify CTM by palpation or ultrasound. (2) Stabilise larynx with non-dominant hand. (3) Horizontal stab incision through skin AND CTM with scalpel. (4) Caudal traction on trachea with hook or finger in wound. (5) Insert bougie through incision caudally. (6) Railroad 6.0mm cuffed ETT over bougie. (7) Inflate cuff, ventilate, confirm with EtCO2. Target: &lt;2 minutes to oxygenation.</div></div>\n<div class='viva-item'><div class='viva-q'>When is awake intubation mandatory?</div><div class='viva-a'>Awake intubation is mandatory when: (1) Difficult airway is anticipated AND patient cannot tolerate even brief apnoea (severe respiratory compromise). (2) Full stomach PLUS anticipated difficult airway (RSI may fail). (3) Unstable cervical spine needing neurological assessment mid-procedure. (4) Supraglottic obstruction where SGA would fail. (5) Patient refuses general anaesthesia. After successful awake intubation, GA can be safely induced.</div></div>\n<div class='viva-item'><div class='viva-q'>What is the Cormack-Lehane grading?</div><div class='viva-a'>Grading of laryngoscopic view: Grade 1 = full glottis visible. Grade 2a = partial glottis visible. Grade 2b = only posterior commissure visible. Grade 3 = only epiglottis visible. Grade 4 = neither epiglottis nor glottis visible. Grades 3 and 4 = difficult laryngoscopy. BURP manoeuvre converts Grade 3 to Grade 2 in 90% of cases.</div></div>\n</div>\n\n<div class='pearl'><div class='pearl-head'>Examiner's Pearl</div>\n<p><strong>(1)</strong> No single test predicts difficult airway reliably - use combination (LEMON). <strong>(2)</strong> Anticipated = awake intubation. Unanticipated = DAS algorithm Plans A-B-C-D. <strong>(3)</strong> CICO = scalpel-bougie-tube, do NOT waste time with needle. <strong>(4)</strong> Maximum 3 laryngoscopy attempts then move to next plan. <strong>(5)</strong> Ultrasound to identify CTM pre-op in all obese/difficult neck patients.</p>\n\n<p style='margin-top:10px'><strong>References:</strong> Frerk C et al. DAS Guidelines 2015 (Anaesthesia 2015;70:1116-1131). Apfelbaum JL et al. ASA Difficult Airway Guidelines 2022 (Anesthesiology 2022;136:31-81). Morgan &amp; Mikhail Clinical Anesthesiology 6th Ed Chapter 19. Miller's Anaesthesia 9th Ed Chapter 44.</p></div>";
ANSWERS["14"]="<h3>Biomedical Waste Management &amp; COVID-19 Anaesthesia Waste [5+5]</h3>\n\n<div class='hl hl-info'><span class='hl-icon'>&#x1F4CB;</span><div class='hl-body'><div class='hl-title'>Legal Framework</div>\n<p>Governed by <strong>Biomedical Waste Management Rules 2016</strong> (amended 2019) under the Environment Protection Act 1986. Enforced by Central Pollution Control Board (CPCB) and State PCBs. All healthcare facilities generating biomedical waste must be registered and follow these rules. Non-compliance = criminal liability.</p></div></div>\n\n<h3>A. Biomedical Waste Management Guidelines [5 marks]</h3>\n\n<h4>Classification and Colour-Coded Segregation</h4>\n<table><thead><tr><th>Category</th><th>Bag/Container Colour</th><th>Waste Type</th><th>Treatment</th></tr></thead>\n<tbody>\n<tr><td><strong>Yellow</strong></td><td>Yellow bag</td><td>Human anatomical waste, soiled dressings, expired medicines, chemical waste, discarded medicines</td><td>Incineration or deep burial</td></tr>\n<tr><td><strong>Red</strong></td><td>Red bag</td><td>Contaminated waste - recyclable (IV tubing, syringes without needles, catheters, gloves)</td><td>Autoclaving then shredding</td></tr>\n<tr><td><strong>White (Translucent)</strong></td><td>Puncture-proof container</td><td>Sharps: needles, syringes with needles, scalpel blades, lancets</td><td>Autoclaving + shredding OR needle destroyers</td></tr>\n<tr><td><strong>Blue</strong></td><td>Blue bag/container</td><td>Glassware: broken glass, ampoules, glass vials</td><td>Disinfection then recycling</td></tr>\n</tbody></table>\n\n<h4>Key Principles of BMW Management</h4>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Segregation at source:</strong> Most critical step \u2014 wrong bag = entire batch becomes hazardous</li>\n<li><strong>No mixing:</strong> General waste NEVER mixed with biomedical waste</li>\n<li><strong>Storage:</strong> Maximum 48 hours in healthcare facility</li>\n<li><strong>Transport:</strong> Labelled, covered vehicles to CBWTF (Common Biomedical Waste Treatment Facility)</li>\n<li><strong>Labelling:</strong> Biohazard symbol on all bags, facility name, date, category</li>\n<li><strong>Records:</strong> Log book maintained, annual report to SPCB</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h4>Treatment Methods</h4>\n<div class='mech-box'><span class='ht'>INCINERATION</span> - Yellow bags. Destroys all pathogens. Temperature &gt;850 degrees C.\nUsed for: anatomical parts, soiled dressings, chemical waste.\n\n<span class='ht'>AUTOCLAVING</span> - Red bags. Steam sterilisation at 134 degrees C, 3 bar, 18 min.\nUsed for: contaminated recyclables, sharps after shredding.\n\n<span class='ht'>CHEMICAL DISINFECTION</span> - 1% hypochlorite for liquid waste.\nBleach 10,000 ppm for high-risk liquid waste (blood, body fluids).\n\n<span class='ht'>DEEP BURIAL</span> - Only in remote areas without CBWTF.\nFor anatomical waste only, &gt;2m deep, lime-covered.</div>\n\n<h4>Sharps Management</h4>\n<div class='hl hl-danger'><span class='hl-icon'>&#x1F6A8;</span><div class='hl-body'><div class='hl-title'>Needlestick Injury Prevention</div>\n<p><strong>Never recap needles</strong> - single-handed scoop technique if unavoidable. Dispose immediately into sharps container at point of care. Container should be: puncture-proof, leak-proof, tamper-evident, filled only to 3/4 capacity then sealed. Needle destroyers/cutters available at point of use. Post-exposure prophylaxis (PEP) within 72 hours for HIV exposure.</p></div></div>\n\n<h3>B. Waste from Anaesthesia Management of COVID-19 [5 marks]</h3>\n\n<h4>Why COVID-19 Waste is Special</h4>\n<ul>\n<li>SARS-CoV-2 survives on plastic surfaces 72 hours, cardboard 24 hours</li>\n<li>Aerosol-generating procedures (AGPs) in anaesthesia = highest risk</li>\n<li>AGPs: intubation, extubation, mask ventilation, bronchoscopy, suctioning, CPR</li>\n<li>All waste from COVID-19 patients treated as Category 1 (highest risk)</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h4>Classification of COVID-19 Anaesthesia Waste</h4>\n<table><thead><tr><th>Waste Type</th><th>Examples in OT</th><th>Disposal</th></tr></thead>\n<tbody>\n<tr><td><strong>PPE waste</strong></td><td>N95 masks, gowns, gloves, face shields, coveralls</td><td>Yellow bag (incineration)</td></tr>\n<tr><td><strong>Airway equipment</strong></td><td>ETT, LMA, breathing circuits, HME filters, suction catheters</td><td>Yellow bag (incineration) - single use only</td></tr>\n<tr><td><strong>Sharps</strong></td><td>Needles, syringes, arterial line cannulae, epidural needles</td><td>White puncture-proof container</td></tr>\n<tr><td><strong>Liquid waste</strong></td><td>Blood, secretions, IV fluids</td><td>1% hypochlorite disinfection then drain</td></tr>\n<tr><td><strong>Drug vials/ampoules</strong></td><td>Used glass ampoules, empty vials</td><td>Blue container (glass) or yellow (contaminated)</td></tr>\n</tbody></table>\n\n<h4>OT Protocols for COVID-19 Anaesthesia Waste</h4>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Dedicated OT:</strong> Negative pressure room preferred. Laminar flow OFF during AGPs</li>\n<li><strong>Double bagging:</strong> Inner yellow bag + outer yellow bag, sealed inside OT</li>\n<li><strong>Label:</strong> \"COVID-19 Waste - Biohazard\" clearly on outer bag</li>\n<li><strong>Disinfect outer bag:</strong> Spray with 1% hypochlorite before transport</li>\n<li><strong>Dedicated transport route:</strong> Not through main corridors</li>\n<li><strong>Terminal cleaning:</strong> Fumigation with hydrogen peroxide vaporiser after COVID case</li>\n<li><strong>Anesthesia machine:</strong> HME filter on both inspiratory and expiratory limbs. Machine wipe down with 70% alcohol + 1% hypochlorite</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h4>PPE Sequence for COVID-19 Anaesthesia</h4>\n<div class='mech-box'><span class='ht'>DONNING (Putting On):</span>\n1. Hand hygiene\n2. Gown\n3. N95 mask (fit check)\n4. Face shield/goggles\n5. Gloves (double glove for intubation)\n\n<span class='ht'>DOFFING (Removing) - Most critical step:</span>\n1. Remove outer gloves (outer surface is most contaminated)\n2. Remove gown (roll inward, away from body)\n3. Hand hygiene\n4. Remove face shield (from behind)\n5. Remove N95 (from behind, DO NOT touch front)\n6. Hand hygiene\n7. Remove inner gloves\n8. Hand hygiene</div>\n\n<h4>Colour-Coded Waste Summary Card</h4>\n<div class='drug-grid'>\n<div class='drug-card dc-amber'><div class='drug-name'>Yellow Bag</div><div class='drug-dose'>INCINERATE</div><div class='drug-note'>Anatomical parts, PPE, soiled dressings, COVID-19 all waste, expired medicines</div></div>\n<div class='drug-card dc-rose'><div class='drug-name'>Red Bag</div><div class='drug-dose'>AUTOCLAVE then SHRED</div><div class='drug-note'>Contaminated recyclables - IV tubing, gloves, catheters (non-COVID)</div></div>\n<div class='drug-card dc-indigo'><div class='drug-name'>White Container</div><div class='drug-dose'>AUTOCLAVE + SHRED</div><div class='drug-note'>All sharps - needles, blades, lancets. Fill only 3/4 full</div></div>\n<div class='drug-card dc-teal'><div class='drug-name'>Blue Container</div><div class='drug-dose'>DISINFECT + RECYCLE</div><div class='drug-note'>Broken glass, ampoules, glass vials - non-contaminated</div></div>\n</div>\n\n<div class='viva-box'><div class='viva-head'>Viva Corner</div>\n<div class='viva-item'><div class='viva-q'>What colour bag do you use for a used ETT from a COVID-19 patient?</div><div class='viva-a'>Yellow bag - for incineration. All waste from COVID-19 patients goes into yellow bags regardless of the type of waste. The ETT is an aerosol-contaminated single-use device and cannot be recycled. It is double-bagged inside the OT, labelled COVID-19 Biohazard, outer bag sprayed with 1% hypochlorite, and transported via dedicated route to incineration.</div></div>\n<div class='viva-item'><div class='viva-q'>What is CBWTF?</div><div class='viva-a'>Common Biomedical Waste Treatment Facility - a centralised facility licensed by the State Pollution Control Board that collects, treats, and disposes biomedical waste from multiple healthcare facilities. Healthcare facilities cannot treat waste on their own premises unless they have an authorised on-site facility. CBWTF must collect waste within 48 hours of generation.</div></div>\n<div class='viva-item'><div class='viva-q'>What are aerosol-generating procedures in anaesthesia?</div><div class='viva-a'>Aerosol-generating procedures (AGPs) in anaesthesia: endotracheal intubation, extubation, bag-mask ventilation, insertion of supraglottic airways, bronchoscopy, tracheostomy, suctioning, high-flow nasal oxygen (HFNO), non-invasive ventilation (NIV), and CPR. During these procedures, N95 mask (not just surgical mask) + face shield + gown + gloves are mandatory for COVID-19 patients. HME filters must be placed on both Y-piece and expiratory port of ventilator circuit.</div></div>\n<div class='viva-item'><div class='viva-q'>Why is doffing more dangerous than donning?</div><div class='viva-a'>During doffing, the outer surfaces of PPE are contaminated with pathogens. Self-contamination occurs if the sequence is wrong or if contaminated outer surfaces touch the face/mucous membranes. The face shield and N95 must be removed last (from behind) - never touch the front. Hand hygiene between each step is mandatory. Studies show most healthcare worker COVID-19 infections occurred during doffing, not during patient care.</div></div>\n</div>\n\n<div class='pearl'><div class='pearl-head'>Examiner's Pearl</div>\n<p><strong>(1)</strong> Four colour bags: Yellow (incinerate), Red (autoclave), White (sharps), Blue (glass). <strong>(2)</strong> ALL COVID-19 waste = Yellow bag regardless of type. <strong>(3)</strong> Double bag inside OT, label, spray hypochlorite on outer bag. <strong>(4)</strong> HME filter on both inspiratory AND expiratory limbs of anaesthesia circuit for COVID-19. <strong>(5)</strong> Doffing sequence is more critical than donning - hand hygiene between each step.</p>\n\n<p style='margin-top:10px'><strong>References:</strong> Biomedical Waste Management Rules 2016 (amended 2019), MoEF&amp;CC, Govt of India. CPCB Guidelines for Handling of BMW during COVID-19 Pandemic 2020. WHO Infection Prevention and Control Guidance for COVID-19 2021. Cook TM et al. Anaesthesia priorities for COVID-19 (Anaesthesia 2020;75:785-799). Miller's Anaesthesia 9th Ed Chapter 84.</p></div>";
ANSWERS["15"]="<h3>Artificial Intelligence and Machine Learning in Anaesthesia [5]</h3>\n\n<div class='hl hl-info'><span class='hl-icon'>&#x1F4CB;</span><div class='hl-body'><div class='hl-title'>Definition</div>\n<p><strong>Artificial Intelligence (AI)</strong> refers to computer systems that perform tasks requiring human intelligence. <strong>Machine Learning (ML)</strong> is a subset of AI where systems learn from data without being explicitly programmed. <strong>Deep Learning</strong> uses neural networks with multiple layers. In anaesthesia, AI analyses vast datasets to predict, diagnose, and automate clinical decisions.</p></div></div>\n\n<h4>Types of AI/ML Relevant to Anaesthesia</h4>\n<table><thead><tr><th>Type</th><th>Method</th><th>Anaesthesia Application</th></tr></thead>\n<tbody>\n<tr><td><strong>Supervised Learning</strong></td><td>Trained on labelled data</td><td>Predicting difficult airway, PONV risk, postop complications</td></tr>\n<tr><td><strong>Unsupervised Learning</strong></td><td>Finds patterns in unlabelled data</td><td>Patient clustering, phenotyping sepsis subtypes</td></tr>\n<tr><td><strong>Reinforcement Learning</strong></td><td>Learns by trial and reward</td><td>Closed-loop drug delivery, ventilator weaning</td></tr>\n<tr><td><strong>Natural Language Processing</strong></td><td>Processes text/speech</td><td>Extracting data from anaesthesia records, voice documentation</td></tr>\n<tr><td><strong>Computer Vision</strong></td><td>Analyses images/video</td><td>Airway assessment, ultrasound interpretation, ECG analysis</td></tr>\n</tbody></table>\n\n<h4>Current and Emerging Applications</h4>\n\n<h4>1. Preoperative Risk Assessment</h4>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Difficult airway prediction:</strong> AI analyses facial images + patient data to predict Mallampati class and Cormack-Lehane grade with higher accuracy than clinical scoring alone</li>\n<li><strong>PONV prediction:</strong> ML models using Apfel score + additional variables predict PONV risk and guide prophylaxis</li>\n<li><strong>Perioperative mortality:</strong> AI-based risk scores (e.g., MySurgeryRisk) outperform ASA grading for 30-day mortality prediction</li>\n<li><strong>Cardiac risk:</strong> Deep learning ECG analysis detects LV dysfunction, arrhythmias, predicting cardiac events</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h4>2. Intraoperative Monitoring and Automation</h4>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Depth of anaesthesia:</strong> BIS and Entropy use processed EEG (AI-derived). Next-gen systems predict awareness 5 min before it occurs</li>\n<li><strong>Haemodynamic prediction:</strong> Hypotension Prediction Index (HPI) - predicts hypotension 15 min before onset using arterial waveform analysis. FDA-approved (Edwards EV1000)</li>\n<li><strong>Closed-loop propofol delivery:</strong> AI maintains BIS target by automatically adjusting propofol infusion rate. Reduces drug use, improves stability</li>\n<li><strong>Closed-loop neuromuscular blockade:</strong> Automatic rocuronium dosing based on TOF monitoring</li>\n<li><strong>Alarm fatigue reduction:</strong> AI filters false alarms, identifies clinically significant alerts</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h4>3. Airway Management</h4>\n<ul>\n<li>Video laryngoscope AI: real-time glottic view grading, guides blade placement</li>\n<li>Ultrasound AI: automatic identification of cricothyroid membrane, epidural space, nerve structures</li>\n<li>AI-assisted bronchoscopy: identifies airway anatomy, guides navigation</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h4>4. Drug Dosing and Pharmacology</h4>\n<ul>\n<li>Target-controlled infusion (TCI) models (Marsh, Schnider) are AI-derived pharmacokinetic models</li>\n<li>Personalised drug dosing based on patient genetics, body composition (ML-based)</li>\n<li>Drug interaction prediction from EHR data</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h4>5. Critical Care and ICU</h4>\n<ul>\n<li>Sepsis early warning systems: predict sepsis 6 hours before clinical diagnosis</li>\n<li>Ventilator optimisation: AI adjusts PEEP, tidal volume based on compliance trends</li>\n<li>ICU mortality prediction: APACHE-IV, SOFA enhanced with ML</li>\n<li>Weaning prediction: ML-based spontaneous breathing trial outcome prediction</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h4>6. Quality Improvement and Research</h4>\n<ul>\n<li>Automated anaesthesia record analysis for quality metrics</li>\n<li>Pattern recognition in adverse event databases</li>\n<li>Clinical trial design optimisation</li>\n</ul>\n\n<div class='hl hl-warn'><span class='hl-icon'>&#x26A0;&#xFE0F;</span><div class='hl-body'><div class='hl-title'>Limitations and Concerns</div>\n<p><strong>Black box problem:</strong> Clinicians cannot understand how AI reached a decision. <strong>Bias:</strong> AI trained on non-diverse datasets may perform poorly in different populations. <strong>Data quality:</strong> Garbage in = garbage out. <strong>Liability:</strong> Who is responsible when AI makes an error? <strong>Over-reliance:</strong> Risk of deskilling of anaesthesiologists. <strong>Cost:</strong> High implementation cost. <strong>Regulatory:</strong> FDA/CE approval process for medical AI is evolving.</p></div></div>\n\n<div class='mech-box'><span class='ht'>AI IN ANAESTHESIA - KEY MILESTONES:</span>\n2010 - BIS (processed EEG) becomes standard depth monitoring\n2015 - TCI models refined using ML pharmacokinetics\n2018 - Hypotension Prediction Index (HPI) FDA approved\n2019 - Closed-loop propofol systems validated in RCTs\n2020 - AI sepsis prediction tools deployed in ICUs\n2022 - AI airway assessment from facial images validated\n2023 - ChatGPT/LLMs explored for anaesthesia documentation\n2024 - Closed-loop NMB monitoring systems commercialised</div>\n\n<div class='viva-box'><div class='viva-head'>Viva Corner</div>\n<div class='viva-item'><div class='viva-q'>What is the Hypotension Prediction Index (HPI)?</div><div class='viva-a'>HPI is an FDA-approved AI algorithm (Edwards Lifesciences) that analyses arterial pressure waveform data in real-time to predict hypotension (MAP &lt;65 mmHg) up to 15 minutes before it occurs. It outputs a score from 0-100; score &gt;85 = imminent hypotension with 88% sensitivity and 87% specificity. Studies show HPI-guided management reduces intraoperative hypotension duration by 50%, potentially improving outcomes. It is available on the EV1000/HemoSphere platform.</div></div>\n<div class='viva-item'><div class='viva-q'>What is closed-loop anaesthesia delivery?</div><div class='viva-a'>Closed-loop (automated feedback) drug delivery uses a sensor (BIS for propofol, TOF for NMB, SpO2 for oxygen) as the input, a controller (AI/PID algorithm) as the processor, and an infusion pump as the output. The system continuously adjusts drug delivery to maintain a target value without manual intervention. Benefits: more precise drug titration, reduced variability, potentially less drug use. Validated systems: closed-loop propofol (BIS target 40-60), closed-loop rocuronium (TOF target 1-2 twitches). Not yet standard of care but promising.</div></div>\n<div class='viva-item'><div class='viva-q'>What is the black box problem in AI?</div><div class='viva-a'>Deep learning neural networks make decisions through millions of weighted connections that cannot be interpreted by humans - hence \"black box.\" A clinician cannot understand WHY the AI made a specific prediction. This is problematic in medicine because: (1) Cannot identify when AI will fail. (2) Cannot explain decision to patient/family. (3) Medicolegal accountability unclear. (4) Cannot catch systematic biases. Explainable AI (XAI) is an active research area aiming to make AI decisions interpretable to clinicians.</div></div>\n</div>\n\n<div class='pearl'><div class='pearl-head'>Examiner's Pearl</div>\n<p><strong>(1)</strong> HPI predicts hypotension 15 min before - most clinically important current application. <strong>(2)</strong> TCI models (Marsh/Schnider) are already AI/ML in routine practice. <strong>(3)</strong> BIS uses processed EEG - early AI in anaesthesia. <strong>(4)</strong> Closed-loop systems: sensor + controller + pump = automated anaesthesia. <strong>(5)</strong> Limitations: black box, bias, liability, deskilling.</p>\n<p style='margin-top:10px'><strong>References:</strong> Hashimoto DA et al. Artificial Intelligence in Anesthesiology (Anesthesiology 2020;132:379-394). Wijnberge M et al. HPI trial (JAMA 2020;323:1052-1060). Connor CW. Artificial Intelligence and Machine Learning in Anaesthesiology (Anesthesiology 2019;131:1346-1359). Miller's Anaesthesia 9th Ed Chapter 4. Pandit JJ. AI in Anaesthesia (BJA 2021;126:e118-e120).</p></div>";
ANSWERS["16"]="<h3>Carbon Footprint of Anaesthesia [5]</h3>\n\n<div class='hl hl-info'><span class='hl-icon'>&#x1F4CB;</span><div class='hl-body'><div class='hl-title'>Why Anaesthesia Matters for Climate</div>\n<p>Healthcare contributes <strong>4-5% of global greenhouse gas emissions</strong> - if it were a country, it would be the 5th largest emitter. Anaesthesia gases are a disproportionately large contributor. The NHS (UK) estimated that anaesthetic gases contribute <strong>5% of NHS total carbon footprint</strong> despite being used in a small fraction of hospital encounters. India performs ~50 million surgeries annually - the environmental impact is enormous.</p></div></div>\n\n<h4>Sources of Carbon Footprint in Anaesthesia</h4>\n\n<h4>1. Volatile Anaesthetic Agents (BIGGEST contributor)</h4>\n<table><thead><tr><th>Agent</th><th>GWP (100yr)</th><th>Atmospheric Lifetime</th><th>Equivalent CO2 per MAC-hour</th></tr></thead>\n<tbody>\n<tr><td><strong>Desflurane</strong></td><td>2540</td><td>14 years</td><td>~630g CO2 equivalent</td></tr>\n<tr><td><strong>Isoflurane</strong></td><td>510</td><td>3.2 years</td><td>~210g CO2 equivalent</td></tr>\n<tr><td><strong>Sevoflurane</strong></td><td>130</td><td>1.1 years</td><td>~55g CO2 equivalent</td></tr>\n<tr><td><strong>Nitrous Oxide</strong></td><td>265</td><td>116 years</td><td>Significant (also ozone depleting)</td></tr>\n<tr><td><strong>Propofol (TIVA)</strong></td><td>~3.5 (plastic waste)</td><td>Hours (metabolised)</td><td>~2g CO2 equivalent</td></tr>\n</tbody></table>\n\n<div class='hl hl-danger'><span class='hl-icon'>&#x1F6A8;</span><div class='hl-body'><div class='hl-title'>Desflurane - The Worst Offender</div>\n<p>1 MAC-hour of Desflurane = driving a car <strong>40km</strong>. 1 MAC-hour of Sevoflurane = driving a car <strong>3km</strong>. Desflurane has 20x the global warming potential of Sevoflurane per MAC-hour. Many countries (UK, USA, Sweden, Denmark) have <strong>banned or severely restricted Desflurane</strong> use. Indian anaesthesiologists should be aware of this trend. The boiling point of Desflurane (-22.8 degrees C) means it requires a heated pressurised vaporiser (Tec-6) that consumes additional energy.</p></div></div>\n\n<h4>2. Nitrous Oxide</h4>\n<ul>\n<li>GWP of 265 (265x more potent than CO2 over 100 years)</li>\n<li>Atmospheric lifetime of 116 years - persists very long</li>\n<li>Also destroys stratospheric ozone (O3 layer)</li>\n<li>Pipeline N2O systems have significant leakage losses (up to 50% wasted)</li>\n<li>N2O filling/manufacturing is energy intensive</li>\n<li>Many European centres have eliminated N2O from routine practice</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h4>3. Medical Gases and Infrastructure</h4>\n<ul>\n<li>Oxygen production (PSA, cryogenic): energy intensive</li>\n<li>Compressed gas cylinder manufacture and transport: carbon intensive</li>\n<li>Pipeline gas leakage from aging infrastructure</li>\n<li>Air conditioning of OT: HFCs used are potent GHGs</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h4>4. Single-Use Equipment</h4>\n<ul>\n<li>Massive plastic waste from single-use items (gloves, drapes, syringes, circuits)</li>\n<li>Manufacturing, packaging, transport, and disposal all have carbon costs</li>\n<li>An average surgical case generates 20-30kg of waste</li>\n<li>Incineration of medical waste releases CO2 and dioxins</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h4>Strategies to Reduce Carbon Footprint</h4>\n\n<h4>1. Choose Low-GWP Anaesthetic Agents</h4>\n<div class='mech-box'><span class='ht'>HIERARCHY (Best to Worst for Environment):</span>\n1. TIVA with Propofol + Remifentanil (lowest footprint)\n2. Sevoflurane (GWP 130) - acceptable\n3. Isoflurane (GWP 510) - moderate\n4. Nitrous Oxide (GWP 265, ozone depleting) - minimise\n5. Desflurane (GWP 2540) - AVOID or phase out</div>\n\n<h4>2. Low-Flow Anaesthesia</h4>\n<ul>\n<li>Fresh gas flow 0.5-1 L/min vs conventional 2-4 L/min</li>\n<li>Reduces volatile agent consumption by 50-75%</li>\n<li>Reduces N2O consumption</li>\n<li>Cost saving AND environmentally friendly</li>\n<li>Monitor with agent analyser to prevent accumulation</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h4>3. Recapture/Recycling of Volatile Agents</h4>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>CLIC (Closed Loop Inhaled anaesthetic Conservation):</strong> Systems that capture exhaled volatile agents from scavenging systems and recycle them</li>\n<li>ZeoSys (Germany): captures Sevoflurane from scavenging, recycles up to 90%</li>\n<li>Not yet widely available in India but coming</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h4>4. Reduce Single-Use Waste</h4>\n<ul>\n<li>Reusable laryngoscope blades (autoclaved) vs single-use</li>\n<li>Reusable LMAs where appropriate</li>\n<li>Minimise unnecessary opening of sterile packs</li>\n<li>Sustainable procurement policies</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h4>5. Regional Anaesthesia</h4>\n<ul>\n<li>Spinal/epidural/peripheral nerve blocks use minimal resources</li>\n<li>No volatile agents, minimal plastic waste</li>\n<li>Where appropriate, regional anaesthesia is the greenest option</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h4>6. System-Level Changes</h4>\n<ul>\n<li>Eliminate pipeline N2O (switch to cylinder-on-demand)</li>\n<li>Energy-efficient OT design (LED lighting, optimised HVAC)</li>\n<li>Electronic anaesthesia records (paperless)</li>\n<li>Carbon footprint reporting as quality metric</li>\n</ul>\n\n<div class='drug-grid'>\n<div class='drug-card dc-green'><div class='drug-name'>TIVA (Propofol)</div><div class='drug-dose'>GWP ~3.5</div><div class='drug-note'>Lowest carbon footprint. No atmospheric persistence. Plastic waste is main concern</div></div>\n<div class='drug-card dc-teal'><div class='drug-name'>Sevoflurane</div><div class='drug-dose'>GWP 130</div><div class='drug-note'>Preferred volatile if inhalational needed. Short atmospheric lifetime (1.1 years)</div></div>\n<div class='drug-card dc-amber'><div class='drug-name'>Nitrous Oxide</div><div class='drug-dose'>GWP 265, 116yr lifetime</div><div class='drug-note'>Also ozone depleting. Minimise use. Consider eliminating from routine practice</div></div>\n<div class='drug-card dc-rose'><div class='drug-name'>Desflurane</div><div class='drug-dose'>GWP 2540</div><div class='drug-note'>AVOID. 20x worse than Sevoflurane. Banned in UK, restricted in USA. Phase out</div></div>\n</div>\n\n<div class='viva-box'><div class='viva-head'>Viva Corner</div>\n<div class='viva-item'><div class='viva-q'>Why is Desflurane being phased out globally?</div><div class='viva-a'>Desflurane has a Global Warming Potential (GWP) of 2540 - meaning 1kg of Desflurane is equivalent to 2540kg of CO2 in terms of greenhouse effect over 100 years. Its atmospheric lifetime is 14 years. One MAC-hour of Desflurane = driving 40km. Additionally, it requires a heated pressurised Tec-6 vaporiser (energy intensive), it has no clinical advantages over Sevoflurane in most cases, and it is more expensive. The UK NHS banned it in 2024. The USA Joint Commission and ASA have urged reduction. India should follow this trend.</div></div>\n<div class='viva-item'><div class='viva-q'>What is low-flow anaesthesia and how does it help?</div><div class='viva-a'>Low-flow anaesthesia uses fresh gas flows of 0.5-1 L/min (vs conventional 2-4 L/min). Benefits: (1) Reduces volatile agent consumption by 50-75% - directly reduces GHG emissions. (2) Reduces cost significantly. (3) Preserves airway heat and humidity. (4) Reduces N2O consumption. Requirements: circle system with CO2 absorber, agent monitor, oxygen analyser (to prevent hypoxic mixtures), and leak-free circuit. Minimal flow (0.5 L/min) is possible with modern workstations but requires careful monitoring.</div></div>\n<div class='viva-item'><div class='viva-q'>What is the carbon footprint of TIVA vs inhalational anaesthesia?</div><div class='viva-a'>TIVA with propofol has dramatically lower carbon footprint: Propofol GWP ~3.5 (from plastic packaging). Remifentanil has negligible GWP. For a 2-hour case: TIVA = ~4g CO2 equivalent; Sevoflurane low-flow = ~110g CO2 equivalent; Desflurane = ~1260g CO2 equivalent. However TIVA generates more plastic waste (syringes, bags, lines) and propofol lipid emulsion has environmental costs. Net result: TIVA still significantly greener than volatile anaesthesia for most cases.</div></div>\n</div>\n\n<div class='pearl'><div class='pearl-head'>Examiner's Pearl</div>\n<p><strong>(1)</strong> GWP hierarchy: Propofol (3.5) &lt;&lt; Sevoflurane (130) &lt; N2O (265) &lt; Isoflurane (510) &lt;&lt; Desflurane (2540). <strong>(2)</strong> Desflurane = 40km car drive per MAC-hour. <strong>(3)</strong> Low-flow anaesthesia reduces consumption 50-75% - simplest green intervention. <strong>(4)</strong> N2O also depletes ozone - dual environmental harm. <strong>(5)</strong> Regional anaesthesia = greenest option where appropriate.</p>\n<p style='margin-top:10px'><strong>References:</strong> McGain F, Naylor C. Environmental sustainability in anaesthesia (BJA 2014;113:551-560). Sherman JD et al. Sustainable Anaesthesiology (Anesth Analg 2018;126:1049-1055). Varughese S, Ahmed R. Environmental and Occupational Considerations of Anaesthesia (Anesth Analg 2021;133:1073-1082). Patel S et al. Carbon footprint of anaesthetic drugs (BJA 2021;126:576-578). Sulbaek Andersen MP et al. GWP of inhalational anaesthetics (BJA 2012;109:249-253). Miller's Anaesthesia 9th Ed Chapter 4.</p></div>";
ANSWERS["17"]="<h3>Sepsis and Septic Shock &#x2014; Surviving Sepsis Campaign (SSC) 2021 Guidelines [10]</h3>\n\n<div class='hl hl-danger'><span class='hl-icon'>&#x1F6A8;</span><div class='hl-body'><div class='hl-title'>Global Burden</div>\n<p>Sepsis affects <strong>49 million people annually</strong> worldwide with <strong>11 million deaths</strong> (20% of all global deaths). In India, sepsis mortality in ICUs ranges 40-60%. It is the final common pathway of most critical illnesses. Early recognition and protocolised management saves lives &#x2014; every hour of delay in antibiotics increases mortality by 7%.</p></div></div>\n\n<h3>1. Definitions &#x2014; Sepsis-3 (2016, Reaffirmed 2021)</h3>\n\n<div class='mech-box'><span class='ht'>SEPSIS-3 DEFINITIONS (Singer et al, JAMA 2016):</span>\n\n<span class='ht'>INFECTION:</span> Pathological process caused by invasion of normally sterile tissue by microorganisms\n\n<span class='ht'>SEPSIS:</span> Life-threatening organ dysfunction caused by dysregulated host response to infection\n= Suspected/confirmed infection + SOFA score increase of >=2 points\n(SOFA >=2 associated with >10% mortality)\n\n<span class='ht'>SEPTIC SHOCK:</span> Sepsis + vasopressor requirement to maintain MAP >=65 mmHg\n+ Serum lactate >2 mmol/L despite adequate fluid resuscitation\n(Associated with >40% mortality)\n\n<span class='ht'>ABANDONED TERMS:</span> SIRS criteria (too sensitive, not specific enough)\nSevere sepsis (replaced by Sepsis-3 definition)</div>\n\n<h4>qSOFA Score (Quick Bedside Screening)</h4>\n<table><thead><tr><th>Parameter</th><th>Score</th></tr></thead>\n<tbody>\n<tr><td>Respiratory Rate &gt;22/min</td><td>1</td></tr>\n<tr><td>Altered mentation (GCS &lt;15)</td><td>1</td></tr>\n<tr><td>Systolic BP &lt;100 mmHg</td><td>1</td></tr>\n</tbody></table>\n<p>qSOFA &gt;= 2 = high risk of poor outcome. Use for screening OUTSIDE ICU. NOT for diagnosis.</p>\n\n<h4>SOFA Score (Sequential Organ Failure Assessment)</h4>\n<table><thead><tr><th>System</th><th>Parameter</th><th>Score 0-4</th></tr></thead>\n<tbody>\n<tr><td><strong>Respiratory</strong></td><td>PaO2/FiO2 ratio</td><td>4 = &lt;100 on ventilator</td></tr>\n<tr><td><strong>Coagulation</strong></td><td>Platelets (x10^3/uL)</td><td>4 = &lt;20</td></tr>\n<tr><td><strong>Liver</strong></td><td>Bilirubin (mg/dL)</td><td>4 = &gt;12</td></tr>\n<tr><td><strong>Cardiovascular</strong></td><td>MAP / vasopressors</td><td>4 = Dopamine &gt;15 or Adrenaline &gt;0.1</td></tr>\n<tr><td><strong>CNS</strong></td><td>GCS</td><td>4 = GCS &lt;6</td></tr>\n<tr><td><strong>Renal</strong></td><td>Creatinine / UO</td><td>4 = &gt;5.0 mg/dL or &lt;200mL/day</td></tr>\n</tbody></table>\n\n<h3>2. SSC 2021 Guidelines &#x2014; Hour-1 Bundle</h3>\n\n<div class='hl hl-danger'><span class='hl-icon'>&#x1F550;</span><div class='hl-body'><div class='hl-title'>SSC Hour-1 Bundle &#x2014; Do ALL within 1 hour of recognition</div>\n<p><strong>1.</strong> Measure lactate. Re-measure if initial lactate &gt;2 mmol/L.<br>\n<strong>2.</strong> Obtain blood cultures BEFORE antibiotics (minimum 2 sets).<br>\n<strong>3.</strong> Administer broad-spectrum antibiotics.<br>\n<strong>4.</strong> Begin 30 mL/kg crystalloid for hypotension OR lactate &gt;= 4 mmol/L.<br>\n<strong>5.</strong> Apply vasopressors if hypotensive during/after fluid resuscitation to maintain MAP &gt;= 65 mmHg.</p></div></div>\n\n<h3>3. Resuscitation &#x2014; SSC 2021</h3>\n\n<h4>A. Fluid Resuscitation</h4>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Initial bolus:</strong> 30 mL/kg IV crystalloid within 3 hours (Strong recommendation)</li>\n<li><strong>Preferred fluid:</strong> Balanced crystalloids (Ringer's Lactate, PlasmaLyte) over Normal Saline</li>\n<li>Normal Saline: risk of hyperchloraemic metabolic acidosis, AKI</li>\n<li><strong>SMART trial (2018):</strong> Balanced crystalloids reduced major adverse kidney events vs NS</li>\n<li><strong>Colloids:</strong> Albumin may be used after initial crystalloid resuscitation (weak recommendation)</li>\n<li><strong>HES (Hydroxyethyl Starch):</strong> CONTRAINDICATED in sepsis (increased AKI and mortality - CHEST trial)</li>\n<li><strong>Reassess after each bolus:</strong> Fluid responsiveness assessment essential to avoid fluid overload</li>\n</ul>\n\n<div class='hl hl-teal'><span class='hl-icon'>&#x1F4A1;</span><div class='hl-body'><div class='hl-title'>Fluid Responsiveness Assessment &#x2014; ROSE Concept</div>\n<p><strong>R</strong>esuscitation &#x2014; aggressive fluid in first hour. <strong>O</strong>ptimisation &#x2014; goal-directed. <strong>S</strong>tabilisation &#x2014; conservative fluids. <strong>E</strong>vacuation &#x2014; de-resuscitation with diuretics. Dynamic markers of fluid responsiveness: Pulse Pressure Variation (PPV) &gt;13% = fluid responsive. Stroke Volume Variation (SVV) &gt;10%. Passive Leg Raise (PLR) test &#x2014; increases venous return, SV increases &gt;10% = responsive. POCUS: IVC collapsibility &gt;50% in spontaneous breathing = hypovolaemia.</p></div></div>\n\n<h4>B. Vasopressors</h4>\n<table><thead><tr><th>Vasopressor</th><th>Dose</th><th>Mechanism</th><th>SSC 2021 Recommendation</th></tr></thead>\n<tbody>\n<tr><td><strong>Noradrenaline</strong></td><td>0.01-3 mcg/kg/min</td><td>Alpha-1 &gt;&gt; Beta-1</td><td>FIRST LINE &#x2014; Strong recommendation</td></tr>\n<tr><td><strong>Vasopressin</strong></td><td>0.03 units/min (fixed)</td><td>V1 receptors</td><td>ADD-ON to reduce noradrenaline dose (VASST trial)</td></tr>\n<tr><td><strong>Adrenaline</strong></td><td>0.01-1 mcg/kg/min</td><td>Alpha + Beta</td><td>Add if MAP target not met with Norad + Vasopressin</td></tr>\n<tr><td><strong>Dopamine</strong></td><td>2-20 mcg/kg/min</td><td>Dose-dependent</td><td>Alternative to Noradrenaline in select patients only (more arrhythmias)</td></tr>\n<tr><td><strong>Phenylephrine</strong></td><td>0.5-9 mcg/kg/min</td><td>Pure Alpha-1</td><td>NOT recommended as first line (reduces cardiac output)</td></tr>\n</tbody></table>\n\n<div class='hl hl-warn'><span class='hl-icon'>&#x26A0;&#xFE0F;</span><div class='hl-body'><div class='hl-title'>MAP Target</div>\n<p>Target MAP <strong>&gt;= 65 mmHg</strong> as initial resuscitation target. Higher MAP (80-85 mmHg) may benefit patients with chronic hypertension (SEPSISPAM trial). Insert arterial line in all patients requiring vasopressors &#x2014; non-invasive BP unreliable in shock. Start vasopressors via peripheral IV while central access being established &#x2014; do NOT delay vasopressors waiting for CVL.</p></div></div>\n\n<h4>C. Corticosteroids</h4>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Indication:</strong> Septic shock requiring &gt;= 0.25 mcg/kg/min noradrenaline for &gt;= 4 hours</li>\n<li><strong>Drug:</strong> Hydrocortisone 200 mg/day IV (50mg QID or 200mg continuous infusion)</li>\n<li><strong>Duration:</strong> Until vasopressors no longer required</li>\n<li><strong>Evidence:</strong> ADRENAL trial (2018) and APROCCHSS trial (2018)</li>\n<li>Hydrocortisone reduces vasopressor duration but does NOT reduce 90-day mortality</li>\n<li>Do NOT use dexamethasone (no mineralocorticoid activity)</li>\n<li>ACTH stimulation test NOT recommended to guide steroid use</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h3>4. Infection Management</h3>\n\n<h4>A. Antibiotics &#x2014; SSC 2021</h4>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Timing:</strong> Within 1 hour of sepsis recognition (Strong recommendation)</li>\n<li>Each hour of delay increases mortality by 7% (Kumar et al, 2006)</li>\n<li><strong>Blood cultures FIRST</strong> &#x2014; but do NOT delay antibiotics &gt;45 min to get cultures</li>\n<li><strong>Empirical regimen:</strong> Broad-spectrum, cover likely pathogens based on:\n<ul>\n<li>Source of infection (UTI vs pneumonia vs abdominal)</li>\n<li>Community vs hospital-acquired (HAP/VAP)</li>\n<li>Local antibiogram and resistance patterns</li>\n<li>Prior culture data and antibiotic history</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n<li><strong>De-escalation:</strong> Narrow based on culture/sensitivity results (antibiotic stewardship)</li>\n<li><strong>Duration:</strong> 7 days for most sepsis. Procalcitonin-guided de-escalation recommended</li>\n<li><strong>Anti-MRSA cover:</strong> If risk factors (nosocomial, indwelling devices, prior MRSA) &#x2014; add Vancomycin or Linezolid</li>\n<li><strong>Anti-fungal:</strong> Only if Candida confirmed/strongly suspected (NOT empirical in most cases)</li>\n</ul>\n\n<div class='drug-grid'>\n<div class='drug-card dc-rose'><div class='drug-name'>Piperacillin-Tazobactam</div><div class='drug-dose'>4.5g IV q6h (extended infusion)</div><div class='drug-note'>Broad-spectrum first line for sepsis. Covers gram-negatives including Pseudomonas. Extended infusion improves PK/PD</div></div>\n<div class='drug-card dc-indigo'><div class='drug-name'>Meropenem</div><div class='drug-dose'>1-2g IV q8h</div><div class='drug-note'>For severe sepsis, ICU, prior resistant organisms, neutropenia. Extended infusion 3-4hr for resistant organisms</div></div>\n<div class='drug-card dc-amber'><div class='drug-name'>Vancomycin</div><div class='drug-dose'>25-30 mg/kg loading, then AUC-guided</div><div class='drug-note'>For MRSA coverage. AUC/MIC guided dosing (target 400-600) superior to trough-based (SSC 2021)</div></div>\n<div class='drug-card dc-teal'><div class='drug-name'>Noradrenaline</div><div class='drug-dose'>0.01-3 mcg/kg/min</div><div class='drug-note'>First-line vasopressor. Titrate to MAP &gt;=65. Peripheral IV acceptable while CVC being placed</div></div>\n<div class='drug-card dc-green'><div class='drug-name'>Hydrocortisone</div><div class='drug-dose'>200 mg/day IV continuous</div><div class='drug-note'>Only if noradrenaline &gt;=0.25 mcg/kg/min for &gt;=4 hours. Reduces vasopressor duration</div></div>\n<div class='drug-card dc-purple'><div class='drug-name'>Vasopressin</div><div class='drug-dose'>0.03 units/min fixed dose</div><div class='drug-note'>Add-on to noradrenaline. Reduces noradrenaline requirements. Do NOT titrate</div></div>\n</div>\n\n<h4>B. Source Control</h4>\n<ul>\n<li>Identify and control source of infection within 6-12 hours</li>\n<li>Drain abscesses, remove infected devices, debride necrotic tissue</li>\n<li>Least invasive approach first (percutaneous drainage vs surgery)</li>\n<li>Remove intravascular access devices if infected</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h3>5. Ventilation in Sepsis-Associated ARDS</h3>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Tidal Volume:</strong> 6 mL/kg predicted body weight (lung protective)</li>\n<li><strong>Plateau Pressure:</strong> &lt;30 cmH2O</li>\n<li><strong>Driving Pressure:</strong> &lt;15 cmH2O (Amato et al, NEJM 2015)</li>\n<li><strong>PEEP:</strong> Higher PEEP strategy for moderate-severe ARDS (P/F &lt;200)</li>\n<li><strong>Prone positioning:</strong> &gt;16 hours/day for P/F &lt;150 (PROSEVA trial)</li>\n<li><strong>Neuromuscular blockade:</strong> 48 hours for severe ARDS (P/F &lt;150) &#x2014; Cisatracurium</li>\n<li><strong>Recruitment manoeuvres:</strong> NOT recommended routinely (ART trial showed harm)</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h3>6. Other SSC 2021 Recommendations</h3>\n\n<h4>Blood Glucose Management</h4>\n<ul>\n<li>Target glucose 7.8-10 mmol/L (140-180 mg/dL)</li>\n<li>Insulin infusion protocol when glucose &gt;10 mmol/L on two readings</li>\n<li>NICE-SUGAR trial: tight control (4.5-6 mmol/L) INCREASED mortality</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h4>Renal Replacement Therapy</h4>\n<ul>\n<li>CRRT preferred over IHD in haemodynamically unstable patients</li>\n<li>No evidence for early RRT in absence of specific indications</li>\n<li>STARRT-AKI trial: early vs standard RRT - no mortality difference</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h4>DVT Prophylaxis</h4>\n<ul>\n<li>LMWH preferred over UFH (Strong recommendation)</li>\n<li>Mechanical prophylaxis (compression stockings) if pharmacological contraindicated</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h4>Stress Ulcer Prophylaxis</h4>\n<ul>\n<li>PPI or H2 blocker for patients with risk factors (coagulopathy, ventilation &gt;48h)</li>\n<li>No prophylaxis for low-risk patients (PEPTIC trial)</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h4>Nutrition</h4>\n<ul>\n<li>Early enteral nutrition within 72 hours (preferred over parenteral)</li>\n<li>Do NOT use early parenteral nutrition if enteral possible</li>\n<li>Permissive underfeeding in first week acceptable</li>\n</ul>\n\n<div class='viva-box'><div class='viva-head'>Viva Corner</div>\n<div class='viva-item'><div class='viva-q'>What is the difference between Sepsis-2 and Sepsis-3 definitions?</div><div class='viva-a'>Sepsis-2 (2001) used SIRS criteria (2 of 4: fever/hypothermia, tachycardia, tachypnoea, WBC abnormality) plus suspected infection. SIRS was too sensitive - nearly every ICU patient met criteria. Sepsis-3 (2016) replaced SIRS with organ dysfunction: Sepsis = infection + SOFA increase &gt;=2. Severe sepsis was eliminated as a separate category. Septic shock = sepsis + vasopressor requirement + lactate &gt;2 despite fluids. Sepsis-3 better predicts mortality and identifies truly sick patients.</div></div>\n<div class='viva-item'><div class='viva-q'>Why are balanced crystalloids preferred over Normal Saline in sepsis?</div><div class='viva-a'>Normal Saline (0.9% NaCl) contains 154 mEq/L of chloride - supraphysiological (plasma chloride = 98-106 mEq/L). Large volumes cause hyperchloraemic metabolic acidosis, which causes renal vasoconstriction and AKI. The SMART trial (2018, NEJM) showed balanced crystalloids (Ringer's Lactate, PlasmaLyte) reduced major adverse kidney events by 1.1% absolute reduction vs NS in ICU patients. Balanced solutions have composition closer to plasma. SSC 2021 gives weak recommendation for balanced crystalloids over NS.</div></div>\n<div class='viva-item'><div class='viva-q'>When do you add vasopressin in septic shock?</div><div class='viva-a'>Vasopressin (0.03 units/min, fixed dose) is added as second-line vasopressor when noradrenaline dose exceeds 0.25-0.5 mcg/kg/min to achieve MAP target. The VASST trial showed vasopressin allowed noradrenaline dose reduction (vasopressor-sparing effect) and may benefit patients with less severe shock. Dose is FIXED at 0.03 units/min and NOT titrated. Higher doses cause mesenteric and coronary vasoconstriction. Terlipressin (0.5-2 mg 4-6 hourly) is an alternative used in India.</div></div>\n<div class='viva-item'><div class='viva-q'>What is the role of corticosteroids in septic shock per SSC 2021?</div><div class='viva-a'>Hydrocortisone 200 mg/day IV is recommended for septic shock patients requiring noradrenaline &gt;=0.25 mcg/kg/min for &gt;=4 hours despite adequate resuscitation (SSC 2021 Weak recommendation). Evidence: ADRENAL trial (2018) - hydrocortisone reduced vasopressor duration and ICU stay but NOT 90-day mortality. APROCCHSS trial (2018) - hydrocortisone + fludrocortisone reduced 90-day mortality. ACTH stimulation test is NOT recommended to select patients. Do not use dexamethasone (lacks mineralocorticoid activity). Taper gradually when vasopressors being weaned.</div></div>\n<div class='viva-item'><div class='viva-q'>What is the lactate target in sepsis resuscitation?</div><div class='viva-a'>SSC 2021 recommends lactate-guided resuscitation with target to normalise lactate in patients with elevated lactate (lactate &gt;2 mmol/L) as a marker of tissue hypoperfusion. Lactate clearance of &gt;10% over 2 hours indicates adequate resuscitation. Initial lactate &gt;4 mmol/L indicates high mortality and mandates immediate aggressive resuscitation. Serial lactate every 1-2 hours until normalised (&lt;2 mmol/L). Lactate elevation in sepsis = tissue hypoperfusion + accelerated aerobic glycolysis from catecholamine stimulation of beta-2 receptors in muscle.</div></div>\n</div>\n\n<div class='pearl'><div class='pearl-head'>Examiner's Pearl</div>\n<p><strong>(1)</strong> Sepsis-3: Infection + SOFA &gt;=2. Septic shock: + vasopressors + lactate &gt;2. <strong>(2)</strong> Hour-1 bundle: Lactate, cultures, antibiotics, 30mL/kg fluid, vasopressors. <strong>(3)</strong> Noradrenaline = first line vasopressor. Add vasopressin 0.03 units/min as second agent. <strong>(4)</strong> Balanced crystalloids over NS. HES contraindicated. <strong>(5)</strong> Antibiotics within 1 hour - every hour delay = 7% mortality increase. <strong>(6)</strong> Hydrocortisone 200mg/day only if norad &gt;=0.25 mcg/kg/min for &gt;=4 hours. <strong>(7)</strong> Lung protective ventilation: TV 6mL/kg, Pplat &lt;30, prone if P/F &lt;150.</p>\n<p style='margin-top:10px'><strong>References:</strong> Evans L et al. Surviving Sepsis Campaign Guidelines 2021 (Crit Care Med 2021;49:e1063-e1143). Singer M et al. Sepsis-3 Definitions (JAMA 2016;315:801-810). SMART Trial - Semler MW et al. (NEJM 2018;378:819-828). ADRENAL Trial - Venkatesh B et al. (NEJM 2018;378:797-808). VASST Trial - Russell JA et al. (NEJM 2008;358:877-887). PROSEVA Trial - Guerin C et al. (NEJM 2013;368:2159-2168). Kumar A et al. Duration of hypotension and mortality in septic shock (Crit Care Med 2006;34:1589-1596). Miller's Anaesthesia 9th Ed Chapter 98. Oh's Intensive Care Manual 8th Ed.</p></div>";
ANSWERS["18"]="<h3>Costoclavicular Approach for Brachial Plexus Block [5]</h3>\n\n<div class='hl hl-info'><span class='hl-icon'>&#x1F4CB;</span><div class='hl-body'><div class='hl-title'>Overview</div>\n<p>The <strong>costoclavicular approach</strong> (CC block) is a relatively new infraclavicular approach to the brachial plexus block, first described by Karmakar et al. in 2015. It targets the brachial plexus cords at the <strong>costoclavicular space</strong> &#x2014; where the three cords (lateral, medial, posterior) are compactly arranged in a single fascial compartment, allowing a single-injection technique with reliable block of all four terminal nerves.</p></div></div>\n\n<h4>Anatomy of Costoclavicular Space</h4>\n\n<div class='mech-box'><span class='ht'>BOUNDARIES OF COSTOCLAVICULAR SPACE:</span>\nAnterior:    Clavicle (posterior surface)\nPosterior:   First rib + Serratus anterior\nMedial:      Subclavian / Axillary vessels\nLateral:     Coracoid process\n\n<span class='ht'>CORD ARRANGEMENT AT THIS LEVEL:</span>\nLateral cord  &#x2014; Anterolateral to axillary artery\nPosterior cord &#x2014; Posterior to axillary artery\nMedial cord   &#x2014; Medial/posteromedial to axillary artery\n\nKEY FEATURE: All 3 cords are <span class='ht'>compact and clustered</span> here\nUnlike infraclavicular (cords spread out) or axillary (terminal nerves diverge)</div>\n\n<h4>Indications</h4>\n<ul>\n<li>Surgery of the elbow, forearm, wrist and hand</li>\n<li>Where supraclavicular block is contraindicated (contralateral phrenic nerve palsy, severe COPD)</li>\n<li>When axillary approach has failed or is difficult (axillary lymphadenopathy, axillary contracture)</li>\n<li>Patient cannot abduct arm for axillary block (trauma, pain)</li>\n<li>Continuous catheter placement for prolonged analgesia</li>\n<li>Obese patients where supraclavicular landmarks are difficult to identify</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h4>Advantages over Other Infraclavicular Approaches</h4>\n<table><thead><tr><th>Feature</th><th>Costoclavicular</th><th>Lateral Sagittal Infraclavicular</th><th>Axillary</th></tr></thead>\n<tbody>\n<tr><td><strong>Needle depth</strong></td><td>Shallow (2-4 cm)</td><td>Deep (4-6 cm)</td><td>Shallow</td></tr>\n<tr><td><strong>Cord arrangement</strong></td><td>Compact cluster</td><td>Triangle around artery</td><td>Diverged</td></tr>\n<tr><td><strong>Injections needed</strong></td><td>Single injection</td><td>1-3 injections</td><td>3-4 injections</td></tr>\n<tr><td><strong>Pneumothorax risk</strong></td><td>Low</td><td>Low</td><td>None</td></tr>\n<tr><td><strong>Phrenic nerve</strong></td><td>Spared</td><td>Spared</td><td>Spared</td></tr>\n<tr><td><strong>Catheter stability</strong></td><td>Excellent</td><td>Good</td><td>Poor (arm movement)</td></tr>\n<tr><td><strong>Arm position needed</strong></td><td>Neutral/adducted</td><td>Abducted 90 degrees</td><td>Abducted 90 degrees</td></tr>\n</tbody></table>\n\n<h4>Ultrasound-Guided Technique</h4>\n\n<h4>Patient Position</h4>\n<ul>\n<li>Supine, head turned slightly away from side to be blocked</li>\n<li>Arm in neutral position at side (KEY ADVANTAGE &#x2014; no arm abduction needed)</li>\n<li>Small roll under ipsilateral shoulder helpful</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h4>Probe Position</h4>\n<ul>\n<li>High-frequency linear probe (10-15 MHz)</li>\n<li>Placed in <strong>infraclavicular fossa</strong>, medial to coracoid process</li>\n<li>Probe orientation: parallel to clavicle (transverse to vessels)</li>\n<li>Identify axillary artery (pulsatile, compressible) and axillary vein</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h4>Sonoanatomy</h4>\n<div class='mech-box'><span class='ht'>ULTRASOUND APPEARANCE AT COSTOCLAVICULAR SPACE:</span>\n\nAxillary Artery  &#x2014; Round, pulsatile, non-compressible\nAxillary Vein    &#x2014; Oval, compressible, medial to artery\nLateral Cord     &#x2014; Hyperechoic, lateral/anterolateral to artery\nPosterior Cord   &#x2014; Hyperechoic, posterior to artery\nMedial Cord      &#x2014; Hyperechoic, medial to artery\n\n<span class='ht'>KEY SIGN: \"Traffic Light\" Sign</span>\nThree cords appear as three hyperechoic dots\naround the artery &#x2014; like a traffic light pattern</div>\n\n<h4>Needle Insertion</h4>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Approach:</strong> In-plane, lateral to medial</li>\n<li><strong>Entry point:</strong> Lateral border of the probe</li>\n<li><strong>Target:</strong> Posterior cord first (posterior to artery) OR centre of the cord cluster</li>\n<li><strong>Needle:</strong> 22G, 50mm echogenic needle</li>\n<li><strong>Depth:</strong> Usually 2-4 cm (shallower than lateral sagittal infraclavicular)</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h4>Local Anaesthetic</h4>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Volume:</strong> 20-30 mL (single injection)</li>\n<li><strong>Agent:</strong> Ropivacaine 0.5% OR Bupivacaine 0.5% for surgical block</li>\n<li>Ropivacaine 0.2% for postoperative analgesia via catheter</li>\n<li>Dexamethasone 4-8 mg added to prolong block duration</li>\n<li><strong>End point:</strong> U-shaped or donut spread around all three cords</li>\n<li>If spread incomplete &#x2014; redirect needle for supplemental injection</li>\n</ul>\n\n<div class='hl hl-teal'><span class='hl-icon'>&#x1F4A1;</span><div class='hl-body'><div class='hl-title'>Single Injection Technique</div>\n<p>The compact arrangement of cords in the costoclavicular space means that a single injection of 20-25 mL posterior to the artery, with gentle needle adjustment, achieves spread to all three cords in &gt;90% of cases. This is the main advantage over the lateral sagittal infraclavicular approach which may require 2-3 separate injections for complete block. Watch for U-shaped spread on ultrasound encompassing all cords.</p></div></div>\n\n<h4>Block Assessment</h4>\n<table><thead><tr><th>Terminal Nerve</th><th>Cord Origin</th><th>Motor Test</th><th>Sensory Test</th></tr></thead>\n<tbody>\n<tr><td><strong>Musculocutaneous</strong></td><td>Lateral</td><td>Elbow flexion</td><td>Lateral forearm</td></tr>\n<tr><td><strong>Median</strong></td><td>Lateral + Medial</td><td>Finger flexion, thumb opposition</td><td>Lateral 3.5 fingers (palm)</td></tr>\n<tr><td><strong>Ulnar</strong></td><td>Medial</td><td>Finger abduction (intrinsics)</td><td>Medial 1.5 fingers</td></tr>\n<tr><td><strong>Radial</strong></td><td>Posterior</td><td>Wrist/finger extension</td><td>Dorsal hand (anatomical snuffbox)</td></tr>\n<tr><td><strong>Axillary</strong></td><td>Posterior</td><td>Shoulder abduction</td><td>Lateral arm (regimental badge)</td></tr>\n</tbody></table>\n\n<h4>Complications</h4>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Vascular puncture:</strong> Axillary artery/vein (always apply pressure, use colour Doppler)</li>\n<li><strong>Pneumothorax:</strong> Low risk (deeper than supraclavicular, but first rib nearby)</li>\n<li><strong>Local anaesthetic systemic toxicity (LAST):</strong> Always aspirate, inject incrementally</li>\n<li><strong>Phrenic nerve palsy:</strong> Very rare at this level (phrenic nerve high in neck)</li>\n<li><strong>Brachial plexus injury:</strong> Use nerve stimulator AND ultrasound, avoid intraneural injection</li>\n<li><strong>Infection:</strong> Strict asepsis</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h4>Comparison with Supraclavicular Block</h4>\n<div class='hl hl-warn'><span class='hl-icon'>&#x26A0;&#xFE0F;</span><div class='hl-body'><div class='hl-title'>When to Choose Costoclavicular over Supraclavicular</div>\n<p><strong>Choose Costoclavicular when:</strong> Contralateral phrenic nerve palsy (supraclavicular causes 100% ipsilateral phrenic palsy). Severe respiratory compromise where any phrenic palsy is dangerous. Difficult supraclavicular sonoanatomy (short neck, obesity). Catheter needed for prolonged analgesia (better fixation). <strong>Choose Supraclavicular when:</strong> Faster onset needed. Shoulder surgery not included in case (costoclavicular may miss axillary nerve). Quick single-injection block for forearm/hand surgery.</p></div></div>\n\n<div class='viva-box'><div class='viva-head'>Viva Corner</div>\n<div class='viva-item'><div class='viva-q'>What is the traffic light sign in costoclavicular block?</div><div class='viva-a'>On ultrasound at the costoclavicular space, the three brachial plexus cords appear as three hyperechoic (bright) dots arranged around the axillary artery - lateral cord anterolaterally, posterior cord posteriorly, and medial cord medially/posteromedially. This three-dot arrangement around the circular artery resembles a traffic light pattern. This compact clustering is the key feature that makes single-injection technique possible and distinguishes this level from the axillary approach where terminal nerves have already diverged.</div></div>\n<div class='viva-item'><div class='viva-q'>Why is arm abduction NOT required for the costoclavicular block?</div><div class='viva-a'>In the axillary approach, arm abduction to 90 degrees is needed to bring the neurovascular bundle into view and allow needle insertion. In the costoclavicular approach, the target is medial to the coracoid process in the infraclavicular fossa, which is accessible with the arm in neutral position at the side. This is a major advantage in trauma patients with painful arm injuries, burns, contractures, or patients with restricted shoulder movement who cannot abduct the arm.</div></div>\n<div class='viva-item'><div class='viva-q'>What volume of local anaesthetic is needed and why is it less than axillary block?</div><div class='viva-a'>Only 20-25 mL is needed for costoclavicular block compared to 30-40 mL for axillary block (which requires 3-4 separate injections for musculocutaneous, median, ulnar, and radial nerves). At the costoclavicular space, all three cords are compact in a tight fascial compartment - a single injection with good spread surrounds all cords simultaneously. This reduces total LA dose, lowers LAST risk, and simplifies technique. Single injection vs multiple injections also reduces patient discomfort and procedure time.</div></div>\n</div>\n\n<div class='pearl'><div class='pearl-head'>Examiner's Pearl</div>\n<p><strong>(1)</strong> Costoclavicular space = between posterior clavicle (anterior) and first rib (posterior). <strong>(2)</strong> Three cords compact here = single injection technique possible. <strong>(3)</strong> Traffic light sign on ultrasound &#x2014; three hyperechoic dots around artery. <strong>(4)</strong> Arm in NEUTRAL position &#x2014; key advantage over axillary block. <strong>(5)</strong> Phrenic nerve spared (unlike supraclavicular). <strong>(6)</strong> 20-25 mL Ropivacaine 0.5% posterior to artery targets all cords.</p>\n<p style='margin-top:10px'><strong>References:</strong> Karmakar MK et al. Costoclavicular brachial plexus block (Reg Anesth Pain Med 2015;40:411-416). Leurcharusmee P et al. Reliability of costoclavicular approach (Reg Anesth Pain Med 2017;42:233-238). Li JW et al. Comparison of costoclavicular and lateral sagittal infraclavicular (Anaesthesia 2017;72:1018-1026). Songthamwat B et al. Ultrasound-guided costoclavicular block (Reg Anesth Pain Med 2018;43:396-401). Hadzic's Peripheral Nerve Blocks 3rd Ed. Miller's Anaesthesia 9th Ed Chapter 46.</p></div>";
ANSWERS["19"]="<h3>Total Intravenous Anaesthesia (TIVA)</h3><div class='hl hl-info'><span class='hl-icon'></span><div class='hl-body'><div class='hl-title'>Definition</div><p>TIVA = technique of general anaesthesia using intravenous agents exclusively (no inhaled agents) to maintain all components of anaesthesia: unconsciousness, analgesia, and where necessary, muscle relaxation. Most commonly achieved with <strong>propofol + remifentanil infusions</strong> using Target-Controlled Infusion (TCI).</p></div></div><h4>Components of TIVA</h4><div class='drug-grid'><div class='drug-card dc-indigo'><div class='drug-name'>Propofol (Hypnosis)</div><div class='drug-dose'>TCI: Marsh or Schnider model; Ke0 effect-site target 3-6 mcg/mL</div><div class='drug-note'>Most commonly used. Antiemetic. \u2193CBF, \u2193CMRO2. Pain on injection</div></div><div class='drug-card dc-rose'><div class='drug-name'>Remifentanil (Analgesia)</div><div class='drug-dose'>TCI: Minto model; effect-site 2-8 ng/mL intraoperative</div><div class='drug-note'>Ultra-short acting (ester hydrolysis). Titratable. Risk of PONV and hyperalgesia on stopping</div></div><div class='drug-card dc-teal'><div class='drug-name'>Ketamine (Adjunct)</div><div class='drug-dose'>Sub-anaesthetic: 0.1-0.3 mg/kg/hr infusion</div><div class='drug-note'>NMDA antagonism \u2192 opioid-sparing + prevents remifentanil-induced hyperalgesia</div></div><div class='drug-card dc-amber'><div class='drug-name'>Muscle Relaxants</div><div class='drug-dose'>Rocuronium 0.6 mg/kg</div><div class='drug-note'>Separate from TIVA components. TOF monitoring essential</div></div></div><h4>Target-Controlled Infusion (TCI) \u2014 How It Works</h4><ul><li>TCI pump uses pharmacokinetic (PK) model (3-compartment model) to calculate infusion rates needed to achieve a target plasma or effect-site drug concentration</li><li>The pump automatically adjusts rate based on the target, patient demographics (age, weight, height), and elapsed time</li><li><strong>Plasma TCI (Cp):</strong> Targets plasma concentration \u2014 Marsh model for propofol</li><li><strong>Effect-site TCI (Ce):</strong> Targets effect-site (brain) concentration \u2014 accounts for equilibration lag (Ke0) \u2014 Schnider model for propofol. More clinically accurate</li><li>Models: Marsh (simple, uses weight only), Schnider (uses age + weight + height + lean body mass \u2014 more accurate in elderly and obese)</li></ul><h4>Advantages of TIVA</h4><ul><li>No environmental pollution (no volatile agent in theatre air)</li><li>Superior PONV prophylaxis \u2014 propofol is antiemetic (ideal for strabismus, ENT, laparoscopy)</li><li>Rapid recovery with predictable emergence</li><li>Neuroanaesthesia \u2014 \u2193CBF, \u2193CMRO2, \u2193ICP (versus volatile agents which vasodilate)</li><li>Remote anaesthesia (MRI, interventional radiology) \u2014 no vaporiser needed</li><li>Malignant hyperthermia susceptibility \u2014 TIVA is safe (no triggering agents)</li><li>Awake craniotomy \u2014 precise titration, rapid offset when needed</li><li>Bain's circuit or field anaesthesia \u2014 any setting with IV access</li></ul><h4>Disadvantages / Risks</h4><ul><li><strong>Awareness risk:</strong> No means of monitoring drug delivery like end-tidal concentration. Use BIS/entropy monitoring (target 40-60). Always monitor for signs of light anaesthesia</li><li>IV access essential \u2014 failure = loss of anaesthesia</li><li>Remifentanil hyperalgesia \u2014 abrupt offset causes acute opioid-induced hyperalgesia; mitigate with pre-emptive ketamine, NSAID, conversion to longer-acting opioid 20 min before end</li><li>Propofol infusion syndrome (PRIS) \u2014 rare but fatal: metabolic acidosis, rhabdomyolysis, cardiac failure. Risk: high dose (&gt;4 mg/kg/hr) + long duration + low carbohydrate intake. Avoid in ICU &gt;48 hours at high doses</li><li>Cost \u2014 TCI pumps and remifentanil are more expensive than volatile agents</li></ul><div class='hl hl-danger'><span class='hl-icon'></span><div class='hl-body'><div class='hl-title'>Propofol Infusion Syndrome (PRIS)</div><p>Rare but potentially fatal. Features: <strong>unexplained metabolic acidosis, rhabdomyolysis, lipaemic plasma, hepatomegaly, cardiac dysrhythmia (right bundle branch block, ST changes)</strong>. Risk factors: dose &gt;4 mg/kg/hr, duration &gt;48 hours, low carbohydrate diet, catecholamine infusions. Management: stop propofol immediately, haemodynamic support, dialysis.</p></div></div><div class='pearl'><div class='pearl-head'>\u2b50 Examiner's Pearl</div><p>Four points that always come up: <strong>(1)</strong> TCI \u2014 effect-site vs plasma target, and why effect-site is preferred (accounts for lag). <strong>(2)</strong> Awareness risk \u2014 BIS monitoring is mandatory. <strong>(3)</strong> Remifentanil hyperalgesia \u2014 pre-emptive ketamine prevents it. <strong>(4)</strong> PRIS features \u2014 ABCDE: Acidosis, bradycardia, cardiac failure, death; Elevated CK and triglycerides. Name these clearly.</p></div>";
ANSWERS["20"]="<h3>Bone Cement Implantation Syndrome (BCIS)</h3><div class='hl hl-danger'><span class='hl-icon'></span><div class='hl-body'><div class='hl-title'>Definition</div><p>BCIS = acute cardiovascular collapse occurring during or immediately after cementation of bone (usually PMMA \u2014 polymethylmethacrylate) in orthopaedic surgery. Characterised by: <strong>hypoxia, hypotension, arrhythmia, and cardiac arrest</strong> occurring within minutes of cement insertion.</p></div></div><div class='mech-box'><span class='ht'>PATHOPHYSIOLOGY \u2014 THREE MECHANISMS:</span>\n1. EMBOLISM: Fat, marrow, air, cement particles \u2192 pulmonary vasculature \u2192 \u2191 PVR \u2192 acute RV failure \u2192 \u2193 CO\n2. METHYLMETHACRYLATE MONOMER: Vasodilatory + myocardial depressant effect; peak at cement mixing\n3. COMPLEMENT ACTIVATION: Immune-mediated \u2192 systemic inflammatory response\n\nNet effect: <span class='ar'>\u2500\u2500\u25b6</span> Hypoxia + Hypotension + \u2191 PAP + \u2193 CO + Arrhythmia</div><h4>Pitto's Classification (Grading)</h4><table><thead><tr><th>Grade</th><th>Features</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><strong>Grade 1</strong></td><td>SpO2 &lt;94% or BP fall &gt;20% from baseline \u2014 no treatment required beyond monitoring</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Grade 2</strong></td><td>SpO2 &lt;88% or BP fall &gt;40% \u2014 requires active intervention</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Grade 3</strong></td><td>CV collapse requiring CPR \u2014 often fatal; cardiac arrest within minutes of cementation</td></tr></tbody></table><h4>Risk Factors</h4><ul><li><strong>Patient factors:</strong> Elderly, pulmonary hypertension, pre-existing cardiovascular disease, osteoporosis (more fat in bone), previous VTE</li><li><strong>Surgical factors:</strong> Cemented prosthesis vs cementless, unreamed vs reamed femoral canal, intramedullary instrumentation without venting, total hip arthroplasty &gt; hemiarthroplasty</li><li><strong>Cement generation:</strong> Older (1st generation) cement with longer monomer release period \u2014 higher risk</li></ul><h4>Prevention</h4><ul><li><strong>Cement technique:</strong> Retrograde filling of femoral canal (distal to proximal with cement gun \u2014 reduces air embolism)</li><li><strong>Canal venting:</strong> Proximal femoral vent hole allows pressurised contents to escape rather than enter vasculature</li><li><strong>Pulse lavage</strong> of femoral canal \u2014 removes fat and marrow debris before cementing</li><li><strong>Reduce cement pressure:</strong> 3rd generation cement technique; not hand packing</li><li><strong>Pre-cement FiO2 1.0:</strong> Administer 100% O2 immediately before and during cementation</li><li><strong>Volume preload:</strong> 500 mL crystalloid before cementation to buffer haemodynamic effect</li><li>Warn surgeon to give 60-second notice before cementing \u2014 anaesthetist prepares</li></ul><h4>Management During BCIS</h4><ul><li><strong>Immediately:</strong> 100% O2, IV fluids (500 mL rapid), vasopressors (phenylephrine or noradrenaline boluses)</li><li><strong>Grade 2-3:</strong> Adrenaline 50-100 mcg IV boluses; atropine for bradycardia</li><li><strong>Cardiac arrest:</strong> CPR, adrenaline 1 mg IV, amiodarone for VF/VT</li><li>Inotropes (dobutamine) if RV failure \u2014 milrinone for pulmonary vasodilation</li><li>Consider TTE/TOE to diagnose massive embolism and guide management</li><li>Post-resuscitation: ICU admission; intubate if not already done</li></ul><div class='pearl'><div class='pearl-head'>\u2b50 Examiner's Pearl</div><p>Three key points: <strong>(1)</strong> Three mechanisms \u2014 embolism, MMA monomer vasodilation, complement activation. Say all three. <strong>(2)</strong> Prevention: 100% O2 before cementation + volume preload + femoral canal venting + surgeon gives 60-second warning. <strong>(3)</strong> Treatment: vasopressors first (phenylephrine), then adrenaline for Grade 2-3. Grade 3 = CPR. Pitto's classification shows you know the grading system.</p></div>";
ANSWERS["21"]="<h3>End-of-Life Counselling in Anaesthesia and Critical Care</h3><div class='hl hl-purple'><span class='hl-icon'></span><div class='hl-body'><div class='hl-title'>Context</div><p>End-of-life (EOL) counselling refers to structured communication between the clinical team and patient/family regarding goals of care, withdrawal/withholding of life-sustaining treatment, palliative care, and death in the context of terminal or irreversible illness. Anaesthetists and intensivists are frequently involved in these conversations in ICU, theatre holding, and do-not-resuscitate (DNR) discussions.</p></div></div><h4>A. Principles of End-of-Life Communication</h4><ul><li><strong>Autonomy:</strong> Respect patient's right to accept or refuse treatment \u2014 even if it leads to death</li><li><strong>Beneficence:</strong> Act in patient's best interest \u2014 sometimes this means stopping futile treatments</li><li><strong>Non-maleficence:</strong> Avoid prolonging suffering with burdensome interventions that offer no meaningful benefit</li><li><strong>Justice:</strong> Fair allocation of ICU resources; not continuing futile care at expense of others</li><li><strong>Honesty with compassion:</strong> Share prognosis truthfully but with sensitivity \u2014 avoid false hope</li></ul><h4>B. SPIKES Framework \u2014 Delivering Bad News</h4><table><thead><tr><th>Step</th><th>Meaning</th><th>Action</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><strong>S</strong></td><td>Setting up</td><td>Private room, all relevant family present, sit at eye level, no interruptions</td></tr><tr><td><strong>P</strong></td><td>Perception</td><td>Assess what patient/family already know: &quot;What have you been told about the illness?&quot;</td></tr><tr><td><strong>I</strong></td><td>Invitation</td><td>Ask permission: &quot;Are you ready to discuss the latest test results?&quot;</td></tr><tr><td><strong>K</strong></td><td>Knowledge</td><td>Give information in plain language. Avoid jargon. Deliver in stages with pauses</td></tr><tr><td><strong>E</strong></td><td>Emotions</td><td>Acknowledge, validate, allow silence. &quot;I can see this is very difficult for you.&quot;</td></tr><tr><td><strong>S</strong></td><td>Summary/Strategy</td><td>Summarise what was discussed, outline next steps, arrange follow-up meeting</td></tr></tbody></table><h4>C. Withholding and Withdrawing Life-Sustaining Treatment</h4><ul><li>Ethically and legally equivalent in most jurisdictions \u2014 stopping treatment = not starting it</li><li><strong>Futility:</strong> When treatment cannot achieve its physiological goal or offers no meaningful benefit to the patient</li><li>Document all discussions clearly in the notes \u2014 date, time, who was present, what was decided</li><li>In India: Supreme Court ruling (Aruna Shanbaug case 2011) + Common Cause judgment (2018) \u2014 Advance Medical Directives (living wills) are legal; passive euthanasia under judicial oversight is permitted</li><li>DNR orders: Discuss proactively, not in crisis. DNR \u2260 do not treat \u2014 other treatment continues</li></ul><h4>D. Palliative Care Integration</h4><ul><li>Early integration of palliative care alongside curative care (not just at end) \u2014 improves quality of life and reduces distress</li><li>Symptom management: pain (opioids), breathlessness (low-dose morphine 2.5-5 mg SC 4-hourly), agitation (midazolam, haloperidol), secretions (glycopyrrolate 0.2 mg SC)</li><li>Spiritual and cultural considerations \u2014 involve chaplain, family's religious beliefs</li><li>Bereavement support for family after death</li></ul><h4>E. Communication with Family in ICU</h4><ul><li>Regular structured family meetings \u2014 at minimum every 72 hours in ICU</li><li>Avoid medical jargon: &quot;His kidneys have failed&quot; not &quot;He has acute tubular necrosis&quot;</li><li>Use VALUE framework: <strong>V</strong>alue family statements, <strong>A</strong>cknowledge emotions, <strong>L</strong>isten, <strong>U</strong>nderstand patient as a person, <strong>E</strong>licit questions</li><li>Cultural sensitivity \u2014 in many Indian families, family makes decisions even if patient is competent; navigate with care</li></ul><div class='pearl'><div class='pearl-head'>\u2b50 Examiner's Pearl</div><p>Three points most tested: <strong>(1)</strong> SPIKES framework \u2014 name all 6 steps in order. <strong>(2)</strong> Withholding vs withdrawing are ethically equivalent \u2014 do not say one is more justified. <strong>(3)</strong> India law: Common Cause judgment (2018) \u2014 Advance Medical Directives are legal. Mention this case \u2014 shows you know the Indian legal context.</p></div>";
ANSWERS["22"]="<h3>Pain \u2014 Definition, Types, and Multidisciplinary Chronic Pain Management</h3><div class='mech-box'><span class='ht'>IASP DEFINITION OF PAIN (revised 2020):</span>\n'An unpleasant sensory and emotional experience associated with, or resembling that associated with,\nactual or potential tissue damage'\nKey addition: pain is always subjective; emotional component is integral, not secondary\nChronic pain: pain persisting >3 months beyond expected healing time</div><h4>A. Nociceptive vs Neuropathic Pain [2 marks]</h4><table><thead><tr><th>Feature</th><th>Nociceptive Pain</th><th>Neuropathic Pain</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><strong>Mechanism</strong></td><td>Activation of nociceptors by tissue damage \u2014 protective function</td><td>Lesion or disease of somatosensory nervous system \u2014 pathological</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Character</strong></td><td>Sharp, throbbing, aching, well-localised</td><td>Burning, shooting, electric shock, pins and needles</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Subtypes</strong></td><td>Somatic (skin, muscle, bone \u2014 well localised) or Visceral (organ \u2014 diffuse, referred)</td><td>Central (spinal cord, brain \u2014 phantom limb, central sensitisation) or Peripheral (nerve \u2014 diabetic neuropathy, PHN, carpal tunnel)</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Allodynia</strong></td><td>Absent</td><td>Present \u2014 pain from non-painful stimulus (light touch)</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Hyperalgesia</strong></td><td>Acute injury related</td><td>Present \u2014 exaggerated response to painful stimulus</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Examples</strong></td><td>Post-op wound pain, fracture, appendicitis</td><td>PHN (post-herpetic neuralgia), diabetic neuropathy, phantom limb, CRPS</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Response to opioids</strong></td><td>Good</td><td>Partial \u2014 adjuvants (gabapentinoids, TCAs) often needed</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Diagnostic tool</strong></td><td>NRS/VAS, clinical</td><td>DN4 questionnaire, NRS, QST, nerve conduction studies</td></tr></tbody></table><h4>B. Multidisciplinary Team (MDT) for Chronic Pain [7 marks]</h4><div class='hl hl-teal'><span class='hl-icon'>\u2b50</span><div class='hl-body'><div class='hl-title'>Why MDT? \u2014 Biopsychosocial Model of Pain</div><p>Chronic pain is not purely physical. It involves biological, psychological, and social factors. No single specialty can address all dimensions. MDT combines expertise to treat the whole person, not just the pain source.</p></div></div><h4>1. Team Composition</h4><ul><li><strong>Pain Physician/Anaesthesiologist:</strong> Interventional procedures (nerve blocks, epidurals, SCS), opioid prescribing, overall programme co-ordination</li><li><strong>Psychologist/Psychiatrist:</strong> CBT (Cognitive Behavioural Therapy) for pain catastrophising, depression, anxiety \u2014 KEY component; identifies and treats psychological comorbidities</li><li><strong>Physiotherapist:</strong> Graded exercise therapy, posture correction, manual therapy, TENS \u2014 addresses deconditioning</li><li><strong>Occupational Therapist:</strong> Return-to-work planning, activity modification, assistive devices</li><li><strong>Nurse Specialist:</strong> Patient education, medication management, liaison</li><li><strong>Social Worker:</strong> Financial issues, work/legal matters, carer support</li><li><strong>Pharmacist:</strong> Complex analgesic regimen review, opioid stewardship, side effect management</li></ul><h4>2. Assessment</h4><ul><li>Multidimensional pain assessment: NRS (intensity), BPI (Brief Pain Inventory \u2014 functional impact), HADS (anxiety/depression), PCS (Pain Catastrophising Scale), DN4 (neuropathic component)</li><li>Identify: pain type, functional impairment, psychological comorbidity, social impact, prior treatments, opioid use/misuse risk</li></ul><h4>3. Treatment Approaches</h4><table><thead><tr><th>Domain</th><th>Interventions</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><strong>Pharmacological</strong></td><td>WHO analgesic ladder; neuropathic: gabapentin/pregabalin, amitriptyline/duloxetine; SNRIs; opioids (reviewed regularly, opioid stewardship); topical: lidocaine patches, capsaicin</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Interventional</strong></td><td>Nerve blocks (medial branch, intercostal, SGB), epidural steroid injections, RF ablation, spinal cord stimulation (SCS), intrathecal drug delivery systems</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Psychological</strong></td><td>CBT (gold standard for chronic pain), Acceptance and Commitment Therapy (ACT), mindfulness-based stress reduction (MBSR), biofeedback</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Physical</strong></td><td>Graded exercise therapy, hydrotherapy, TENS, acupuncture (evidence limited), yoga, physiotherapy</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Complementary</strong></td><td>Meditation, relaxation training \u2014 adjunctive role</td></tr></tbody></table><h4>4. Goals of MDT Programme</h4><ul><li>Improve function and quality of life (not cure of pain \u2014 often unachievable)</li><li>Reduce pain intensity by \u226530% (clinically meaningful)</li><li>Reduce healthcare utilisation</li><li>Return to work where possible</li><li>Reduce opioid dependency</li></ul><div class='pearl'><div class='pearl-head'>\u2b50 Examiner's Pearl</div><p>Two key points: <strong>(1)</strong> Neuropathic pain features to know: allodynia + hyperalgesia + burning/shooting quality + DN4 questionnaire. <strong>(2)</strong> MDT: CBT is the psychological cornerstone \u2014 name it specifically. Psychologist is as important as pain physician. Show you know the biopsychosocial model.</p></div>";
ANSWERS["23"]="<h3>Non-Invasive Cardiac Output Monitoring</h3><div class='hl hl-info'><span class='hl-icon'></span><div class='hl-body'><div class='hl-title'>Why Non-Invasive?</div><p>Traditional PA catheter (Pulmonary Artery Catheter/Swan-Ganz) is invasive, has significant complications, and has not been shown to improve outcomes. Non-invasive techniques provide comparable haemodynamic data with fewer risks \u2014 ideal for perioperative goal-directed therapy.</p></div></div><h4>Methods of Non-Invasive Cardiac Output Monitoring</h4><h4>1. Transthoracic Echocardiography (TTE)</h4><ul><li>Measures LVOT VTI (velocity-time integral) \u00d7 LVOT cross-sectional area = Stroke Volume</li><li>CO = SV \u00d7 HR</li><li>Also assesses: valve function, wall motion, preload (IVC collapsibility), fluid responsiveness</li><li>Limitation: operator dependent, intermittent measurement, technically difficult in obese/COPD</li></ul><h4>2. Oesophageal Doppler (CardioQ)</h4><ul><li>Probe placed in oesophagus under sedation/GA; Doppler measures descending aortic blood flow velocity</li><li>SV calculated from velocity \u00d7 aortic cross-sectional area (from nomogram)</li><li>Provides: CO, SV, FTc (flow time corrected) \u2014 FTc &lt;330 ms = hypovolaemia</li><li>Limitation: only 70% of CO (descending aorta); position-dependent; semi-invasive</li></ul><h4>3. Bioreactance (NICOM \u2014 Cheetah Medical)</h4><ul><li>Applies small AC current across chest; measures phase shift in transmitted signal (bioreactance) \u2014 correlates with aortic blood flow</li><li>4-electrode patch system \u2014 completely non-invasive</li><li>Good for trends; less accurate in arrhythmia and low-output states</li></ul><h4>4. Pulse Contour Analysis from Non-Invasive BP (Clearsight/Finger Cuff)</h4><ul><li>Volume clamp finger cuff (Penaz principle) maintains constant arterial volume \u2192 derives beat-to-beat BP waveform \u2192 pulse contour analysis \u2192 CO</li><li>Commercial systems: Clearsight (Edwards), CNAP (CNSystems)</li><li>Limitations: peripheral vasoconstriction affects accuracy; finger oedema; Raynaud's</li></ul><h4>5. Thoracic Bioimpedance</h4><ul><li>High-frequency current applied; changes in chest impedance with cardiac cycle \u2192 SV</li><li>Affected by fluid in chest (pulmonary oedema, pleural effusion), COPD, arrhythmia</li><li>Less accurate than Doppler-based methods</li></ul><h4>6. Partially Invasive \u2014 Arterial Waveform Analysis (LiDCO, PiCCO, FloTrac/Vigileo)</h4><ul><li>Requires arterial line (radial) but no CVC or PA catheter</li><li>Pulse pressure variation (PPV) and Stroke Volume Variation (SVV) derived from arterial waveform</li><li>SVV &gt;13% \u2192 fluid responsive (mechanically ventilated, sinus rhythm)</li><li>FloTrac/Vigileo: validated for perioperative use in major surgery</li></ul><h4>Clinical Applications in Anaesthesia</h4><ul><li>Goal-directed fluid therapy (GDT) \u2014 titrate fluids to optimise SV; shown to reduce post-op complications in major surgery</li><li>Haemodynamic monitoring in high-risk patients avoiding PA catheter</li><li>Monitoring during prone, laparoscopic, sitting position where central access difficult</li></ul><div class='pearl'><div class='pearl-head'>\u2b50 Examiner's Pearl</div><p>Know SVV/PPV interpretation: <strong>SVV &gt;13% = fluid responsive</strong> (only valid in fully mechanically ventilated patients in sinus rhythm, TV \u22658 mL/kg). Oesophageal Doppler: <strong>FTc &lt;330 ms = hypovolaemia</strong>. These two numbers demonstrate you actually use these monitors, not just know the devices exist.</p></div>";
ANSWERS["24"]="<h3>Uterine Atony</h3><div class='hl hl-danger'><span class='hl-icon'></span><div class='hl-body'><div class='hl-title'>Definition and Importance</div><p>Uterine atony = failure of uterus to contract adequately after delivery of placenta. Accounts for <strong>70-80% of all primary PPH</strong>. PPH = blood loss &gt;500 mL after vaginal delivery or &gt;1000 mL after caesarean section. Leading cause of maternal mortality worldwide.</p></div></div><h4>Risk Factors \u2014 4 T's Mnemonic</h4><table><thead><tr><th>T</th><th>Cause</th><th>Examples</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><strong>Tone</strong> (most common)</td><td>Uterine atony \u2014 failure to contract</td><td>Overdistension (twins/polyhydramnios/macrosomia), prolonged labour, augmented labour, multiparity, uterine anomalies, fibroids</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Tissue</strong></td><td>Retained products</td><td>Retained placenta, membranes, clots, placenta accreta spectrum</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Trauma</strong></td><td>Genital tract injury</td><td>Lacerations, episiotomy, uterine rupture, surgical trauma</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Thrombin</strong></td><td>Coagulopathy</td><td>DIC, pre-eclampsia, abruption, AFE, dilutional coagulopathy</td></tr></tbody></table><h4>Prevention of Uterine Atony</h4><ul><li>Active management of third stage of labour (AMTSL): uterotonic drug at/immediately after delivery + controlled cord traction + uterine massage</li><li>Oxytocin 5-10 IU slow IV bolus (preferred) or IM at delivery of anterior shoulder \u2014 first-line</li><li>High-risk patients: oxytocin infusion (40 IU in 500 mL at 125 mL/hr) after delivery</li></ul><h4>Management of Established Uterine Atony/PPH</h4><div class='hl hl-teal'><span class='hl-icon'>\u2b50</span><div class='hl-body'><div class='hl-title'>E-MOTIVE Bundle (WHO 2022) \u2014 Evidence-Based PPH Management</div><p><strong>E:</strong> Examine + Estimate blood loss (weigh clots/blood)<br><strong>M:</strong> Massage the uterus (bimanual compression)<br><strong>O:</strong> Oxytocics \u2014 uterotonic drug bundle<br><strong>T:</strong> Tranexamic acid 1g IV within 3 hours<br><strong>I:</strong> IV fluids, IV access, resuscitation<br><strong>V:</strong> Ventilate (oxygen), escalate if needed<br><strong>E:</strong> Evaluate and escalate if not responding</p></div></div><h4>Stepwise Uterotonic Drug Use</h4><div class='drug-grid'><div class='drug-card dc-teal'><div class='drug-name'>Oxytocin (1st Line)</div><div class='drug-dose'>5-10 IU slow IV OR 10 IU IM. Infusion 20-40 IU/500 mL</div><div class='drug-note'>Rapid onset. Side effects: vasodilation, hypotension, water retention. NEVER rapid IV bolus \u2014 cardiac arrest reported</div></div><div class='drug-card dc-indigo'><div class='drug-name'>Ergometrine (2nd Line)</div><div class='drug-dose'>0.25 mg IM or slow IV</div><div class='drug-note'>Sustained tetanic contraction. Contraindicated: hypertension, pre-eclampsia, Raynaud's, peripheral vascular disease</div></div><div class='drug-card dc-amber'><div class='drug-name'>Carboprost (PGF2\u03b1)</div><div class='drug-dose'>250 mcg IM every 15-90 min (max 8 doses = 2 mg)</div><div class='drug-note'>Contraindicated: asthma. Side effects: bronchoconstriction, diarrhoea, fever</div></div><div class='drug-card dc-rose'><div class='drug-name'>Misoprostol (PGE1)</div><div class='drug-dose'>800-1000 mcg sublingual/rectal</div><div class='drug-note'>Oral/rectal/sublingual \u2014 useful in low-resource settings. Fever very common</div></div></div><h4>Surgical Management (if uterotonics fail)</h4><ul><li>Intrauterine balloon tamponade (Bakri balloon 300-500 mL saline) \u2014 first-line surgical</li><li>Bimanual uterine compression</li><li>B-Lynch suture (compression suture \u2014 uterus-preserving)</li><li>Internal iliac artery ligation</li><li>Uterine artery embolisation (if IR available and haemodynamically stable)</li><li>Hysterectomy \u2014 last resort, life-saving</li></ul><div class='pearl'><div class='pearl-head'>\u2b50 Examiner's Pearl</div><p>Three must-know points: <strong>(1)</strong> 4 T's \u2014 Tone causes 80% of PPH \u2014 memorise. <strong>(2)</strong> Oxytocin NEVER as rapid IV bolus \u2014 causes cardiac arrest (vasodilation + tachycardia). <strong>(3)</strong> Carboprost contraindicated in asthma. E-MOTIVE bundle from WHO 2022 \u2014 show you know the latest guideline name.</p></div>";
ANSWERS["25"]="<h3>Organophosphorus (OP) Poisoning</h3><div class='mech-box'><span class='ht'>MECHANISM:</span>\nOP compound <span class='ar'>\u2500\u2500\u25b6</span> Inhibits acetylcholinesterase (AChE) irreversibly\n<span class='ar'>\u2500\u2500\u25b6</span> ACh accumulates at all cholinergic synapses\n<span class='ar'>\u2500\u2500\u25b6</span> Muscarinic (M) receptors: SLUDGE + bradycardia\n<span class='ar'>\u2500\u2500\u25b6</span> Nicotinic (N) receptors: fasciculations + paralysis + tachycardia\n<span class='ar'>\u2500\u2500\u25b6</span> CNS: anxiety, seizures, coma, respiratory failure\nAGING: Covalent bond between OP and AChE becomes permanent after hours (aging time)\n<span class='ar'>\u2500\u2500\u25b6</span> Pralidoxime must be given BEFORE aging \u2014 effectiveness lost after aging</div><h4>Clinical Features \u2014 DUMBELS + Nicotinic</h4><table><thead><tr><th>System</th><th>Receptor</th><th>Features</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><strong>DUMBELS</strong></td><td>Muscarinic (M)</td><td>D-Defecation/Diarrhoea, U-Urination, M-Miosis, B-Bradycardia/Bronchospasm/Bronchorrhoea, E-Emesis, L-Lacrimation, S-Salivation/Seizures/Sweating</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Nicotinic</strong></td><td>Nicotinic (N)</td><td>Muscle fasciculations \u2192 weakness \u2192 flaccid paralysis. Tachycardia (can override bradycardia). Hypertension, pallor</td></tr><tr><td><strong>CNS</strong></td><td>Both</td><td>Anxiety, restlessness, headache \u2192 seizures \u2192 coma \u2192 central respiratory failure</td></tr></tbody></table><h4>Management</h4><h4>1. Resuscitation (First Priority)</h4><ul><li>Remove from exposure, remove clothing (protect rescuers \u2014 PPE)</li><li>Airway: most die from respiratory failure \u2014 secretions + bronchospasm + paralysis</li><li>Intubation if GCS \u22648 or respiratory failure \u2014 use morphine/midazolam NOT succinylcholine for induction</li><li><strong>AVOID SUCCINYLCHOLINE</strong> \u2014 plasma ChE inhibited by OP \u2192 prolonged apnoea (hours)</li><li>Use rocuronium 1.2 mg/kg for RSI; revert with sugammadex</li><li>100% O2; suction excessive secretions</li></ul><div class='hl hl-danger'><span class='hl-icon'></span><div class='hl-body'><div class='hl-title'>AVOID SUCCINYLCHOLINE in OP Poisoning</div><p>OP inhibits plasma cholinesterase (pseudocholinesterase) which normally breaks down succinylcholine. If given \u2192 succinylcholine not metabolised \u2192 <strong>prolonged neuromuscular block (hours of paralysis)</strong>. Use rocuronium + sugammadex instead.</p></div></div><h4>2. Antidotes</h4><div class='drug-grid'><div class='drug-card dc-teal'><div class='drug-name'>Atropine (First Line)</div><div class='drug-dose'>2-4 mg IV every 5-10 min until secretions dry. Titrate to secretions \u2014 NOT to heart rate. May need 20-100 mg over 24 hrs</div><div class='drug-note'>Blocks MUSCARINIC effects. Does NOT treat nicotinic (paralysis). End-point: drying of secretions, not tachycardia</div></div><div class='drug-card dc-indigo'><div class='drug-name'>Pralidoxime (PAM)</div><div class='drug-dose'>1-2 g IV over 15-30 min, then 500 mg/hr infusion for 24-48 hrs. Must give BEFORE aging</div><div class='drug-note'>Reactivates AChE \u2014 reverses BOTH M and N effects. Ineffective after aging (compound-specific: hours to days). Give early</div></div><div class='drug-card dc-amber'><div class='drug-name'>Benzodiazepines</div><div class='drug-dose'>Diazepam 5-10 mg IV for seizures; Midazolam 0.1-0.2 mg/kg</div><div class='drug-note'>Seizures respond better to benzodiazepines than phenytoin in OP poisoning</div></div></div><h4>3. Decontamination</h4><ul><li>Skin: Remove clothing, wash with soap and water copiously</li><li>GI: Activated charcoal 1 g/kg within 1 hour if ingested + not vomiting. Gastric lavage if &lt;1 hour</li><li>Eyes: Irrigate with NS for 15-20 min</li></ul><div class='pearl'><div class='pearl-head'>\u2b50 Examiner's Pearl</div><p>Three critical points: <strong>(1)</strong> Atropine endpoint = <strong>drying of secretions</strong>, NOT heart rate or pupil size. <strong>(2)</strong> Pralidoxime must be given BEFORE aging \u2014 useless after. Mention compound-specific aging times. <strong>(3)</strong> <strong>AVOID succinylcholine</strong> \u2014 plasma ChE inhibited \u2192 hours of paralysis. These three are the classic exam traps.</p></div>";
ANSWERS["26"]="<h3>Thromboelastogram (TEG)</h3><div class='hl hl-info'><span class='hl-icon'></span><div class='hl-body'><div class='hl-title'>Concept</div><p>TEG is a point-of-care viscoelastic haemostatic assay that measures <strong>the entire process of clot formation, clot strength, and clot dissolution</strong> in whole blood. Unlike conventional coagulation tests (PT, APTT) which only measure individual steps in isolation, TEG provides a global, dynamic picture of haemostasis.</p></div></div><div class='mech-box'><span class='ht'>TEG PARAMETERS AND WHAT THEY MEASURE:</span>\nR (Reaction Time)    Normal: 5-10 min  <span class='ar'>\u2500\u2500\u25b6</span> Time to initial fibrin formation (clotting factor function)\nK (Kinetics)          Normal: 1-3 min   <span class='ar'>\u2500\u2500\u25b6</span> Time to reach 20mm amplitude (fibrinogen + platelet)\n\u03b1 (Alpha angle)       Normal: 53-72\u00b0    <span class='ar'>\u2500\u2500\u25b6</span> Rate of clot strengthening (fibrinogen + platelet interaction)\nMA (Max Amplitude)   Normal: 50-70 mm  <span class='ar'>\u2500\u2500\u25b6</span> Peak clot strength = platelet + fibrin contribution\nLY30                  Normal: 0-8%      <span class='ar'>\u2500\u2500\u25b6</span> % amplitude reduction at 30 min = fibrinolysis\nCI (Coagulation Index) Normal: -3 to +3  <span class='ar'>\u2500\u2500\u25b6</span> Overall haemostatic assessment</div><h4>TEG Waveform Interpretation</h4><table><thead><tr><th>Parameter</th><th>Prolonged / Reduced</th><th>Interpretation</th><th>Treatment</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><strong>R time \u2191</strong></td><td>&gt;10 min</td><td>Factor deficiency, anticoagulant effect, heparin</td><td>FFP; heparinase cup if heparin suspected</td></tr><tr><td><strong>K time \u2191 / \u03b1 angle \u2193</strong></td><td>K&gt;3, \u03b1&lt;53\u00b0</td><td>Fibrinogen deficiency</td><td>Cryoprecipitate or fibrinogen concentrate</td></tr><tr><td><strong>MA \u2193</strong></td><td>&lt;50 mm</td><td>Platelet dysfunction or thrombocytopaenia</td><td>Platelet transfusion \u00b1 DDAVP</td></tr><tr><td><strong>LY30 \u2191</strong></td><td>&gt;8%</td><td>Fibrinolysis</td><td>Tranexamic acid</td></tr><tr><td><strong>All normal</strong></td><td>\u2014</td><td>Surgical bleeding (anatomical), not coagulopathic</td><td>Surgical haemostasis \u2014 no blood products</td></tr></tbody></table><h4>Clinical Uses of TEG in Anaesthesia</h4><ul><li><strong>Massive haemorrhage and trauma:</strong> Guide blood product transfusion \u2014 avoids empirical ratio-based transfusion. TEG-guided therapy reduces FFP and platelet use without worse outcomes (PROPPR trial)</li><li><strong>Cardiac surgery:</strong> Heparin monitoring (heparinase cup), protamine reversal adequacy, post-bypass coagulopathy</li><li><strong>Liver transplantation:</strong> Dynamic coagulation during anhepatic phase; fibrinolysis detection</li><li><strong>Obstetric haemorrhage (PPH):</strong> Rapid diagnosis of fibrinogen deficiency (key early feature)</li><li><strong>Platelet function assays (PlateletMapping):</strong> Effect of antiplatelet drugs (aspirin, clopidogrel) on MA \u2014 helps time surgery after antiplatelet therapy</li></ul><h4>TEG vs ROTEM \u2014 Key Differences</h4><ul><li>TEG (Haemonetics): cup oscillates, pin fixed. ROTEM (TEM International): pin oscillates, cup fixed</li><li>ROTEM uses different nomenclature: CT (= R time), CFT (= K time), MCF (= MA), ML (= LY30)</li><li>Both provide equivalent clinical information; ROTEM more common in European centres</li></ul><div class='pearl'><div class='pearl-head'>\u2b50 Examiner's Pearl</div><p>The examiner expects you to link TEG parameters to treatment: <strong>R \u2191 \u2192 FFP, K\u2191/\u03b1\u2193 \u2192 cryoprecipitate/fibrinogen, MA \u2193 \u2192 platelets, LY30 \u2191 \u2192 TXA</strong>. Also: if ALL parameters normal despite bleeding \u2192 surgical bleeding \u2192 no blood products needed. This diagnostic logic is what the examiner tests \u2014 not just the definitions.</p></div>";
ANSWERS["27"]="<h3>Liposomal Bupivacaine (Exparel)</h3><div class='hl hl-info'><span class='hl-icon'></span><div class='hl-body'><div class='hl-title'>Concept</div><p>Liposomal bupivacaine (trade name: Exparel) is a formulation of bupivacaine encapsulated in multivesicular liposomes (DepoFoam technology). Slow, sustained release from lipid vesicles produces <strong>prolonged local anaesthetic effect up to 72-96 hours</strong> from a single injection \u2014 eliminating the need for continuous infusion catheters in many cases.</p></div></div><div class='mech-box'><span class='ht'>MECHANISM OF PROLONGED ACTION:</span>\nBupivacaine encapsulated in multivesicular DepoFoam particles\n<span class='ar'>\u2500\u2500\u25b6</span> Lipid membrane slowly degrades over 72-96 hours\n<span class='ar'>\u2500\u2500\u25b6</span> Bupivacaine released gradually into surrounding tissue\n<span class='ar'>\u2500\u2500\u25b6</span> Sustained sensory blockade WITHOUT continuous catheter\nPeak plasma concentration: 24-36 hours after injection (delayed vs plain bupivacaine)</div><h4>Formulation Details</h4><ul><li>Concentration: 1.3% (13.3 mg/mL) suspension \u2014 different from standard bupivacaine HCl</li><li>Cannot be mixed with standard bupivacaine &lt;20 min (disrupts liposome structure \u2192 burst release \u2192 toxicity)</li><li>Can mix with normal saline or ropivacaine for volume expansion</li><li>Single-use vials: 20 mL (266 mg) or 10 mL (133 mg)</li><li>Maximum dose: 266 mg total</li></ul><h4>FDA-Approved Indications</h4><ul><li>Infiltration for surgical site analgesia (field blocks) \u2014 haemorrhoidectomy, bunionectomy</li><li>Interscalene block for shoulder surgery</li><li>Femoral nerve block (extended approval)</li></ul><h4>Off-Label Uses (Widely Used)</h4><ul><li>TAP (Transversus Abdominis Plane) block \u2014 abdominal surgery, caesarean section</li><li>Pectoral nerve blocks (PECS I, II)</li><li>Wound infiltration after total knee/hip arthroplasty</li><li>Erector spinae plane (ESP) block</li><li>Paravertebral block for thoracic surgery</li></ul><h4>Advantages</h4><ul><li>72-96 hours of analgesia from single injection \u2014 covers most acute post-op pain period</li><li>Eliminates catheter-related complications (infection, displacement, dislodgement)</li><li>No infusion pump needed \u2014 beneficial in ambulatory surgery settings</li><li>Opioid-sparing \u2014 part of multimodal Enhanced Recovery After Surgery (ERAS) protocols</li></ul><h4>Disadvantages and Controversies</h4><ul><li><strong>Cost:</strong> Significantly more expensive than standard bupivacaine with catheter</li><li><strong>Evidence base:</strong> Several systematic reviews show liposomal bupivacaine not superior to plain bupivacaine with or without catheter infusion in all contexts. Better evidence in specific procedures (shoulder, arthroplasty)</li><li>Delayed peak plasma concentration \u2014 LAST (local anaesthetic systemic toxicity) risk can be delayed and prolonged</li><li>Specific dilution rules \u2014 cannot be mixed with standard bupivacaine HCl &lt;20 min</li></ul><div class='pearl'><div class='pearl-head'>\u2b50 Examiner's Pearl</div><p>Three specific points: <strong>(1)</strong> DepoFoam technology \u2014 multivesicular liposomes, slow release 72-96 hours. <strong>(2)</strong> Cannot mix with standard bupivacaine HCl within 20 minutes \u2014 disrupts liposomes \u2192 burst release \u2192 LAST risk. <strong>(3)</strong> Evidence is mixed \u2014 it is NOT clearly superior to well-placed continuous catheter infusion. Acknowledge the controversy \u2014 shows intellectual honesty.</p></div>";
ANSWERS["28"]="<h3>Sugammadex</h3><div class='hl hl-purple'><span class='hl-icon'></span><div class='hl-body'><div class='hl-title'>Classification and Mechanism</div><p>Sugammadex = modified gamma-cyclodextrin. A <strong>selective relaxant binding agent (SRBA)</strong>. Works by encapsulating rocuronium (and vecuronium) in a tight 1:1 inclusion complex \u2192 rapidly removes free drug from plasma \u2192 creates concentration gradient \u2192 drug dissociates from NMJ \u2192 NMB reversed. Completely novel mechanism \u2014 unlike neostigmine (AChE inhibitor).</p></div></div><div class='mech-box'><span class='ht'>MECHANISM:</span>\nSugammadex (hollow ring molecule with hydrophobic core)\n    <span class='ar'>\u2500\u2500\u25b6</span> Encapsulates rocuronium/vecuronium in tight 1:1 complex\n    <span class='ar'>\u2500\u2500\u25b6</span> Free plasma rocuronium \u2193\u2193 rapidly\n    <span class='ar'>\u2500\u2500\u25b6</span> Concentration gradient: NMJ \u2192 plasma \u2192 sugammadex complex\n    <span class='ar'>\u2500\u2500\u25b6</span> Rocuronium dissociates from AChR at NMJ\n    <span class='ar'>\u2500\u2500\u25b6</span> NMB reversed completely and quickly\n    <span class='ar'>\u2500\u2500\u25b6</span> Complex excreted renally (unchanged)\nSelectivity: Rocuronium &gt;&gt; Vecuronium &gt; Pancuronium. Does NOT reverse atracurium, cisatracurium, succinylcholine</div><h4>Doses</h4><table><thead><tr><th>Indication</th><th>Dose</th><th>Expected Reversal Time</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><strong>Routine reversal</strong> (TOF \u22652)</td><td><strong>2 mg/kg</strong></td><td>~3 minutes to TOF 0.9</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Profound block</strong> (TOF = 0, PTC 1-2)</td><td><strong>4 mg/kg</strong></td><td>~3-5 minutes to TOF 0.9</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Immediate reversal</strong> (full dose rocuronium 1.2 mg/kg \u2014 RSI)</td><td><strong>16 mg/kg</strong></td><td>~3 minutes \u2014 RSI reversal</td></tr></tbody></table><h4>Advantages Over Neostigmine</h4><table><thead><tr><th>Feature</th><th>Sugammadex</th><th>Neostigmine</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Mechanism</td><td>Encapsulation of drug</td><td>AChE inhibition</td></tr><tr><td>Cholinergic side effects</td><td style='color:var(--green)'>None \u2014 no muscarinic effects</td><td style='color:var(--rose)'>Yes \u2014 bradycardia, secretions, bronchospasm; needs anticholinergic</td></tr><tr><td>Reversal at deep block</td><td style='color:var(--green)'>Yes \u2014 even at PTC &gt;0</td><td style='color:var(--rose)'>No \u2014 only at TOF \u22652</td></tr><tr><td>Reversal time</td><td style='color:var(--green)'>~3 min (dose-dependent)</td><td style='color:var(--rose)'>10-15 min</td></tr><tr><td>Can be used in MG</td><td style='color:var(--green)'>Yes \u2014 no cholinergic crisis</td><td style='color:var(--rose)'>Risk of cholinergic crisis</td></tr><tr><td>Residual NMB eliminated</td><td style='color:var(--green)'>Complete (if adequate dose)</td><td style='color:var(--rose)'>Incomplete at deep block</td></tr></tbody></table><h4>Special Indications</h4><ul><li><strong>Cannot intubate \u2014 reversal of RSI:</strong> Rocuronium 1.2 mg/kg (equivalent intubating conditions to succinylcholine) \u2192 if cannot intubate \u2192 sugammadex 16 mg/kg \u2192 complete reversal in 3 min \u2192 patient wakes, breathes \u2014 avoiding surgical airway</li><li><strong>Myasthenia Gravis:</strong> Preferred reversal agent \u2014 no cholinergic crisis risk (see Q1)</li><li><strong>Paediatrics:</strong> Approved &gt;2 years; 2 mg/kg (routine) or 4 mg/kg (deep block)</li></ul><h4>Limitations</h4><ul><li>Only reverses rocuronium and vecuronium \u2014 NOT atracurium, cisatracurium, succinylcholine</li><li>Renal failure: complex excreted renally \u2014 accumulation possible; use with caution in severe renal impairment (eGFR &lt;30)</li><li>Recurrence of block (rare): if sugammadex dose inadequate relative to rocuronium dose</li><li>Interferes with hormonal contraception: advise barrier contraception for 7 days (progesterone encapsulated by cyclodextrin)</li><li>Cost: significantly more expensive than neostigmine</li></ul><div class='pearl'><div class='pearl-head'>\u2b50 Examiner's Pearl</div><p>Three critical points: <strong>(1)</strong> 16 mg/kg for immediate reversal of 1.2 mg/kg rocuronium RSI \u2014 this is the cannot-intubate rescue dose. <strong>(2)</strong> Does NOT reverse atracurium or succinylcholine \u2014 only rocuronium/vecuronium. <strong>(3)</strong> Advise barrier contraception 7 days \u2014 hormonal contraceptive interaction. These three points separate candidates who truly understand sugammadex from those who just know it reverses rocuronium.</p></div>";
ANSWERS["29"]="<h3>Neonatal TEF Repair \u2014 Assessment, Optimisation, Anaesthetic Management</h3><div class='hl hl-purple'><span class='hl-icon'></span><div class='hl-body'><div class='hl-title'>Types of TEF (Gross Classification)</div><p><strong>Type C (most common \u2014 85%):</strong> Proximal oesophageal atresia (blind upper pouch) + distal TEF connecting lower oesophagus to trachea. Gas enters stomach, saliva pools in upper pouch \u2192 aspiration. This is what we anaesthetise.</p></div></div><div class='mech-box'><span class='ht'>WATERSTON CLASSIFICATION (surgical risk):</span>\nGroup A: BW >2.5 kg, healthy       \u2192 Low risk \u2014 primary repair\nGroup B: BW 1.8-2.5 kg OR pneumonia \u2192 Moderate \u2014 staged repair possible\nGroup C: BW <1.8 kg OR severe pneumonia \u2192 High risk \u2014 staged: gastrostomy first</div><h4>A. Preoperative Assessment [3 marks]</h4><ul><li><strong>Diagnose associated anomalies \u2014 VACTERL:</strong> Vertebral, Anal atresia, Cardiac (VSD/ASD/TOF \u2014 30%), TEF, Esophageal atresia, Renal anomalies, Limb defects. Cardiac = most important anaesthetic concern</li><li><strong>ECHO mandatory:</strong> Cardiac defects in 30%. Also determines side of aortic arch \u2014 if right arch, surgeon approaches from left thoracotomy</li><li>Chest X-ray: coiled NG tube in upper pouch (confirms EA), gas in stomach (confirms distal fistula)</li><li>Renal US, spine X-ray, check vertebrae</li><li>Assess respiratory status: degree of aspiration pneumonia, SpO2 on room air</li></ul><h4>B. Preoperative Optimisation [2 marks]</h4><ul><li><strong>Head-up 30\u00b0 position</strong> \u2014 reduces aspiration of pooled saliva into lungs</li><li><strong>Replogle tube</strong> (double-lumen) in upper pouch with continuous suction \u2014 drains saliva before it spills</li><li>Correct fluid deficit: 10% dextrose with electrolytes \u2014 avoid hypoglycaemia</li><li>Temperature: maintain 36.5-37.5\u00b0C \u2014 radiant warmer</li><li>Antibiotics: ampicillin + gentamicin for aspiration pneumonia</li><li>Delay surgery until optimised \u2014 do NOT rush a sick neonate to OT</li></ul><h4>C. Anaesthetic Management [5 marks]</h4><h4>Key Intraoperative Challenge</h4><div class='hl hl-danger'><span class='hl-icon'></span><div class='hl-body'><div class='hl-title'>The Critical Problem: Gas Leaking Through Fistula</div><p>Positive pressure ventilation \u2192 gas takes path of least resistance \u2192 through fistula \u2192 inflates stomach \u2192 diaphragm splints \u2192 cannot ventilate lungs \u2192 life-threatening. Solution: <strong>intubate DISTAL to fistula</strong> before any PPV, or use spontaneous ventilation during induction.</p></div></div><h4>Induction \u2014 Avoid PPV Until Fistula is Controlled</h4><ul><li><strong>Option 1 (preferred):</strong> Inhalational induction with sevoflurane in 100% O2, maintaining spontaneous ventilation \u2192 intubate awake/light \u2192 advance ETT PAST the fistula (usually just above carina, right mainstem then pull back) \u2192 confirm with FOB \u2192 now safe for PPV</li><li><strong>Option 2:</strong> Awake intubation under topical lignocaine \u2014 neonate tolerates if expert</li><li>ATropine 20 mcg/kg IV pre-induction to prevent bradycardia and dry secretions</li></ul><h4>ETT Positioning \u2014 Critical Step</h4><ul><li>ETT tip must sit <strong>below the fistula</strong> (fistula opens into posterior trachea, usually 1-2 cm above carina)</li><li>Advance ETT into right main bronchus \u2192 auscultate \u2192 pull back until bilateral \u2014 ensures below fistula</li><li>FOB confirmation: directly visualise ETT tip below fistula opening</li><li>Signs of correct position: stomach does NOT inflate with PPV, SpO2 stable, bilateral chest movement</li></ul><h4>Monitoring</h4><ul><li>Pre-ductal SpO2 (right hand) \u2014 PPHN monitoring</li><li>Arterial line right radial \u2014 serial ABG, beat-to-beat BP</li><li>Temperature probe \u2014 neonate loses heat rapidly; warm OT (28\u00b0C), warm fluids</li><li>Careful neuromuscular monitoring \u2014 neonates sensitive to NMBs</li></ul><h4>Maintenance</h4><ul><li>Sevoflurane + air/O2 (FiO2 titrated to SpO2 94-98%)</li><li>Low TV (4-6 mL/kg), PIP &lt;25 cmH2O \u2014 minimise gas through fistula</li><li>PEEP 3-5 cmH2O \u2014 maintains FRC</li><li>Fentanyl 1-3 mcg/kg/hr \u2014 opioid-sparing with volatile</li><li>Position: left lateral decubitus for right thoracotomy (standard approach)</li><li>Once surgeon divides fistula \u2014 much easier to ventilate</li></ul><h4>Postoperative</h4><ul><li>Planned ventilation 24-48 hours in NICU \u2014 anastomotic tension, pain, prematurity</li><li>Head-up position, neck slightly flexed \u2014 reduces tension on oesophageal anastomosis</li><li>TPN until anastomosis heals (5-7 days), then contrast swallow before oral feeds</li><li>Watch: anastomotic leak (fever, mediastinitis), stricture, recurrent fistula, tracheomalacia</li></ul><div class='pearl'><div class='pearl-head'>\u2b50 Examiner's Pearl</div><p>The single most tested point: <strong>ETT must go BELOW the fistula before any PPV</strong> \u2014 and how you achieve this (advance to RMB then withdraw). Second: <strong>maintain spontaneous ventilation during induction</strong> until fistula is bypassed. Third: <strong>VACTERL \u2014 cardiac defect in 30%</strong> \u2014 always mention ECHO pre-op. These three make the answer.</p></div>";
ANSWERS["30"]="<h3>Pacemakers and ICDs \u2014 Perioperative Management</h3><div class='mech-box'><span class='ht'>NBG PACEMAKER CODE (first 3 letters most important):</span>\nPosition I:  Chamber PACED    (A=Atrium, V=Ventricle, D=Dual, O=None)\nPosition II: Chamber SENSED   (A, V, D, O)\nPosition III: Response to sensing (I=Inhibited, T=Triggered, D=Dual, O=None)\nPosition IV: Rate modulation   (R=rate-responsive, O=none)\nPosition V:  Multisite pacing  (A/V/D/O)\nExample: VVI = Ventricle paced, Ventricle sensed, Inhibited response (most common)\n         DDD = Dual chamber paced + sensed, Dual response (physiological, tracks P waves)</div><h4>A. Pacemaker Classification [4 marks]</h4><table><thead><tr><th>Type</th><th>Code</th><th>Indication</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Single-chamber ventricular demand</td><td>VVI</td><td>AF with slow ventricular rate, AV block</td></tr><tr><td>Single-chamber atrial demand</td><td>AAI</td><td>Sick sinus syndrome with intact AV node</td></tr><tr><td>Dual chamber (physiological)</td><td>DDD</td><td>AV block, sinus node dysfunction \u2014 maintains AV synchrony</td></tr><tr><td>Rate-responsive</td><td>VVIR/DDDR</td><td>Chronotropic incompetence \u2014 sensor adjusts rate with activity</td></tr><tr><td>Biventricular (CRT)</td><td>DDDV</td><td>Heart failure with LBBB \u2014 resynchronisation therapy</td></tr></tbody></table><h4>ICD Classification</h4><ul><li>ICD = defibrillator + pacemaker combined</li><li>Detects VT/VF \u2192 delivers shock (up to 30-40 J internal shock) to cardiovert</li><li>Also has anti-tachycardia pacing (ATP) to overdrive-pace and terminate VT</li><li>NASPE/HRS codes: VV-IVVR (V=shock chamber, V=sensing, I=inhibit ATP, V=V pacing, R=rate responsive)</li></ul><h4>B. Preoperative Information Required [3 marks]</h4><ul><li><strong>Device details:</strong> Manufacturer, model, year of implant, indication for implant, programmed mode and rate, last interrogation date</li><li><strong>Patient dependence:</strong> Is patient pacemaker-dependent? (no underlying rhythm at all if paced off = cardiac arrest risk). Check: what happens if pacing inhibited by EMI?</li><li><strong>ICD:</strong> Is it active? When was last shock? What arrhythmias is it set to treat?</li><li><strong>Symptoms:</strong> Syncope, palpitations, recent device therapy (shock delivery)</li><li><strong>Battery status:</strong> End-of-life indicator? When is next battery change due?</li><li><strong>Contact device clinic:</strong> Request formal device interrogation report within 6 months or before major surgery</li></ul><h4>C. Perioperative Precautions [3 marks]</h4><h4>Electromagnetic Interference (EMI) \u2014 The Main Danger</h4><div class='hl hl-danger'><span class='hl-icon'></span><div class='hl-body'><div class='hl-title'>Diathermy/Electrocautery \u2014 Biggest Intraoperative Risk</div><p>Monopolar diathermy generates EMI that pacemaker senses as cardiac signal \u2192 inhibits pacing (if inhibit-mode, e.g. VVI) \u2192 bradycardia/asystole in pacemaker-dependent patient. ICD: senses EMI as VF \u2192 delivers inappropriate shock \u2014 can cause VF.</p></div></div><h4>Management of Diathermy in Pacemaker Patient</h4><ul><li><strong>Use bipolar diathermy</strong> wherever possible \u2014 minimal EMI, safe for all devices</li><li>If monopolar necessary: <strong>return electrode (plate) as far from device as possible</strong>, current path must not cross device</li><li>Short bursts only \u2014 &lt;1 second at a time, &lt;3 seconds between bursts</li><li>Pacemaker-dependent patients: <strong>programme to asynchronous mode (VOO/DOO)</strong> pre-op \u2014 paces regardless of EMI, never inhibited. Or place magnet over pacemaker</li><li>ICD: <strong>SUSPEND ICD therapy</strong> before surgery \u2014 activate magnet over ICD or programme off shock therapy</li></ul><h4>Magnet Behaviour</h4><ul><li><strong>Pacemaker:</strong> Magnet converts to asynchronous mode (VOO/DOO) \u2014 paces at fixed rate regardless of sensing. Removes EMI inhibition. Rate varies by manufacturer/battery (Medtronic ~85/min, St Jude ~98/min)</li><li><strong>ICD:</strong> Magnet suspends shock therapy but does NOT change pacing behaviour. Remove magnet once surgery done to reactivate</li><li>Check manufacturer-specific response \u2014 NOT all magnets do the same</li></ul><h4>Other Precautions</h4><ul><li>Continuous ECG + peripheral SpO2 + palpate pulse \u2014 if diathermy inhibits ECG, pulse confirms cardiac output</li><li>External defibrillator/pacemaker pads applied before induction in pacemaker-dependent or active ICD patients</li><li>Avoid MRI unless MRI-conditional device confirmed (most modern devices after 2011 are MRI-conditional)</li><li>Avoid: succinylcholine fasciculations (EMI from muscle activity), shivering, hyperkalaemia (T-wave oversensing)</li><li>Post-op: re-interrogate device, restore original settings, re-enable ICD therapy</li></ul><div class='pearl'><div class='pearl-head'>\u2b50 Examiner's Pearl</div><p>Three points that score marks: <strong>(1)</strong> Magnet on pacemaker = asynchronous mode (VOO); magnet on ICD = suspends shocks only. Different effects \u2014 get this right. <strong>(2)</strong> Pacemaker-dependent patient + monopolar diathermy = programme to VOO or apply magnet. <strong>(3)</strong> Always re-enable ICD and restore settings post-operatively \u2014 do not discharge without this.</p></div>";
ANSWERS["31"]="<h3>Total Hip Replacement \u2014 CAD + Drug-Eluting Stent on Dual Antiplatelet [5+5]</h3><div class='hl hl-danger'><span class='hl-icon'></span><div class='hl-body'><div class='hl-title'>The Core Dilemma</div><p>Drug-eluting stent (DES) placed 1 year ago requires DAPT (dual antiplatelet \u2014 aspirin + clopidogrel) for minimum 12 months to prevent in-stent thrombosis. THR is a high-bleeding-risk surgery. <strong>Stopping DAPT \u2192 stent thrombosis \u2192 MI/death. Continuing DAPT \u2192 major surgical bleeding.</strong> This is the central clinical decision.</p></div></div><h4>A. Preoperative Assessment [5 marks]</h4><h4>1. Cardiac Risk Stratification</h4><ul><li>PTCA with DES 1 year ago: per AHA/ACC \u2014 elective non-cardiac surgery should be <strong>delayed minimum 6 months after DES</strong> (ideally 12 months). If &gt;12 months post-DES, risk lower but stent thrombosis still possible</li><li>Assess current cardiac status: angina, heart failure, arrhythmia, exercise tolerance (METs \u2014 can they climb stairs?)</li><li>Review recent cardiology notes, ECG, ECHO (LV function)</li><li>Check medications: aspirin, clopidogrel, atenolol (beta-blocker \u2014 continue perioperatively, sudden stop \u2192 rebound ischaemia), losartan (hold morning of surgery)</li></ul><h4>2. Antiplatelet Decision \u2014 Cardiologist + Haematologist + Surgeon Consensus</h4><table><thead><tr><th>Option</th><th>Risk</th><th>Recommended When</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><strong>Continue both (DAPT)</strong></td><td>Increased surgical bleeding, epidural haematoma if neuraxial</td><td>Highest cardiac risk, recent stent (&lt;6 months)</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Stop clopidogrel, continue aspirin</strong></td><td>Intermediate stent thrombosis risk</td><td>>12 months post-DES, moderate cardiac risk, current consensus for THR</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Stop both</strong></td><td>High stent thrombosis risk \u2014 not recommended for DES</td><td>Only if absolutely necessary with bridging</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Bridge with UFH/LMWH</strong></td><td>No evidence supports bridging for antiplatelet drugs</td><td>NOT recommended for antiplatelet \u2014 bridging is for anticoagulants only</td></tr></tbody></table><div class='hl hl-teal'><span class='hl-icon'>\u2b50</span><div class='hl-body'><div class='hl-title'>Current Consensus (ESC/ACC 2022)</div><p>If DES &gt;12 months: <strong>Stop clopidogrel 5 days before surgery, continue aspirin throughout.</strong> Resume clopidogrel ASAP post-op (within 24-48 hours). This balances bleeding vs thrombosis risk.</p></div></div><h4>3. Other Preoperative Issues</h4><ul><li>Atenolol: continue perioperatively \u2014 beta-blocker withdrawal \u2192 rebound tachycardia + ischaemia</li><li>Losartan: hold morning of surgery \u2014 ACE inhibitors/ARBs cause severe induction hypotension</li><li>Metformin: hold 24-48 hours pre-op if contrast planned; hold day of surgery</li><li>Blood: Group + save, crossmatch 2 units packed cells (THR: expected blood loss 500-1500 mL)</li><li>Anaemia screen: optimise pre-op Hb &gt;10 g/dL \u2014 iron supplements, EPO if needed (avoid transfusion)</li><li>DVT risk: VERY HIGH (THR + immobility + cardiac history) \u2014 plan thromboprophylaxis</li></ul><h4>B. Anaesthetic Plan [5 marks]</h4><h4>Choice of Anaesthesia</h4><div class='hl hl-success'><span class='hl-icon'>\u2b50</span><div class='hl-body'><div class='hl-title'>Neuraxial Anaesthesia = Better Outcomes for THR</div><p>Spinal or combined spinal-epidural (CSE) preferred: reduces blood loss (hypotension lowers surgical bleeding), reduces DVT (compared to GA), less PONV, preserves cognitive function. <strong>BUT: clopidogrel must be stopped 7 days before spinal/epidural (ASRA guidelines).</strong> If aspirin-only, spinal is safe.</p></div></div><ul><li><strong>If clopidogrel stopped 5-7 days:</strong> Spinal anaesthesia with hyperbaric bupivacaine 12.5-15 mg + fentanyl 25 mcg intrathecal. Level T10 needed. Maintain BP within 20% of baseline with phenylephrine infusion (first-line in cardiac patients \u2014 maintains SVR without tachycardia)</li><li><strong>If clopidogrel continued (high cardiac risk):</strong> GA \u2014 avoid neuraxial. Induction: propofol 1-2 mg/kg IV, rocuronium, ETT or LMA. Maintain: sevoflurane + air/O2. Invasive arterial line mandatory</li></ul><h4>Intraoperative Key Points</h4><ul><li>Bone Cement Implantation Syndrome (BCIS): pre-cement 100% O2, 500 mL fluid preload, warn surgeon for 60-second notice. Have vasopressors drawn up</li><li>Haemostasis: TXA (tranexamic acid) 1g IV at induction + 1g at wound closure \u2014 reduces blood loss 30-50% in THR without increasing DVT in low-risk patients (evidence: TRANX trial)</li><li>Temperature: active warming (forced air warmer) \u2014 cardiac patients poorly tolerate hypothermia (\u2191 SVR, shivering \u2192 \u2191 O2 demand)</li><li>ECG: continuous ST-segment monitoring (lead II + V5) \u2014 detect ischaemia intraoperatively</li></ul><h4>Post-operative</h4><ul><li>HDU admission \u2014 cardiac monitoring, 12-lead ECG on arrival</li><li>Resume clopidogrel within 24-48 hours post-op</li><li>Multimodal analgesia: paracetamol + NSAIDs (caution in CAD) + opioids (titrated)</li><li>Early mobilisation, TEDS, LMWH (start 12 hours post-op or after neuraxial catheter removal)</li></ul><div class='pearl'><div class='pearl-head'>\u2b50 Examiner's Pearl</div><p>The examiner tests your decision on antiplatelet management. State clearly: <strong>stop clopidogrel 5-7 days, continue aspirin, resume clopidogrel ASAP post-op</strong>. Then: <strong>neuraxial safe only if clopidogrel stopped &gt;7 days (ASRA guideline)</strong>. Third: BCIS prevention \u2014 100% O2 + fluid preload + 60-second warning. Three decisions = full marks.</p></div>";
ANSWERS["32"]="<h3>Koch's Spine + Pregnancy + Paraplegia \u2192 Anterolateral Decompression</h3><div class='hl hl-warn'><span class='hl-icon'>\u26a0\ufe0f</span><div class='hl-body'><div class='hl-title'>Unique Complexity \u2014 Triple Challenge</div><p>This case combines: <strong>(1)</strong> Active tuberculosis spine with neurological deficit (paraplegia). <strong>(2)</strong> 5 months pregnant (20 weeks \u2014 second trimester). <strong>(3)</strong> Major spinal surgery in prone/lateral position. Each factor alone is complex \u2014 combined, this demands expert multidisciplinary management.</p></div></div><h4>A. Preoperative Preparation [3 marks]</h4><ul><li><strong>Multidisciplinary team:</strong> Obstetrician, neurosurgeon, anaesthetist, neonatology, TB specialist \u2014 plan together</li><li><strong>Fetal assessment:</strong> Obstetric USS \u2014 fetal viability, placental position, amniotic fluid. Fetal heart rate monitoring capability in OT</li><li><strong>TB disease:</strong> Is patient on ATT (anti-tuberculosis therapy)? Continue all ATT perioperatively \u2014 do not stop. Check hepatotoxicity (LFT), peripheral neuropathy (from isoniazid)</li><li><strong>Neurological assessment:</strong> Level and completeness of paraplegia (ASIA scale). Autonomic dysfunction below lesion level (T6 and above = risk of autonomic dysreflexia)</li><li><strong>Investigations:</strong> MRI spine (extent of disease), chest X-ray (TB lung involvement \u2014 with lead shield over abdomen), ECG, LFT/RFT, coagulation, group + crossmatch, FBC</li><li><strong>Positioning plan:</strong> Anterolateral decompression \u2014 lateral or prone with wedge. At 20 weeks, prone position compresses IVC + uterus \u2192 \u2193 venous return \u2192 fetal distress. Lateral preferred</li></ul><h4>B. Anaesthetic Management [4 marks]</h4><h4>1. Drug Considerations in Pregnancy</h4><table><thead><tr><th>Drug</th><th>Safe?</th><th>Notes</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Propofol</td><td style='color:var(--amber)'>Caution \u2014 short exposure acceptable</td><td>Crosses placenta; avoid prolonged TIVA. Safe for induction</td></tr><tr><td>Ketamine</td><td style='color:var(--rose)'>Caution first trimester</td><td>Acceptable second trimester for induction; \u2191 uterine tone at high doses</td></tr><tr><td>Thiopentone</td><td style='color:var(--green)'>Safe</td><td>Traditional induction agent in obstetric GA</td></tr><tr><td>Succinylcholine</td><td style='color:var(--green)'>Safe</td><td>For RSI \u2014 standard dose 1.5 mg/kg</td></tr><tr><td>Volatile agents</td><td style='color:var(--green)'>Safe (short exposure)</td><td>Sevoflurane preferred; avoid prolonged high-dose</td></tr><tr><td>N2O</td><td style='color:var(--rose)'>AVOID</td><td>Inhibits methionine synthase \u2192 folate pathway disruption \u2192 fetal harm. Contraindicated in pregnancy</td></tr><tr><td>NSAIDs</td><td style='color:var(--rose)'>AVOID after 20 weeks</td><td>Premature closure of ductus arteriosus, oligohydramnios</td></tr><tr><td>Opioids</td><td style='color:var(--amber)'>Short-term safe</td><td>Fentanyl, morphine acceptable; neonatal respiratory depression if close to delivery</td></tr></tbody></table><h4>2. Induction</h4><ul><li>20 weeks: aspiration risk present (delayed gastric emptying from progesterone) \u2192 <strong>RSI mandatory from 16-20 weeks onwards</strong></li><li>RSI: Pre-oxygenate 3-5 min \u2192 Thiopentone 4-5 mg/kg (or propofol) \u2192 Succinylcholine 1.5 mg/kg \u2192 BURP/Sellick's (cricoid pressure) \u2192 intubate</li><li>Left lateral uterine displacement \u2014 even at 20 weeks, IVC compression can occur. Wedge under right hip</li></ul><h4>3. Maintenance</h4><ul><li>Sevoflurane 1-1.5% in O2/air (NO N2O)</li><li>FiO2 minimum 0.4 \u2014 fetal oxygen delivery depends on maternal PaO2</li><li>Maintain normotension \u2014 hypotension \u2192 uteroplacental insufficiency \u2192 fetal distress</li><li>If vasopressor needed: Phenylephrine preferred (maintains uterine blood flow) over ephedrine (limited role)</li><li>Normoventilation: PaCO2 30-32 mmHg (physiological alkalosis of pregnancy) \u2014 do not ventilate to normal non-pregnant targets</li></ul><h4>4. Autonomic Dysreflexia Risk (T6 and above paraplegia)</h4><ul><li>Surgical stimulation below level of injury \u2192 massive sympathetic discharge \u2192 hypertensive crisis + bradycardia</li><li>Prevent with adequate depth of anaesthesia and regional techniques (spinal or epidural analgesia)</li><li>Treat: deepen anaesthesia, vasodilators (GTN, labetalol, hydralazine \u2014 safe in pregnancy)</li></ul><h4>C. Postoperative Care [3 marks]</h4><ul><li>HDU monitoring: maternal SpO2, continuous CTG (cardiotocography) \u2014 fetal heart monitoring</li><li>Obstetric review post-op: exclude pre-term labour (surgery may trigger uterine contractions)</li><li>Tocolysis if contractions: MgSO4 or nifedipine (avoid indomethacin &gt;20 weeks)</li><li>Thromboprophylaxis: LMWH \u2014 very high DVT risk (paraplegia + pregnancy + major surgery). Balance with epidural haematoma risk if neuraxial used</li><li>Continue ATT \u2014 check LFT weekly (rifampicin + isoniazid hepatotoxic)</li><li>Analgesia: Paracetamol + opioids (fentanyl PCA) + wound infiltration. Avoid NSAIDs</li></ul><div class='pearl'><div class='pearl-head'>\u2b50 Examiner's Pearl</div><p>Three specific points: <strong>(1)</strong> Avoid N2O in pregnancy \u2014 inhibits methionine synthase \u2192 folate disruption. <strong>(2)</strong> RSI mandatory \u2014 aspiration risk from 16-20 weeks. <strong>(3)</strong> Autonomic dysreflexia if T6 or above injury \u2014 massive hypertension from surgical stimulation. These three show you understand ALL three layers of complexity.</p></div>";
ANSWERS["33"]="<h3>Emergency CS \u2014 PIH + Fetal Distress [3+4+3]</h3><div class='hl hl-danger'><span class='hl-icon'></span><div class='hl-body'><div class='hl-title'>Time-Critical \u2014 Two Lives at Risk</div><p>Fetal distress = Category 1 CS (delivery within 30 minutes of decision). PIH adds: hypertensive crisis risk, coagulopathy (HELLP), thrombocytopaenia, raised ICP (eclampsia). Every anaesthetic decision must balance maternal + fetal safety under time pressure.</p></div></div><h4>A. Assessment [3 marks]</h4><ul><li><strong>Urgency grading:</strong> Category 1 (immediate threat to life) \u2014 DDI (decision to delivery interval) target &lt;30 minutes</li><li><strong>BP:</strong> Severe hypertension if \u2265160/110. Control before induction \u2014 IV labetalol 20 mg (repeat 40-80 mg) or IV hydralazine 5 mg. Target: MAP 105-125 mmHg (not too low \u2014 uteroplacental perfusion)</li><li><strong>Fetal heart:</strong> Review CTG \u2014 decelerations, bradycardia, poor variability</li><li><strong>Platelet count:</strong> CRITICAL for regional decision. ASRA: spinal safe if platelets \u226570-80 \u00d7 10\u2079/L with no rapid fall. If HELLP: check recent trend</li><li><strong>Proteinuria, LFT, RFT, uric acid:</strong> Assess severity of PIH</li><li><strong>Seizure history:</strong> Eclampsia? MgSO4 started?</li><li><strong>Airway:</strong> Oedema of face/tongue from PIH \u2014 may be difficult airway. Assess carefully</li></ul><h4>B. Anaesthesia [4 marks]</h4><h4>Choice of Technique</h4><div class='hl hl-teal'><span class='hl-icon'>\u2b50</span><div class='hl-body'><div class='hl-title'>Spinal Anaesthesia = Preferred Even in Emergency CS</div><p>Spinal is faster to establish than epidural, avoids GA risks (failed intubation, aspiration, awareness, neonatal drug depression). In PIH: spinal \u2193 BP which is HELPFUL (lowers raised BP). Use if platelets \u226570-80 \u00d7 10\u2079/L and no coagulopathy.</p></div></div><h4>Spinal Technique for Emergency CS</h4><ul><li>Position: sitting or lateral \u2014 lateral if BP unstable</li><li>Drug: Hyperbaric bupivacaine 10-12.5 mg + fentanyl 15-25 mcg + morphine 100-150 mcg (for post-op analgesia) intrathecally</li><li>Target level: T4-T6 (test with ice/pinprick)</li><li>Prevent/treat hypotension: phenylephrine infusion 25-50 mcg/min (preferred in PIH \u2014 maintains SVR) started simultaneously. In PIH, hypotension less severe because vasodilation is already blunted</li><li>Left lateral tilt 15\u00b0 \u2014 IVC decompression</li></ul><h4>If GA Required (failed spinal, coagulopathy, extreme urgency)</h4><ul><li>PIH airway is notoriously difficult \u2014 oedema, large tongue, short neck. Call experienced help</li><li>Pre-oxygenate 3-5 min (full FRC), difficult airway trolley ready, video laryngoscope first-line</li><li>RSI: Thiopentone 4-5 mg/kg (or propofol 2 mg/kg) + succinylcholine 1.5 mg/kg + cricoid pressure</li><li>Avoid: ketamine (\u2191 BP \u2014 dangerous in PIH)</li><li>If can't intubate: declare CICO, LMA insertion, scalpel cricothyrotomy</li><li>Maintenance: sevoflurane 1% + O2/air + opioids post-delivery. Add muscle relaxant after cord cut</li></ul><h4>MgSO4 and Anaesthesia</h4><ul><li>Continue MgSO4 throughout surgery (4g loading over 20 min \u2192 1-2g/hr maintenance) \u2014 prevents eclampsia</li><li>MgSO4 potentiates NMBs \u2014 reduce rocuronium/vecuronium dose by 30-50%, monitor TOF carefully</li><li>MgSO4 can cause: hypotension, respiratory depression. Antidote: calcium gluconate 1g IV</li></ul><h4>C. Postoperative / Analgesia [3 marks]</h4><ul><li>Intrathecal morphine 100-150 mcg: 12-24 hours analgesia post-CS</li><li>Scheduled paracetamol 1g 6-hourly + NSAIDs when haemostasis confirmed (COX-2 or diclofenac)</li><li>PCA morphine if intrathecal morphine not given</li><li>BP monitoring: PIH can worsen in first 24-48 hours post-delivery. Continue antihypertensives</li><li>MgSO4: continue 24-48 hours post-delivery (highest eclampsia risk period)</li><li>Monitor for: PPH (uterine atony \u2014 PIH patients have impaired platelet function), HELLP progression</li><li>Fluid restriction: PIH patients have \u2193 oncotic pressure \u2192 pulmonary oedema risk. Do NOT over-hydrate</li></ul><div class='pearl'><div class='pearl-head'>\u2b50 Examiner's Pearl</div><p>Three specifics: <strong>(1)</strong> MgSO4 potentiates NMBs \u2014 reduce dose by 30-50% and monitor TOF. <strong>(2)</strong> In PIH, spinal-induced hypotension is LESS severe than normal pregnancy (vasodilation already present), making spinal safer than commonly thought. <strong>(3)</strong> Fluid restriction post-CS in PIH \u2014 over-hydration \u2192 pulmonary oedema (\u2193 oncotic pressure). Show this nuance.</p></div>";
ANSWERS["34"]="<h3>VATS Lobectomy \u2014 Carcinoma Lung, FEV1 78%, Smoker, 35M [3+3+4]</h3><div class='hl hl-info'><span class='hl-icon'></span><div class='hl-body'><div class='hl-title'>What is VATS Lobectomy?</div><p>Video-Assisted Thoracoscopic Surgery lobectomy \u2014 minimally invasive removal of a lung lobe. Requires <strong>One-Lung Ventilation (OLV)</strong> to collapse the operative lung for surgical access. Less pain, less blood loss, faster recovery than open thoracotomy \u2014 but anaesthetic challenges are identical.</p></div></div><h4>A. Assessment [3 marks]</h4><h4>1. Pulmonary Reserve \u2014 Can He Tolerate Lobectomy?</h4><ul><li>FEV1 78% predicted: moderate \u2014 acceptable for lobectomy</li><li>FVC 65% predicted \u2014 restrictive pattern? Check FEV1/FVC ratio. If &gt;0.7 = no obstruction</li><li><strong>Predicted post-operative FEV1 (ppo-FEV1):</strong> ppo-FEV1 = pre-op FEV1 \u00d7 (1 \u2212 fraction of segments removed). For right lower lobe lobectomy (5 segments of 19 total): ppo-FEV1 = 78% \u00d7 (1 \u2212 5/19) = ~58%. If ppo-FEV1 &gt;40% \u2192 low risk. If 30-40% \u2192 moderate. If &lt;30% \u2192 very high risk</li><li>DLCO (diffusing capacity): should also be measured \u2014 ppo-DLCO &gt;40% predicted = acceptable</li><li>CPEX (cardiopulmonary exercise testing): VO2 max &gt;20 mL/kg/min = low risk; &lt;10 = inoperable</li></ul><h4>2. Cardiac Assessment</h4><ul><li>ECG, ECHO \u2014 check RV function (cor pulmonale risk in chronic smoker)</li><li>6-minute walk test: &gt;400 m = adequate reserve</li><li>20-year smoking history: coronary artery disease risk \u2014 stress test if symptoms</li></ul><h4>B. Optimisation [3 marks]</h4><ul><li><strong>Smoking cessation:</strong> 8 weeks ideally \u2014 reduces secretions, \u2191 mucociliary clearance, \u2193 complications. Even 24-48 hours \u2193 COHb</li><li>Bronchodilators: salbutamol + ipratropium nebulisers if any obstruction \u2014 continue perioperatively</li><li>Chest physiotherapy: pre-op breathing exercises, incentive spirometry \u2014 improves post-op respiratory function</li><li>Nutritional optimisation: chronic smokers often malnourished \u2014 albumin &lt;30 g/L = high complication risk</li><li>VTE prophylaxis: cancer + surgery = very high DVT risk \u2014 LMWH pre-op discussion with surgeon</li></ul><h4>C. Anaesthetic Plan [4 marks]</h4><h4>1. One-Lung Ventilation (OLV) \u2014 Key Requirement</h4><div class='hl hl-teal'><span class='hl-icon'>\u2b50</span><div class='hl-body'><div class='hl-title'>DLT for VATS \u2014 Gold Standard Device for OLV</div><p>Left-sided DLT (37-39 Fr for male) preferred for most lobectomies regardless of side \u2014 left bronchus is longer, less risk of cuff herniation into left upper lobe orifice. Confirm position with FOB after intubation AND after final lateral positioning.</p></div></div><h4>DLT Placement Sequence</h4><ul><li>Intubate with DLT (left-sided, 37-39 Fr) under direct laryngoscopy</li><li>Advance until moderate resistance felt, cuff just below cords</li><li>FOB confirmation: right lumen \u2014 view carina, left lumen opening; left lumen \u2014 advance FOB, confirm left main bronchus (upper lobe orifice visible laterally)</li><li>Reconfirm position after patient goes lateral \u2014 position changes after turning</li></ul><h4>2. OLV Ventilation Strategy</h4><ul><li>TV: <strong>4-6 mL/kg IBW</strong> (not based on total predicted weight \u2014 lung-protective)</li><li>PEEP: 5 cmH2O to dependent (ventilated) lung \u2014 prevents atelectasis</li><li>RR: 12-16/min to maintain PaCO2 35-45 mmHg \u2014 permissive hypercapnia acceptable (up to 50-55)</li><li>FiO2: Start at 1.0 \u2192 titrate down to maintain SpO2 &gt;94% \u2014 minimise O2 toxicity in inflated lung</li><li>I:E: 1:2 to allow adequate expiration \u2014 smoker may have air trapping</li></ul><h4>3. Managing Hypoxia During OLV</h4><div class='mech-box'><span class='ht'>STEPWISE MANAGEMENT OF OLV HYPOXIA (SpO2 <90%):</span>\nStep 1: FiO2 \u2192 1.0\nStep 2: Check DLT position \u2014 FOB confirmation\nStep 3: Recruitment manoeuvre to dependent lung (30 cmH2O \u00d7 30 sec)\nStep 4: CPAP 2-5 cmH2O to non-ventilated (operative) lung\nStep 5: Intermittent re-inflation of operative lung\nStep 6: Surgeon to clip/ligate pulmonary artery early (HPV benefit)\nStep 7: Consider going back to two-lung ventilation if life-threatening</div><h4>4. Analgesia \u2014 Thoracic Epidural or Paravertebral</h4><ul><li>VATS: paravertebral block (PVB) at T4-T6 \u2014 20 mL 0.375% ropivacaine under USS guidance \u2192 opioid-sparing, no sympathetic block to both sides</li><li>Open thoracotomy: thoracic epidural T4-T6 \u2014 gold standard</li><li>Both reduce post-op opioid requirements, enable deep breathing, reduce pulmonary complications</li></ul><h4>5. Postoperative</h4><ul><li>HDU/thoracic ICU \u2014 chest drains, SpO2, RR monitoring</li><li>Early extubation (VATS allows same-day extubation in most cases)</li><li>Chest physiotherapy from day 1, early ambulation</li><li>DVT prophylaxis: LMWH 12 hours post-op (cancer patient = very high risk)</li></ul><div class='pearl'><div class='pearl-head'>\u2b50 Examiner's Pearl</div><p>Three must-know facts: <strong>(1)</strong> ppo-FEV1 calculation \u2014 show the formula (pre-op FEV1 \u00d7 [1 \u2212 segments removed/total segments]). ppo-FEV1 &gt;40% = acceptable risk. <strong>(2)</strong> OLV TV = <strong>4-6 mL/kg IBW</strong>, not 8-10 mL/kg. Lung-protective ventilation prevents VILI. <strong>(3)</strong> CPAP to non-dependent lung = step 4 in hypoxia management \u2014 avoids stopping surgery.</p></div>";
ANSWERS["35"]="<h3>Cataract Surgery \u2014 COPD + T2DM on Metformin + Steroids [4+6]</h3><div class='hl hl-info'><span class='hl-icon'></span><div class='hl-body'><div class='hl-title'>Context</div><p>Cataract surgery = short (20-30 min), minimally invasive, low-blood-loss procedure under topical/peribulbar anaesthesia. The anaesthetic challenge is almost entirely <strong>preoperative \u2014 managing the comorbidities</strong>, not intraoperative. Patient positioning (supine), drug interactions, and anxiety management are the key issues.</p></div></div><h4>A. Preoperative Assessment [4 marks]</h4><h4>1. COPD Assessment</h4><ul><li>GOLD staging, exercise tolerance (METs), home O2?, recent exacerbations, current medications (inhalers \u2014 SABA, LABA, ICS)</li><li>Spirometry: FEV1, FVC \u2014 quantify severity</li><li>SpO2 at baseline, ABG if severe COPD (PaCO2 retention?)</li><li>Can patient lie flat supine for 20-30 minutes? Severe COPD may cause orthopnoea in supine position \u2014 this is the most relevant question for cataract surgery</li><li>Continue all inhalers morning of surgery \u2014 bronchodilators should be used pre-op</li></ul><h4>2. Diabetes Mellitus Assessment</h4><ul><li>Duration, control (HbA1c &lt;8.5% acceptable for elective surgery), complications: neuropathy, nephropathy, CVS</li><li><strong>Metformin:</strong> Hold 24-48 hours before surgery if contrast planned or in poorly controlled patient. For routine cataract with good renal function: many centres omit metformin morning of surgery only. Check eGFR</li><li><strong>Rosiglitazone (thiazolidinedione):</strong> Continue \u2014 no perioperative interaction. Note: associated with fluid retention, cardiac failure risk in elderly</li><li>Blood glucose day of surgery: target 6-10 mmol/L. Check finger-stick glucose pre-op, intra-op (if prolonged), post-op</li><li>Autonomic neuropathy: silent MI, orthostatic hypotension, gastroparesis \u2014 affects sedation safety</li></ul><h4>3. Steroid Inhalers</h4><ul><li>Systemic absorption from inhaled steroids is minimal \u2014 usually no perioperative supplementation needed</li><li>If patient on systemic steroids (oral) for COPD: stress-dose hydrocortisone 25-50 mg IV at induction</li></ul><h4>4. Drug Interactions Summary</h4><table><thead><tr><th>Drug</th><th>Perioperative Action</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Metformin</td><td>Hold morning of surgery (lactic acidosis risk if hypoperfusion)</td></tr><tr><td>Rosiglitazone</td><td>Continue \u2014 no interaction</td></tr><tr><td>Bronchodilator inhaler</td><td>Use morning of surgery \u2014 continue all inhalers</td></tr><tr><td>Steroid inhaler</td><td>Continue \u2014 minimal systemic absorption</td></tr></tbody></table><h4>B. Anaesthetic Plan [6 marks]</h4><h4>1. Technique of Choice \u2014 Local Anaesthesia</h4><div class='hl hl-success'><span class='hl-icon'>\u2705</span><div class='hl-body'><div class='hl-title'>Topical + Intracameral Anaesthesia = Gold Standard for Cataract</div><p>Topical lignocaine 4% eye drops + intracameral lignocaine 1% injected by surgeon into anterior chamber. Completely avoids systemic effects, no needle near orbit, patient mobile immediately after, no akinesia needed with modern phacoemulsification. Most suitable for COPD (no supine position issues) + DM (no fasting-induced hypoglycaemia).</p></div></div><h4>Alternative: Peribulbar Block (if topical not feasible)</h4><ul><li>Bupivacaine 0.5% 5-7 mL + hyaluronidase \u2014 injected outside muscle cone, inferolateral</li><li>Akinesia (eye immobility) achieved \u2014 ideal for less cooperative patients</li><li>Safer than retrobulbar (no optic nerve risk, no brainstem anaesthesia)</li><li>Risk: retrobulbar haemorrhage, globe perforation (rare), chemosis</li></ul><h4>2. Sedation (if needed)</h4><ul><li>Most cataract patients need minimal or no sedation with topical technique</li><li>If anxious: midazolam 0.5-1 mg IV (caution in COPD \u2014 respiratory depression), or dexmedetomidine 0.2-0.5 mcg/kg/hr (preserves respiration, cooperative sedation)</li><li>Avoid: large doses of opioids or propofol (respiratory depression + loss of patient cooperation \u2014 patient must remain still)</li></ul><h4>3. Oculocardiac Reflex (OCR)</h4><ul><li>Trigeminal (V1) afferent \u2192 brainstem \u2192 vagal efferent \u2192 bradycardia + dysrhythmia</li><li>Triggered by: traction on extraocular muscles, eyeball pressure, retrobulbar block</li><li>Treatment: tell surgeon to stop, IV atropine 20 mcg/kg if severe</li><li>Prevention: peribulbar block + gentle surgical technique</li></ul><h4>4. If GA Required (rare \u2014 uncooperative patient)</h4><ul><li>LMA (supraglottic) preferred \u2014 avoids airway stimulation in COPD</li><li>Spontaneous ventilation \u2014 avoid PPV if COPD allows</li><li>Sevoflurane maintenance</li><li>Avoid N2O if intraocular gas has been injected (SF6 \u2014 expands by up to 3\u00d7 with N2O)</li></ul><h4>5. Blood Glucose Management</h4><ul><li>Cataract surgery is short \u2014 most patients can be first on morning list and resume medications immediately after</li><li>If prolonged fast: dextrose-saline infusion, glucose monitoring hourly</li><li>Post-op: resume metformin once eating + drinking, renal function confirmed stable</li></ul><div class='pearl'><div class='pearl-head'>\u2b50 Examiner's Pearl</div><p>Three specific points: <strong>(1)</strong> Can COPD patient lie flat for 30 minutes? \u2014 this determines suitability for local anaesthesia. Most mild-moderate COPD can. <strong>(2)</strong> Topical + intracameral anaesthesia = first choice \u2014 safest, no needle, no systemic effects. <strong>(3)</strong> Metformin: hold morning of surgery \u2014 lactic acidosis risk. Resume when eating and renal function confirmed. These three show clinical-level thinking.</p></div>";
ANSWERS["36"]="<h3>Inadequate Reversal of Neuromuscular Blockade</h3><div class='mech-box'><span class='ht'>RESIDUAL NMB (rNMB) = TOF ratio <0.9 on extubation\nIncidence: up to 40-50% of patients extubated without quantitative TOF monitoring\nConsequence: impaired upper airway reflexes \u2192 aspiration, obstruction, hypoxia, re-intubation</span></div><h4>A. Causes [3 marks]</h4><h4>1. Pharmacological Causes</h4><ul><li>Excessive NMB dose relative to surgical duration (too much drug for too short a surgery)</li><li>Long-acting NMBs (pancuronium) \u2014 not eliminated before emergence</li><li>Recurarisation: redistribution of NMB from peripheral compartments back into plasma after reversal</li><li>Inadequate neostigmine dose (underdosing) or reversal attempted too early (deep block \u2014 TOF count &lt;2)</li></ul><h4>2. Pharmacokinetic Causes (Decreased Elimination)</h4><ul><li><strong>Renal failure:</strong> Most NMBs excreted renally \u2014 pancuronium, vecuronium, rocuronium accumulate</li><li><strong>Hepatic failure:</strong> Vecuronium, rocuronium partly hepatically eliminated</li><li><strong>Hypothermia:</strong> Slows all metabolism + prolongs NMB action; also directly impairs NMJ function</li><li>Elderly: \u2193 renal/hepatic function, \u2193 Vd, prolonged elimination</li></ul><h4>3. Drug Interactions Potentiating NMB</h4><ul><li>Volatile agents (enhance NMJ block by decreasing ACh release + postjunctional sensitivity)</li><li>Aminoglycoside antibiotics, fluoroquinolones</li><li>Magnesium sulphate \u2014 inhibits ACh release presynaptically</li><li>Local anaesthetics (at high doses)</li><li>Calcium channel blockers</li><li>Furosemide (hypokalaemia \u2014 prolongs NMB)</li></ul><h4>4. Patient Factors</h4><ul><li>Metabolic: hypokalaemia, hypocalcaemia, hypomagnesaemia (all worsen NMB)</li><li>Acidosis: \u2193 neuromuscular transmission</li><li>Myasthenia gravis (hypersensitive to NMBs)</li><li>Pseudocholinesterase deficiency (prolongs succinylcholine)</li></ul><h4>B. Signs and Symptoms [2 marks]</h4><table><thead><tr><th>Test</th><th>Residual Block Finding</th><th>Clinical Significance</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>TOF ratio (quantitative)</td><td>&lt;0.9 (most sensitive)</td><td>Impaired pharyngeal function, aspiration risk even at TOF 0.7-0.9</td></tr><tr><td>Head lift &lt;5 sec</td><td>Cannot sustain 5 sec</td><td>Crude \u2014 insensitive; normal head lift does NOT exclude rNMB</td></tr><tr><td>Tongue depressor test</td><td>Cannot grip depressor</td><td>Better than head lift for detecting rNMB</td></tr><tr><td>Respiratory pattern</td><td>See-saw breathing, tracheal tug, paradoxical</td><td>Diaphragm works before intercostals recover</td></tr><tr><td>SpO2</td><td>Desaturation on air</td><td>Late sign \u2014 poor sensitivity for early rNMB</td></tr></tbody></table><h4>C. Management [5 marks]</h4><h4>1. Prevention \u2014 Best Management</h4><ul><li>Quantitative TOF monitoring (acceleromyography) on every patient \u2014 do NOT rely on qualitative feel or head lift</li><li>Use minimum effective NMB dose \u2014 titrate to surgical requirement, not by weight alone</li><li>Plan reversal based on depth of block (TOF count first)</li></ul><h4>2. Reversal Options</h4><div class='drug-grid'><div class='drug-card dc-teal'><div class='drug-name'>Sugammadex</div><div class='drug-dose'>2 mg/kg (TOF \u22652), 4 mg/kg (deep block), 16 mg/kg (immediate)</div><div class='drug-note'>Drug of choice. Encapsulates rocuronium/vecuronium. No cholinergic effects. Works at any depth of block</div></div><div class='drug-card dc-amber'><div class='drug-name'>Neostigmine</div><div class='drug-dose'>0.05 mg/kg IV (max 5 mg) + Glycopyrrolate 0.01 mg/kg</div><div class='drug-note'>Only effective if TOF count \u22652. AChE inhibitor. Add anticholinergic to prevent bradycardia. Cannot reverse deep block</div></div></div><h4>3. If Patient Already Extubated with Residual Block</h4><ul><li>Reapply oxygen mask/face mask \u2014 support oxygenation</li><li>If partial obstruction: jaw thrust, airway adjunct (NPA/OPA)</li><li>If respiratory failure: BVM ventilation + call for help</li><li>Give sugammadex IV (if rocuronium/vecuronium used) \u2014 works extubated</li><li>If neostigmine previously given and recurarisation: DO NOT give more neostigmine (ceiling effect). Give sugammadex</li><li>Reintubate if: SpO2 cannot be maintained, severe respiratory distress, airway compromise</li></ul><h4>4. If Succinylcholine Prolonged (Pseudocholinesterase Deficiency)</h4><ul><li>No antidote \u2014 sugammadex does NOT work on succinylcholine</li><li>Sedate + ventilate until drug wears off</li><li>May take 2-8 hours (homozygous dibucaine-resistant variant)</li><li>Post-op: dibucaine number test, counsel patient and relatives</li></ul><div class='pearl'><div class='pearl-head'>\u2b50 Examiner's Pearl</div><p>Three critical distinctions: <strong>(1)</strong> Head lift &lt;5 seconds is NOT reliable to exclude residual block \u2014 only quantitative TOF ratio &lt;0.9 is the definition. <strong>(2)</strong> Neostigmine has a ceiling \u2014 cannot reverse deep block (TOF count &lt;2). <strong>(3)</strong> If recurarisation post-neostigmine occurs \u2014 give sugammadex, not more neostigmine. These three show you understand the pharmacology.</p></div>";
ANSWERS["37"]="<h3>Labour Analgesia \u2014 All Methods [10]</h3><div class='hl hl-info'><span class='hl-icon'></span><div class='hl-body'><div class='hl-title'>Pain of Labour \u2014 Two Phases</div><p><strong>First stage:</strong> Visceral pain from uterine contractions + cervical dilation \u2192 T10-L1 (lower thoracic sympathetics). Cramping, diffuse, referred to back and thighs.<br><strong>Second stage:</strong> Somatic pain from perineal distension + fetal descent \u2192 S2-S4 (pudendal nerve). Sharp, well-localised perineal pain.</p></div></div><div class='mech-box'><span class='ht'>NERVE PATHWAYS TO BLOCK FOR COMPLETE LABOUR ANALGESIA:</span>\nFirst stage:   Uterine + cervical pain via T10-L1 sympathetics\nSecond stage:  Perineal pain via S2-S4 (pudendal nerve)\nIdeal method:  Must cover T10-S4 for complete analgesia throughout labour</div><h4>A. Non-Pharmacological Methods</h4><ul><li>Continuous support (SUPPORT trial \u2014 reduces CS rate, improves outcomes)</li><li>TENS (transcutaneous electrical nerve stimulation) \u2014 minimal evidence but safe</li><li>Hydrotherapy (warm water immersion) \u2014 reduces pain scores, reduces analgesic use</li><li>Acupuncture, massage, breathing techniques \u2014 limited evidence, safe, patient-preferred</li></ul><h4>B. Systemic Opioids</h4><ul><li><strong>Pethidine (meperidine) IM/IV</strong> \u2014 traditional, widely used. Dose: 50-100 mg IM. Peak: 40-50 min. Limitation: crosses placenta \u2192 neonatal respiratory depression, norpethidine (toxic metabolite) \u2192 neonatal seizures. Being phased out</li><li><strong>Morphine 0.1 mg/kg IM</strong> \u2014 limited use in labour due to neonatal depression</li><li><strong>Fentanyl IV PCA</strong> \u2014 patient-controlled, rapid onset, less neonatal effect than pethidine. Dose: 10-25 mcg bolus, 5-10 min lockout. Maternal sedation is limiting factor</li><li><strong>Remifentanil IV PCA (Minto)</strong> \u2014 best systemic option. Ultra-short acting (1-3 min half-life). 0.2-0.8 mcg/kg bolus with 2-min lockout. Bolus timed to contraction. Limitation: desaturation between contractions \u2014 continuous SpO2 monitoring mandatory, O2 ready, 1:1 midwife ratio. Antidote: naloxone 0.4 mg</li></ul><h4>C. Neuraxial Techniques \u2014 Gold Standard</h4><div class='hl hl-success'><span class='hl-icon'>\u2b50</span><div class='hl-body'><div class='hl-title'>Epidural Labour Analgesia \u2014 Gold Standard</div><p>Most effective, most flexible method. Provides complete analgesia throughout labour and can be extended for CS if needed. No effect on neonatal Apgar scores when properly administered.</p></div></div><h4>1. Epidural Analgesia</h4><ul><li>Insertion: L2-L3 or L3-L4 space, sitting or lateral, epidural space identified by loss of resistance to saline</li><li>Test dose: 3 mL of 1.5% lignocaine + 1:200,000 adrenaline (detects intravascular = tachycardia, intrathecal = motor block)</li><li>Initiation: Bupivacaine 0.1% + fentanyl 2 mcg/mL \u2014 10-15 mL bolus</li><li>Maintenance: PCEA (Patient-Controlled Epidural Analgesia) \u2014 background 5-10 mL/hr + demand 5 mL, 15-min lockout. Or PIEB (Programmed Intermittent Epidural Bolus) \u2014 superior spread</li><li>Advantages: titratable, can extend for CS/instrumental delivery, no neonatal effect</li><li>Complications: hypotension (treat with IV fluid + phenylephrine/ephedrine), accidental dural puncture (1%), post-dural puncture headache, patchy/unilateral block, motor block at high concentrations</li></ul><h4>2. Combined Spinal-Epidural (CSE)</h4><ul><li>Needle-through-needle technique: spinal injected first \u2192 immediate analgesia \u2192 epidural catheter placed</li><li>Intrathecal: Fentanyl 15-25 mcg \u00b1 bupivacaine 2.5 mg \u2192 profound analgesia onset in 5 minutes</li><li>Then epidural maintained as above</li><li>Advantage: fastest onset of all neuraxial techniques \u2014 ideal for advanced labour</li><li>Risk: fetal bradycardia from rapid pain relief \u2192 \u2193 maternal catecholamines \u2192 uterine hyperstimulation \u2192 give terbutaline 0.25 mg SC if sustained bradycardia</li></ul><h4>3. Dural Puncture Epidural (DPE)</h4><ul><li>Spinal needle punctures dura but no drug injected \u2192 epidural catheter placed</li><li>Better sacral spread than standard epidural, faster onset, less unilateral block</li><li>Newer technique \u2014 gaining popularity</li></ul><h4>D. Regional Nerve Blocks</h4><ul><li><strong>Pudendal nerve block:</strong> Bilateral transvaginal injection of 10 mL 1% lignocaine near ischial spine \u2192 blocks S2-S4 \u2192 perineal analgesia only (second stage + episiotomy repair). Does NOT cover first stage</li><li><strong>Paracervical block:</strong> Local around cervix \u2192 blocks uterine pain (first stage). Risk: fetal bradycardia (vasoconstriction of uterine arteries). Largely abandoned</li></ul><h4>E. Inhaled Analgesia</h4><ul><li><strong>Entonox (50% N2O + 50% O2):</strong> Self-administered by patient via mask at start of each contraction. Takes 30-45 seconds to act \u2014 must inhale before contraction peak. Provides modest analgesia (reduces VAS by ~2-3 cm). Can cause dizziness, nausea, light-headedness. Safe for mother and baby (no neonatal accumulation). Useful as bridge while epidural being sited</li></ul><div class='viva-box'><div class='viva-head'> Viva Corner</div><div class='viva-item'><div class='viva-q'>Does epidural analgesia increase CS rate?</div><div class='viva-a'>No \u2014 large RCTs (ASA, COMET trial) show epidural does NOT increase CS rate. It may slightly prolong first and second stage but does not affect mode of delivery when low-concentration bupivacaine is used.</div></div><div class='viva-item'><div class='viva-q'>Why is remifentanil PCA superior to pethidine?</div><div class='viva-a'>Remifentanil is ultra-short acting (half-life 1-3 min) \u2014 metabolised by plasma esterases, not accumulated in neonatal circulation. Pethidine has active metabolite norpethidine (6-23 hour half-life) that causes neonatal seizures.</div></div><div class='viva-item'><div class='viva-q'>When would you choose CSE over epidural alone?</div><div class='viva-a'>Advanced labour (cervix &gt;7 cm) \u2014 need immediate analgesia. Intrathecal fentanyl works in 5 minutes vs epidural 15-20 minutes. Also if patient unable to stay still for prolonged epidural sitting period.</div></div></div><div class='pearl'><div class='pearl-head'>\u2b50 Examiner's Pearl</div><p>Four points that make this answer complete: <strong>(1)</strong> Epidural \u2014 gold standard, explain PCEA vs PIEB. <strong>(2)</strong> Remifentanil PCA \u2014 best systemic option with <strong>mandatory SpO2 monitoring and 1:1 nursing</strong>. <strong>(3)</strong> CSE \u2014 fastest onset, best for advanced labour. <strong>(4)</strong> Epidural does NOT increase CS rate \u2014 state this confidently. These four cover the examiner's likely sub-questions.</p></div>";
ANSWERS["38"]="<h3>Robot-Assisted Radical Prostatectomy (RARP) \u2014 Anaesthetic Considerations [10]</h3><div class='hl hl-info'><span class='hl-icon'></span><div class='hl-body'><div class='hl-title'>Unique Triple Challenge</div><p><strong>(1)</strong> Steep Trendelenburg position (30-45\u00b0) for 3-5 hours. <strong>(2)</strong> Prolonged CO2 pneumoperitoneum (12-15 mmHg). <strong>(3)</strong> No patient access once robot is docked \u2014 surgical emergency requires undocking (2-3 minutes). These three factors combine to create unique physiological stresses.</p></div></div><h4>A. Preoperative Considerations</h4><ul><li>Typical patient: male 60-75 years, often with comorbidities (CAD, COPD, DM, HTN)</li><li><strong>Screen for:</strong> Glaucoma (IOP rises markedly in Trendelenburg \u2014 contraindication to RARP in uncontrolled glaucoma), OSA (sedation risk post-op), morbid obesity (FRC reduction + access worsened), cervical spine disease (neck position), GORD (aspiration risk)</li><li>Discuss: post-op pain (shoulder-tip referred pain from CO2 very common), catheter for 7-10 days</li><li>Cardiac: stress ECG if symptoms; echo if LV dysfunction suspected</li><li>Ensure IV access sites accessible after robot docking \u2014 place wide-bore cannula in antecubital fossa</li></ul><h4>B. Intraoperative \u2014 Core Anaesthetic Considerations</h4><h4>1. Airway</h4><ul><li>Cuffed ETT mandatory \u2014 LMA contraindicated (high airway pressures in Trendelenburg + pneumoperitoneum; aspiration risk, inadequate seal)</li><li>Secure ETT meticulously with adhesive tape and benzoin \u2014 once robot docked, airway inaccessible</li><li>Check ETT position AFTER final steep Trendelenburg positioning \u2014 head-down advances ETT toward carina, risk of endobronchial intubation</li></ul><h4>2. Ventilation</h4><ul><li>Lung-protective: TV 6-8 mL/kg IBW, PEEP 5-8 cmH2O (higher PEEP needed \u2014 Trendelenburg + pneumoperitoneum \u2193 FRC by 30-40%)</li><li>RR adjusted to maintain EtCO2 35-40 mmHg \u2014 CO2 absorbed from peritoneum \u2192 hypercapnia \u2192 \u2191 RR needed</li><li>Peak airway pressure will be HIGH (25-35 cmH2O) \u2014 inform surgeon, accept if Pplat &lt;30 cmH2O</li><li>Recruitment manoeuvre at start of Trendelenburg \u2014 40 cmH2O \u00d7 30 sec \u2014 then PEEP to prevent atelectasis</li></ul><h4>3. Cardiovascular Effects of Position + Pneumoperitoneum</h4><table><thead><tr><th>Effect</th><th>Mechanism</th><th>Management</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>\u2191 Venous return initially</td><td>Legs up + abdominal pressure pushes blood cranially</td><td>Can cause pulmonary oedema in poor LV \u2014 restrict fluids</td></tr><tr><td>\u2191 SVR and MAP</td><td>CO2 \u2192 catecholamine release + direct vasoconstriction</td><td>Titrate anaesthetic depth; vasodilators if needed</td></tr><tr><td>\u2191 ICP and IOP</td><td>Venous congestion from head-down</td><td>Avoid in glaucoma; mention IOP monitoring</td></tr><tr><td>Vagal bradycardia</td><td>Peritoneal stretch at insufflation</td><td>Atropine ready; warn surgeon to slow insufflation</td></tr><tr><td>Facial/tongue oedema</td><td>Venous pooling in head</td><td>Assess airway oedema before extubation</td></tr></tbody></table><h4>4. Positioning Complications</h4><ul><li><strong>Brachial plexus:</strong> Arms tucked at sides or abducted \u2014 risk if excessive stretch. Arms at sides preferred; supinate forearms; pad ulnar groove</li><li><strong>Eye care:</strong> Tape eyelids shut, protective goggles \u2014 corneal abrasion common, ischaemic optic neuropathy (PION) rare but catastrophic, especially with prolonged hypotension + steep Trendelenburg</li><li><strong>Compartment syndrome:</strong> Lower legs in compression sleeves for prolonged procedures \u2014 rare but reported</li><li><strong>Shoulder braces:</strong> Risk of brachial plexus stretch injury \u2014 avoid; use anti-slip mattress instead</li></ul><h4>5. Access and Monitoring</h4><ul><li>Invasive arterial line (radial) \u2014 beat-to-beat BP, serial ABG (EtCO2 underestimates PaCO2 by 3-5 mmHg in Trendelenburg)</li><li>Two large-bore IV \u2014 arms may be padded and inaccessible after docking</li><li>BIS/entropy for depth of anaesthesia</li><li>Urinary catheter placed by surgeon as part of operation</li></ul><h4>6. Emergency Planning (Robot Docked = No Access)</h4><div class='hl hl-danger'><span class='hl-icon'></span><div class='hl-body'><div class='hl-title'>Pre-Dock Checklist \u2014 Before Robot is Locked In</div><p>Before robot docked: <strong>(1)</strong> All IV access functional and accessible. <strong>(2)</strong> Emergency drugs drawn \u2014 adrenaline, atropine, vasopressors, labetalol. <strong>(3)</strong> External defibrillator pads applied. <strong>(4)</strong> ETT position confirmed. <strong>(5)</strong> Surgeon briefed on undocking protocol for emergency. Any cardiac arrest: <strong>robot undocked immediately \u2192 CPR</strong>.</p></div></div><h4>7. Fluid Management</h4><ul><li><strong>Restrictive strategy</strong> \u2014 excessive fluids worsen head/airway oedema in prolonged Trendelenburg</li><li>Target: UO 0.5 mL/kg/hr (difficult to measure during operation \u2014 ureter may be temporarily ligated)</li><li>Use vasopressors (phenylephrine/noradrenaline) for hypotension rather than fluid boluses</li><li>Transfusion trigger: Hb &lt;7 g/dL (RARP usually low blood loss &lt;200 mL)</li></ul><h4>C. Postoperative Considerations</h4><ul><li><strong>Airway oedema:</strong> Cuff leak test before extubation \u2014 deflate cuff, listen for leak. No leak \u2192 significant supraglottic oedema \u2192 delay extubation. Nebulised adrenaline 0.5 mL of 1:1000 in 2 mL NS may help</li><li><strong>PONV:</strong> Very common \u2014 dual antiemetic prophylaxis (ondansetron + dexamethasone) given intraoperatively</li><li><strong>Analgesia:</strong> Multimodal \u2014 paracetamol + NSAIDs (if renal function adequate) + port-site infiltration. Shoulder-tip pain (CO2 diaphragm irritation) responds to NSAIDs + elevation of head</li><li><strong>DVT prophylaxis:</strong> High risk \u2014 prolonged immobility + pelvic dissection + cancer. LMWH from 12 hours post-op, TED stockings, early ambulation</li><li>Urinary catheter remains 7-10 days \u2014 bladder-urethral anastomosis healing</li></ul><div class='pearl'><div class='pearl-head'>\u2b50 Examiner's Pearl</div><p>Four RARP-specific points: <strong>(1)</strong> Check ETT position AFTER Trendelenburg \u2014 advances toward carina. <strong>(2)</strong> Robot docked = no access \u2014 pre-dock checklist mandatory. <strong>(3)</strong> Restrictive fluids + vasopressors (not fluid boluses) for haemodynamics. <strong>(4)</strong> Assess for airway oedema before extubation (cuff leak test). These four are what separate a good RARP answer from a generic anaesthesia answer.</p></div>";
ANSWERS["39"]="<h3>Capnography &#x2014; Principles, Waveform Analysis and Clinical Applications [10]</h3>\n\n<div class='hl hl-info'><span class='hl-icon'>&#x1F4CB;</span><div class='hl-body'><div class='hl-title'>Definition</div>\n<p><strong>Capnography</strong> is the continuous measurement and graphical display of CO2 concentration in exhaled gases as a function of time or volume. The numerical value of end-tidal CO2 (EtCO2) is called <strong>capnometry</strong>. It is one of the most important monitors in anaesthesia &#x2014; the ASA mandates capnography for all patients receiving general anaesthesia.</p></div></div>\n\n<h3>1. Principles of CO2 Measurement</h3>\n\n<h4>A. Infrared Spectroscopy (Most Common)</h4>\n<ul>\n<li>CO2 absorbs infrared light at wavelength <strong>4.26 micrometres</strong></li>\n<li>IR light passed through gas sample &#x2014; amount absorbed proportional to CO2 concentration</li>\n<li>Beer-Lambert Law: Absorbance = concentration x path length x molar absorptivity</li>\n<li>Two types:\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Mainstream:</strong> Sensor placed directly in breathing circuit at Y-piece. No sampling delay. Heavy, adds dead space</li>\n<li><strong>Sidestream:</strong> Gas aspirated from circuit via fine tube to analyser. Lighter, cheaper. 2-3 sec delay. Risk of blockage with water</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h4>B. Other Methods</h4>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Mass spectrometry:</strong> Most accurate, measures all gases. Expensive, used in research</li>\n<li><strong>Colorimetric:</strong> Qualitative only. pH-sensitive indicator changes colour. Used for ETT confirmation in emergency/transport</li>\n<li><strong>Raman spectroscopy:</strong> Accurate, measures all anaesthetic gases simultaneously</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h3>2. Normal Capnogram Waveform</h3>\n\n<div class='mech-box'><span class='ht'>NORMAL CAPNOGRAM &#x2014; 4 PHASES:</span>\n\n<span class='ht'>Phase I (A-B):</span>   Inspiratory baseline = 0 mmHg\n                   Dead space gas (no CO2)\n                   Normally flat at zero\n\n<span class='ht'>Phase II (B-C):</span>  Expiratory upstroke\n                   Rapid rise as alveolar gas mixes with dead space gas\n                   Normally steep slope at 45 degrees\n\n<span class='ht'>Phase III (C-D):</span> Alveolar plateau\n                   Nearly horizontal &#x2014; pure alveolar gas\n                   Slight upslope (0-1 mmHg) is normal\n                   Point D = EtCO2 (end-tidal CO2)\n                   Normal EtCO2 = 35-45 mmHg\n\n<span class='ht'>Phase IV (D-E):</span>  Inspiratory downstroke\n                   Rapid fall to zero as fresh gas inhaled\n                   Normally vertical\n\n<span class='ht'>ALPHA ANGLE (B-C-D):</span>  Between phase II and III &#x2014; normally 100-110 degrees\n<span class='ht'>BETA ANGLE (D-E-A):</span>   Between phase III and IV &#x2014; normally 90 degrees</div>\n\n<h3>3. PaCO2 vs EtCO2 Gradient</h3>\n<ul>\n<li>Normal PaCO2 - EtCO2 gradient = <strong>2-5 mmHg</strong> (PaCO2 higher)</li>\n<li>EtCO2 underestimates PaCO2 because dead space gas dilutes alveolar CO2</li>\n<li>Increased gradient occurs with: increased dead space (PE, low cardiac output, COPD, steep Trendelenburg)</li>\n<li>Decreased/reversed gradient: left heart failure (pulmonary oedema dilutes alveolar CO2 from below)</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h3>4. Abnormal Capnogram Patterns</h3>\n<table><thead><tr><th>Pattern</th><th>Appearance</th><th>Cause</th></tr></thead>\n<tbody>\n<tr><td><strong>EtCO2 = 0 suddenly</strong></td><td>Flat line at zero</td><td>Oesophageal intubation, circuit disconnect, cardiac arrest, apnoea</td></tr>\n<tr><td><strong>Elevated EtCO2</strong></td><td>Waveform raised</td><td>Hypoventilation, rebreathing, MH, tourniquet release, NaHCO3 injection</td></tr>\n<tr><td><strong>Decreased EtCO2</strong></td><td>Waveform lowered</td><td>Hyperventilation, hypothermia, PE, cardiac arrest, severe haemorrhage</td></tr>\n<tr><td><strong>Shark fin pattern</strong></td><td>Slanted plateau, no clear Phase III</td><td>Bronchospasm, COPD &#x2014; uneven emptying of lung units</td></tr>\n<tr><td><strong>Curare cleft</strong></td><td>Notch in plateau</td><td>Inadequate neuromuscular blockade &#x2014; patient attempting to breathe</td></tr>\n<tr><td><strong>Elevated baseline</strong></td><td>Above zero baseline</td><td>CO2 rebreathing &#x2014; exhausted soda lime, faulty expiratory valve</td></tr>\n<tr><td><strong>Gradual increase</strong></td><td>Slowly rising EtCO2</td><td>Malignant hyperthermia &#x2014; massive CO2 production. EARLIEST sign of MH</td></tr>\n<tr><td><strong>Cleft in inspiration</strong></td><td>Notch in downstroke</td><td>Patient breathing against ventilator, light anaesthesia</td></tr>\n<tr><td><strong>Two-hump camel</strong></td><td>Double plateau</td><td>Cardiac oscillations, right mainstem intubation</td></tr>\n</tbody></table>\n\n<h3>5. Clinical Applications</h3>\n\n<h4>A. Confirm ETT Placement</h4>\n<div class='hl hl-danger'><span class='hl-icon'>&#x1F6A8;</span><div class='hl-body'><div class='hl-title'>Most Important Application</div>\n<p>Continuous waveform capnography is the <strong>gold standard</strong> for ETT position confirmation. Presence of sustained waveform for &gt;6 breaths = tracheal intubation confirmed. EtCO2 present but waveform disappears = oesophageal intubation (initial CO2 from stomach gas). Colorimetric capnometry alone is insufficient &#x2014; can be falsely positive with stomach CO2. After cardiac arrest, low EtCO2 despite tracheal intubation is common due to low pulmonary blood flow.</p></div></div>\n\n<h4>B. Monitor Ventilation</h4>\n<ul>\n<li>Guide ventilator settings &#x2014; target EtCO2 35-40 mmHg in normal patients</li>\n<li>Neuroanaesthesia: target EtCO2 30-35 mmHg (mild hyperventilation for ICP control)</li>\n<li>COPD: allow permissive hypercapnia &#x2014; target EtCO2 50-60 mmHg</li>\n<li>Steep Trendelenburg: EtCO2 underestimates PaCO2 more &#x2014; check ABG</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h4>C. Cardiac Output and CPR</h4>\n<ul>\n<li>EtCO2 reflects pulmonary blood flow = indirect cardiac output monitor</li>\n<li>Sudden drop in EtCO2 = pulmonary embolism, cardiac arrest, severe haemorrhage</li>\n<li>During CPR: EtCO2 &gt;10 mmHg = adequate chest compressions</li>\n<li>EtCO2 &gt;40 mmHg during CPR = ROSC (Return of Spontaneous Circulation) &#x2014; often before pulse palpable</li>\n<li>EtCO2 persistently &lt;10 mmHg after 20 min CPR = poor prognosis</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h4>D. Early Warning of Complications</h4>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Malignant Hyperthermia:</strong> Rising EtCO2 is EARLIEST sign (before temperature rise)</li>\n<li><strong>Pulmonary embolism:</strong> Sudden drop in EtCO2 + increased PaCO2-EtCO2 gradient</li>\n<li><strong>Venous air embolism:</strong> Sudden drop in EtCO2</li>\n<li><strong>Bronchospasm:</strong> Shark fin capnogram + rising EtCO2</li>\n<li><strong>Circuit disconnect:</strong> EtCO2 drops to zero immediately</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h4>E. Procedural Sedation Monitoring</h4>\n<ul>\n<li>Capnography detects apnoea 60-120 seconds BEFORE SpO2 falls (especially on supplemental O2)</li>\n<li>Essential for non-intubated patients receiving sedation</li>\n<li>Detects airway obstruction before hypoxia develops</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h4>F. Weaning from Ventilation</h4>\n<ul>\n<li>Trend of EtCO2 guides weaning decisions</li>\n<li>Rising EtCO2 during spontaneous breathing trial = fatigue, not ready to wean</li>\n</ul>\n\n<div class='drug-grid'>\n<div class='drug-card dc-teal'><div class='drug-name'>Normal EtCO2</div><div class='drug-dose'>35-45 mmHg</div><div class='drug-note'>PaCO2 - EtCO2 gradient = 2-5 mmHg. EtCO2 always lower than PaCO2 in normal patients</div></div>\n<div class='drug-card dc-indigo'><div class='drug-name'>Neuroanaesthesia Target</div><div class='drug-dose'>30-35 mmHg</div><div class='drug-note'>Mild hyperventilation causes cerebral vasoconstriction, reduces ICP. Avoid below 30 (cerebral ischaemia)</div></div>\n<div class='drug-card dc-amber'><div class='drug-name'>CPR Target</div><div class='drug-dose'>&gt;10 mmHg during CPR</div><div class='drug-note'>EtCO2 &gt;40 = ROSC. &lt;10 after 20 min = poor prognosis. Guides compression quality</div></div>\n<div class='drug-card dc-rose'><div class='drug-name'>MH Warning</div><div class='drug-dose'>Rising EtCO2 = EARLIEST sign</div><div class='drug-note'>Temperature rises later. Rising EtCO2 during anaesthesia = consider MH. Act immediately</div></div>\n</div>\n\n<div class='viva-box'><div class='viva-head'>Viva Corner</div>\n<div class='viva-item'><div class='viva-q'>What are the 4 phases of a normal capnogram?</div><div class='viva-a'>Phase I (A-B): Inspiratory baseline at zero - dead space gas with no CO2. Phase II (B-C): Expiratory upstroke - rapid rise as alveolar gas emerges. Phase III (C-D): Alveolar plateau - nearly flat, represents pure alveolar CO2. Point D is EtCO2 (normal 35-45 mmHg). Phase IV (D-E): Inspiratory downstroke - rapid fall to zero as fresh gas enters. Alpha angle between Phase II and III = 100-110 degrees. Beta angle between Phase III and IV = 90 degrees.</div></div>\n<div class='viva-item'><div class='viva-q'>What is the shark fin pattern and what causes it?</div><div class='viva-a'>The shark fin pattern shows a slanted, prolonged Phase III without a clear alveolar plateau. Instead of a flat plateau, there is a continuous upward slope giving a shark fin appearance. Caused by bronchospasm or COPD where different lung units empty at different rates - fast units empty first (low CO2), slow obstructed units empty later (high CO2), giving a continuously rising plateau. Treat underlying bronchospasm with salbutamol, deepen anaesthesia.</div></div>\n<div class='viva-item'><div class='viva-q'>How does capnography help during CPR?</div><div class='viva-a'>During CPR, EtCO2 reflects pulmonary blood flow which depends on cardiac output generated by chest compressions. EtCO2 greater than 10 mmHg indicates effective chest compressions. Sudden rise in EtCO2 above 40 mmHg indicates ROSC - often seen before pulse is palpable, allowing immediate recognition of ROSC. EtCO2 persistently below 10 mmHg after 20 minutes of CPR with optimal technique is a poor prognostic sign. Also confirms ETT position during resuscitation.</div></div>\n<div class='viva-item'><div class='viva-q'>Why is capnography superior to pulse oximetry for detecting hypoventilation?</div><div class='viva-a'>SpO2 is a late indicator of hypoventilation especially when supplemental oxygen is being given. A patient breathing 2L/min O2 can have significant CO2 retention (EtCO2 60-70 mmHg) while SpO2 remains 98-99% for 60-120 seconds. Capnography detects apnoea and hypoventilation immediately (within one breath cycle) by showing loss of waveform or rising EtCO2. This makes capnography mandatory for procedural sedation where oxygen is routinely given.</div></div>\n</div>\n\n<div class='pearl'><div class='pearl-head'>Examiner's Pearl</div>\n<p><strong>(1)</strong> IR spectroscopy at 4.26 micrometres - Beer Lambert law. <strong>(2)</strong> 4 phases - know each one. Shark fin = bronchospasm. Curare cleft = inadequate NMB. Elevated baseline = CO2 rebreathing. <strong>(3)</strong> EtCO2 = 0 suddenly = oesophageal intubation / disconnect / cardiac arrest. <strong>(4)</strong> MH: rising EtCO2 is EARLIEST sign. <strong>(5)</strong> ROSC during CPR: EtCO2 suddenly rises above 40 mmHg. <strong>(6)</strong> EtCO2 always 2-5 mmHg LESS than PaCO2 in normal patients.</p>\n<p style='margin-top:10px'><strong>References:</strong> Bhavani-Shankar K et al. Capnometry and Anaesthesia (Can J Anaesth 1992;39:617-632). Kodali BS. Capnography outside the operating rooms (Anesthesiology 2013;118:192-201). Morgan and Mikhail Clinical Anesthesiology 6th Ed Chapter 6. Miller's Anaesthesia 9th Ed Chapter 41. ASA Standards for Basic Anesthetic Monitoring 2020.</p></div>";
ANSWERS["40"]="<h3>Safety Features in Modern Anaesthesia Machine [10]</h3>\n\n<div class='hl hl-info'><span class='hl-icon'>&#x1F4CB;</span><div class='hl-body'><div class='hl-title'>Overview</div>\n<p>The anaesthesia machine (workstation) is one of the most complex pieces of medical equipment. Numerous safety features prevent the delivery of hypoxic gas mixtures, incorrect vapour concentrations, and other catastrophic errors. Understanding these features is essential for safe practice and for the pre-use check (machine checkout procedure).</p></div></div>\n\n<h3>1. Oxygen Supply Safety Features</h3>\n\n<h4>A. Pin Index Safety System (PISS)</h4>\n<ul>\n<li>Prevents wrong cylinder being connected to wrong yoke</li>\n<li>Each gas has unique pin configuration on cylinder valve</li>\n<li>O2 = pins at position 2 and 5. N2O = 3 and 5. Air = 1 and 5</li>\n<li>Pins on yoke fit only into corresponding holes on cylinder</li>\n<li>Prevents N2O cylinder being connected to O2 yoke</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h4>B. Diameter Index Safety System (DISS)</h4>\n<ul>\n<li>For pipeline connections (not cylinders)</li>\n<li>Each gas has unique diameter and thread for pipeline connection</li>\n<li>Prevents wrong pipeline being connected to wrong machine inlet</li>\n<li>Colour coded: O2 = white (India/UK) or green (USA). N2O = blue. Air = yellow</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h4>C. Oxygen Failure Protection Device (OFPD) / Fail-Safe Valve</h4>\n<ul>\n<li>Automatically cuts off or proportionally reduces N2O and other gases if O2 pressure falls</li>\n<li>Triggered when O2 pressure falls below threshold (typically 30 psi)</li>\n<li>DOES NOT guarantee hypoxia prevention &#x2014; only cuts N2O when O2 fails</li>\n<li>Does NOT protect against operator error (setting wrong flowmeter)</li>\n<li>Older machines: pressure sensor cut-off (Tec series). Newer: electronic proportioning</li>\n</ul>\n\n<div class='hl hl-danger'><span class='hl-icon'>&#x1F6A8;</span><div class='hl-body'><div class='hl-title'>Oxygen Alarm</div>\n<p>When O2 pipeline pressure falls: <strong>(1) Audible alarm</strong> (whistle/electronic) sounds automatically. <strong>(2) OFPD cuts N2O supply.</strong> <strong>(3) Hypoxic guard activates.</strong> The oxygen failure alarm must be: battery-powered (not dependent on pipeline O2), non-silenceable for first 7 seconds (ISO standard), and audible at 65 dB from 1 metre. Reserve O2 cylinder must be checked and kept full before every list.</p></div></div>\n\n<h3>2. Hypoxic Guard / N2O-O2 Proportioning System</h3>\n<ul>\n<li>Prevents delivery of hypoxic gas mixtures by mechanically linking O2 and N2O flowmeters</li>\n<li>Ensures minimum O2 concentration of <strong>25% in fresh gas flow</strong> (some systems 30%)</li>\n<li><strong>Link-25 system (Ohmeda):</strong> Chain and sprocket links O2 and N2O rotameters. If O2 is turned down, N2O automatically reduces proportionally</li>\n<li><strong>Oxygen Ratio Monitor Controller (ORMC - North American Drager):</strong> Pneumatic proportioning device</li>\n<li>Limitation: Does NOT prevent delivery of hypoxic mixture if third gas (air, helium) is also flowing</li>\n<li>Does NOT account for oxygen flush being off (patient gets pipeline gas)</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h3>3. Flowmeter Safety Features</h3>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Oxygen flowmeter always positioned DOWNSTREAM (nearest to patient):</strong> If upstream flowmeter leaks, O2 not lost &#x2014; prevents hypoxic mixture reaching patient</li>\n<li>Flowmeter tubes are gas-specific &#x2014; cannot interchange tubes</li>\n<li>Anti-static coating prevents static electricity igniting anaesthetic gases</li>\n<li>Flow control valves: needle valves with detent for O2 (different feel from other gases)</li>\n<li>O2 flow control knob: larger, protruding, different shape (fluted) &#x2014; identifiable by touch in dark</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h3>4. Vaporiser Safety Features</h3>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Selectatec/Selectatec Plus interlock system:</strong> Only one vaporiser can be turned on at a time. Prevents simultaneous delivery of two volatile agents</li>\n<li><strong>Agent-specific filling systems:</strong> Keyed Filling Device (KFD) &#x2014; each agent bottle has unique key fitting its vaporiser filler port. Prevents wrong agent filling wrong vaporiser</li>\n<li>Colour coding: Sevoflurane = yellow. Isoflurane = purple. Desflurane = blue. Halothane = red</li>\n<li>Vaporisers are temperature-compensated &#x2014; output accurate despite temperature changes</li>\n<li>Desflurane Tec-6: electrically heated pressurised vaporiser &#x2014; has additional safety: low agent level alarm, power failure alarm, tilt alarm</li>\n<li>Anti-spill mechanism: prevents liquid agent entering back bar if machine tilted</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h3>5. Breathing Circuit Safety Features</h3>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Pressure relief valve (APL valve / pop-off valve):</strong> Limits circuit pressure to 70 cmH2O. Prevents barotrauma</li>\n<li><strong>Airway pressure alarm:</strong> High pressure alarm (barotrauma risk), low pressure alarm (disconnect), sustained pressure alarm</li>\n<li><strong>Disconnect alarm:</strong> Triggered if pressure does not rise with each ventilator breath</li>\n<li><strong>Oxygen analyser:</strong> Mandatory in circle system. Measures FiO2 continuously. Alarms if FiO2 falls below set threshold (usually 28%)</li>\n<li><strong>CO2 absorber:</strong> Prevents CO2 rebreathing. Colour change indicator (white to purple/violet when exhausted)</li>\n<li>One-way valves (inspiratory and expiratory): ensure unidirectional gas flow</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h3>6. Ventilator Safety Features</h3>\n<ul>\n<li>High pressure alarm: circuit obstruction, kinked ETT, bronchospasm</li>\n<li>Low pressure alarm: circuit disconnect</li>\n<li>Low volume alarm: inadequate tidal volume delivery (leak)</li>\n<li>Apnoea alarm: no spontaneous breathing detected</li>\n<li>Battery backup: continues monitoring if power fails</li>\n<li>Manual ventilation override: hand ventilation possible if ventilator fails</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h3>7. Machine Checkout (Pre-use Check)</h3>\n<div class='mech-box'><span class='ht'>AAGBI / ASA PRE-USE CHECKLIST:</span>\n\n<span class='ht'>DAILY CHECKS:</span>\n1. Check O2 cylinder pressure (at least half full as backup)\n2. Check pipeline connections (firmly seated, correct gas)\n3. Flow control valves closed, vaporisers off\n4. Check oxygen analyser calibration\n5. Check CO2 absorber (colour, granule integrity)\n6. Check breathing system integrity (pressure test)\n7. Check APL valve function\n8. Check ventilator function\n9. Check suction (working)\n10. Check emergency drugs available\n\n<span class='ht'>BEFORE EACH CASE:</span>\nCheck circuit integrity, ETT/LMA available,\ndifficult airway equipment available,\ndrug doses calculated for patient weight</div>\n\n<div class='viva-box'><div class='viva-head'>Viva Corner</div>\n<div class='viva-item'><div class='viva-q'>What is the Pin Index Safety System and why is it important?</div><div class='viva-a'>The Pin Index Safety System (PISS) prevents wrong cylinders being attached to wrong yokes on the anaesthesia machine. Each medical gas cylinder has a unique pattern of holes at the valve block, and the corresponding yoke has matching pins. O2 = pins 2 and 5, N2O = 3 and 5, Air = 1 and 5. If someone accidentally tried to connect an N2O cylinder to the O2 yoke, the pins would not fit. This prevents the potentially fatal error of delivering N2O instead of O2. The system was introduced after cases of accidental O2 deprivation from incorrect cylinder connections.</div></div>\n<div class='viva-item'><div class='viva-q'>Why is O2 flowmeter positioned last (downstream) in the rotameter bank?</div><div class='viva-a'>If O2 flowmeter is positioned upstream (first) and any downstream flowmeter leaks, O2 would be lost into the atmosphere through the leak before reaching the patient, creating a hypoxic mixture. By placing O2 downstream (last, nearest to the back bar exit), even if upstream flowmeters (N2O, air) leak, O2 is added downstream of the leak and reaches the patient safely. This simple design feature prevents hypoxic mixtures from leaking flowmeters.</div></div>\n<div class='viva-item'><div class='viva-q'>What does the Oxygen Failure Protection Device do?</div><div class='viva-a'>The OFPD (also called fail-safe valve) automatically cuts off or proportionally reduces N2O (and other anaesthetic gas) supply when O2 pipeline pressure falls below a threshold (typically 30 psi). This prevents pure N2O from being delivered when O2 fails. However, it has important limitations: (1) It does NOT guarantee minimum O2 concentration - only cuts N2O when O2 pressure fails. (2) It does NOT protect against operator error of turning O2 flowmeter to zero. (3) It does NOT cut off volatile agent delivery. The hypoxic guard/proportioning system provides additional protection against low O2 concentration in fresh gas flow.</div></div>\n</div>\n\n<div class='pearl'><div class='pearl-head'>Examiner's Pearl</div>\n<p><strong>(1)</strong> PISS = cylinder safety. DISS = pipeline safety. Both prevent wrong gas connections. <strong>(2)</strong> OFPD cuts N2O when O2 pressure fails &#x2014; does NOT prevent operator error. <strong>(3)</strong> Hypoxic guard ensures minimum 25% O2 in FGF by linking N2O and O2 flowmeters. <strong>(4)</strong> O2 flowmeter ALWAYS downstream (last) in rotameter bank. <strong>(5)</strong> Selectatec interlock = only one vaporiser on at a time. KFD = agent-specific filling. <strong>(6)</strong> O2 analyser mandatory in circle system &#x2014; monitors FiO2 continuously.</p>\n<p style='margin-top:10px'><strong>References:</strong> Dorsch JA, Dorsch SE. Understanding Anaesthesia Equipment 5th Ed. Boumphrey S, Marshall N. Understanding vaporisers (BJA CEACCP 2011;11:199-203). Morgan and Mikhail Clinical Anesthesiology 6th Ed Chapter 4. Miller's Anaesthesia 9th Ed Chapter 25. AAGBI Checking Anaesthetic Equipment Guidelines 2012.</p></div>";
ANSWERS["41"]="<h3>Hypoxic Pulmonary Vasoconstriction &#x2014; Mechanism, Factors and Anaesthetic Implications [10]</h3>\n\n<div class='hl hl-info'><span class='hl-icon'>&#x1F4CB;</span><div class='hl-body'><div class='hl-title'>Definition</div>\n<p><strong>Hypoxic Pulmonary Vasoconstriction (HPV)</strong> is a local, protective reflex of the pulmonary vasculature in which alveolar hypoxia causes constriction of the adjacent pulmonary arterioles. This diverts blood flow away from poorly ventilated (hypoxic) lung regions towards better ventilated regions, thereby optimising ventilation-perfusion (V/Q) matching and maintaining systemic oxygenation. It is unique to the pulmonary circulation &#x2014; systemic vessels vasodilate in hypoxia.</p></div></div>\n\n<h3>1. Mechanism of HPV</h3>\n\n<div class='mech-box'><span class='ht'>TRIGGER:</span> Alveolar PO2 (PAO2) &lt; 70 mmHg is primary trigger\n         Mixed venous PO2 is secondary trigger (less important)\n         NOT arterial PO2\n\n<span class='ht'>SENSOR:</span> Smooth muscle cells of small pulmonary arterioles (precapillary)\n\n<span class='ht'>MEDIATORS (Inhibitors of vasodilation = cause vasoconstriction):</span>\n- INHIBITION of K+ channels &#x2192; membrane depolarisation\n- Opening of voltage-gated Ca2+ channels &#x2192; Ca2+ influx\n- Smooth muscle contraction &#x2192; vasoconstriction\n\n<span class='ht'>VASODILATORS (Reduced in hypoxia):</span>\n- Nitric Oxide (NO) - most important\n- Prostacyclin (PGI2)\n\n<span class='ht'>VASOCONSTRICTORS (Increased in hypoxia):</span>\n- Endothelin-1\n- Thromboxane A2\n- Reactive Oxygen Species (ROS)\n\n<span class='ht'>BIPHASIC RESPONSE:</span>\nPhase 1 (mins): Rapid onset &#x2014; K+ channel inhibition\nPhase 2 (hours): Sustained &#x2014; gene expression changes</div>\n\n<h3>2. Physiological Significance</h3>\n<ul>\n<li>Optimises V/Q matching by redirecting blood from hypoxic to normoxic lung units</li>\n<li>Maintains PaO2 during one-lung ventilation, pneumonia, atelectasis</li>\n<li>Without HPV: shunting would be much greater, causing severe hypoxaemia</li>\n<li>HPV accounts for 50% of the V/Q matching in normal lung</li>\n<li>Magnitude: reduces blood flow to hypoxic segment by 50-60%</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h3>3. Factors Affecting HPV</h3>\n\n<h4>A. Factors that INHIBIT HPV (Worsen oxygenation)</h4>\n<table><thead><tr><th>Factor</th><th>Mechanism</th><th>Clinical Significance</th></tr></thead>\n<tbody>\n<tr><td><strong>Volatile anaesthetic agents</strong></td><td>Direct smooth muscle relaxation, increase NO</td><td>ALL inhibit HPV dose-dependently. Isoflurane &gt; Sevoflurane &gt; Desflurane. At 1 MAC, reduces HPV by ~30%</td></tr>\n<tr><td><strong>Vasodilators</strong></td><td>Dilate pulmonary vessels non-selectively</td><td>SNP, GTN, calcium channel blockers, hydralazine, adenosine all inhibit HPV</td></tr>\n<tr><td><strong>High FiO2 to non-dependent lung</strong></td><td>Abolishes hypoxic stimulus</td><td>During OLV: if O2 given to collapsed lung, HPV lost in that segment</td></tr>\n<tr><td><strong>Increased pulmonary artery pressure</strong></td><td>Overdistension of vessels</td><td>Mitral stenosis, ARDS, volume overload</td></tr>\n<tr><td><strong>Hypothermia</strong></td><td>Reduces metabolic activity</td><td>Attenuates HPV</td></tr>\n<tr><td><strong>Alkalosis</strong></td><td>Vasodilation</td><td>Both respiratory and metabolic alkalosis</td></tr>\n<tr><td><strong>Infection/inflammation</strong></td><td>Inflammatory mediators</td><td>Pneumonia, ARDS - HPV blunted</td></tr>\n</tbody></table>\n\n<h4>B. Factors that ENHANCE HPV (Improve V/Q matching)</h4>\n<table><thead><tr><th>Factor</th><th>Clinical Significance</th></tr></thead>\n<tbody>\n<tr><td><strong>Acidosis</strong></td><td>Both respiratory and metabolic acidosis enhance HPV</td></tr>\n<tr><td><strong>Hypercapnia</strong></td><td>Enhances HPV directly</td></tr>\n<tr><td><strong>Vasopressors</strong></td><td>Almitrine (pulmonary vasoconstrictor) specifically enhances HPV &#x2014; used in OLV</td></tr>\n<tr><td><strong>Propofol/IV anaesthesia</strong></td><td>TIVA preserves HPV better than volatile agents</td></tr>\n<tr><td><strong>Low PAP</strong></td><td>Normal pulmonary artery pressure allows HPV to be effective</td></tr>\n</tbody></table>\n\n<h3>4. HPV and One-Lung Ventilation (OLV)</h3>\n\n<div class='hl hl-teal'><span class='hl-icon'>&#x1F4A1;</span><div class='hl-body'><div class='hl-title'>HPV in OLV &#x2014; Most Important Clinical Application</div>\n<p>During OLV for thoracic surgery, the non-dependent (collapsed/operative) lung is not ventilated. HPV constricts vessels in this lung, reducing shunt from ~40% to ~20% of cardiac output. Without HPV, severe hypoxaemia would occur in all OLV cases. TIVA with propofol PRESERVES HPV during OLV &#x2014; this is why some thoracic anaesthetists prefer TIVA over volatile agents for one-lung ventilation. Volatile agents at &gt;1 MAC significantly inhibit HPV and worsen oxygenation during OLV.</p></div></div>\n\n<h4>Management of Hypoxaemia During OLV</h4>\n<ol>\n<li>Increase FiO2 to 1.0</li>\n<li>Check position of double lumen tube (FOB confirmation)</li>\n<li>Apply CPAP 5 cmH2O to non-dependent (collapsed) lung</li>\n<li>Apply PEEP 5 cmH2O to dependent (ventilated) lung</li>\n<li>Reduce volatile agent &#x2014; switch to TIVA if needed</li>\n<li>Almitrine IV (selective pulmonary vasoconstrictor) &#x2014; enhances HPV in collapsed lung</li>\n<li>Intermittent two-lung ventilation if severe hypoxaemia</li>\n<li>Inform surgeon &#x2014; may need to clamp pulmonary artery early</li>\n</ol>\n\n<h3>5. HPV in Disease States</h3>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Pulmonary Hypertension:</strong> Chronic HPV from widespread alveolar hypoxia (COPD, high altitude) causes sustained pulmonary hypertension &#x2014; cor pulmonale</li>\n<li><strong>ARDS:</strong> HPV blunted by inflammatory mediators &#x2014; contributes to severe hypoxaemia</li>\n<li><strong>Pneumonia:</strong> Affected lobe is hypoxic, HPV redirects blood &#x2014; limits hypoxaemia</li>\n<li><strong>Neonatal circulation:</strong> At birth, increase in PaO2 reverses foetal HPV &#x2014; pulmonary vascular resistance drops, ductus arteriosus closes</li>\n</ul>\n\n<div class='drug-grid'>\n<div class='drug-card dc-green'><div class='drug-name'>Propofol (TIVA)</div><div class='drug-dose'>Preferred for OLV</div><div class='drug-note'>Preserves HPV. Better oxygenation during one-lung ventilation vs volatile agents</div></div>\n<div class='drug-card dc-teal'><div class='drug-name'>Almitrine</div><div class='drug-dose'>4-8 mcg/kg/min IV</div><div class='drug-note'>Selective pulmonary vasoconstrictor. Enhances HPV in non-ventilated lung during OLV. Not available in all countries</div></div>\n<div class='drug-card dc-rose'><div class='drug-name'>Volatile agents</div><div class='drug-dose'>Avoid &gt;1 MAC in OLV</div><div class='drug-note'>All volatile agents inhibit HPV dose-dependently. Use minimum effective concentration during thoracic surgery</div></div>\n<div class='drug-card dc-amber'><div class='drug-name'>CPAP to operative lung</div><div class='drug-dose'>5-10 cmH2O</div><div class='drug-note'>Keeps some alveoli open in collapsed lung. Reduces shunt. First intervention for hypoxaemia during OLV</div></div>\n</div>\n\n<div class='viva-box'><div class='viva-head'>Viva Corner</div>\n<div class='viva-item'><div class='viva-q'>What triggers HPV and why is it unique to pulmonary circulation?</div><div class='viva-a'>HPV is triggered by LOW alveolar PO2 (PAO2 below 70 mmHg) - this is the primary sensor. Mixed venous PO2 is a secondary trigger. HPV is unique to pulmonary circulation because in systemic circulation, hypoxia causes vasodilation (to deliver more blood to hypoxic tissues). In pulmonary circulation, the opposite occurs - hypoxia causes vasoconstriction to divert blood away from poorly ventilated areas, protecting oxygenation. The mechanism involves inhibition of K+ channels in pulmonary arteriolar smooth muscle, causing depolarisation, Ca2+ influx, and constriction.</div></div>\n<div class='viva-item'><div class='viva-q'>Why do volatile agents worsen oxygenation during OLV?</div><div class='viva-a'>During OLV, the collapsed lung is hypoxic. Normally HPV would constrict vessels in the collapsed lung, diverting blood to the ventilated lung and reducing shunt to about 20% of cardiac output. Volatile agents directly relax pulmonary arteriolar smooth muscle and increase NO production, inhibiting HPV. At 1 MAC, volatile agents reduce HPV by approximately 30%, allowing more blood to flow through the unventilated collapsed lung, increasing shunt and causing hypoxaemia. TIVA with propofol preserves HPV, which is why many thoracic anaesthetists prefer TIVA for OLV procedures.</div></div>\n<div class='viva-item'><div class='viva-q'>What is the sequence of management for hypoxaemia during OLV?</div><div class='viva-a'>Stepwise approach: (1) Increase FiO2 to 1.0 immediately. (2) Check DLT position with FOB - malposition is common cause. (3) Apply CPAP 5-10 cmH2O to the operative (collapsed) lung via suction catheter. (4) Apply PEEP 5 cmH2O to ventilated lung. (5) Reduce volatile agent concentration or switch to TIVA with propofol. (6) Optimise cardiac output (vasopressors if needed - increases mixed venous O2). (7) Inform surgeon and request intermittent two-lung ventilation if SpO2 below 88%. (8) Consider early pulmonary artery clamping if pneumonectomy.</div></div>\n</div>\n\n<div class='pearl'><div class='pearl-head'>Examiner's Pearl</div>\n<p><strong>(1)</strong> HPV triggered by LOW alveolar PO2 (&lt;70 mmHg) - NOT arterial PO2. <strong>(2)</strong> Unique to pulmonary circulation - systemic vessels vasodilate in hypoxia. <strong>(3)</strong> Mechanism: K+ channel inhibition &#x2192; Ca2+ influx &#x2192; smooth muscle contraction. <strong>(4)</strong> Volatile agents INHIBIT HPV - TIVA preserves it. Key point for OLV. <strong>(5)</strong> HPV reduces shunt from 40% to 20% during OLV - without it, severe hypoxaemia. <strong>(6)</strong> Chronic HPV from COPD/altitude causes pulmonary hypertension and cor pulmonale.</p>\n<p style='margin-top:10px'><strong>References:</strong> Lumb AB. Nunn's Applied Respiratory Physiology 8th Ed. Marshall C, Marshall B. Site and sensitivity for stimulation of HPV (J Appl Physiol 1983;55:711-716). Karzai W, Schwarzkopf K. Hypoxemia during one-lung ventilation (Anesthesiology 2009;110:1402-1411). Morgan and Mikhail Clinical Anesthesiology 6th Ed Chapter 23. Miller's Anaesthesia 9th Ed Chapter 70.</p></div>";
ANSWERS["42"]="<h3>Sevoflurane &#x2014; Pharmacology, Clinical Uses and Advantages [5]</h3>\n\n<div class='hl hl-info'><span class='hl-icon'>&#x1F4CB;</span><div class='hl-body'><div class='hl-title'>Introduction</div>\n<p>Sevoflurane (Ultane, Sojourn) is a <strong>fluorinated methyl isopropyl ether</strong> volatile anaesthetic agent. It has become the most widely used inhalational agent worldwide due to its pleasant odour, rapid onset and offset, haemodynamic stability and suitability for inhalational induction. It replaced halothane in paediatric anaesthesia globally.</p></div></div>\n\n<h4>Physical and Chemical Properties</h4>\n<table><thead><tr><th>Property</th><th>Value</th><th>Clinical Significance</th></tr></thead>\n<tbody>\n<tr><td><strong>Molecular weight</strong></td><td>200 Da</td><td>Fluorinated compound, stable</td></tr>\n<tr><td><strong>Boiling point</strong></td><td>58.5 degrees C</td><td>Standard variable bypass vaporiser (Tec-7)</td></tr>\n<tr><td><strong>Saturated vapour pressure</strong></td><td>157 mmHg at 20 degrees C</td><td>Allows up to ~20% concentration delivery</td></tr>\n<tr><td><strong>Blood:Gas partition coefficient</strong></td><td><strong>0.65</strong></td><td>RAPID onset and offset. Second only to Desflurane (0.42)</td></tr>\n<tr><td><strong>Oil:Gas partition coefficient</strong></td><td>47-54</td><td>Moderate potency</td></tr>\n<tr><td><strong>MAC (in O2)</strong></td><td><strong>2.05% (adults)</strong></td><td>Higher MAC than isoflurane or halothane</td></tr>\n<tr><td><strong>MAC in children (6-12 months)</strong></td><td>3.2%</td><td>Children need higher concentration</td></tr>\n<tr><td><strong>Global Warming Potential</strong></td><td>130</td><td>Much better than Desflurane (2540)</td></tr>\n<tr><td><strong>Odour</strong></td><td>Non-pungent, sweet</td><td>Suitable for inhalational induction</td></tr>\n</tbody></table>\n\n<h4>Pharmacological Effects</h4>\n\n<h4>1. CNS</h4>\n<ul>\n<li>Dose-dependent CNS depression &#x2014; unconsciousness at 1-2 MAC</li>\n<li>Decreases CMRO2 (cerebral metabolic rate) and cerebral blood flow</li>\n<li>At &gt;1.5 MAC: may increase ICP (use with caution in raised ICP)</li>\n<li>No epileptiform activity at clinical doses (unlike enflurane)</li>\n<li>Provides cerebral protection through CMRO2 reduction</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h4>2. Cardiovascular</h4>\n<ul>\n<li>Dose-dependent decrease in SVR and MAP</li>\n<li>Heart rate: minimally increased or unchanged (unlike isoflurane which causes tachycardia)</li>\n<li>Minimal cardiac depression at clinical doses</li>\n<li>Does NOT sensitise myocardium to catecholamines (unlike halothane)</li>\n<li><strong>Coronary vasodilation:</strong> Theoretical coronary steal possible but clinically rare</li>\n<li>Preserves cardiac output better than isoflurane</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h4>3. Respiratory</h4>\n<ul>\n<li>Bronchodilation &#x2014; useful in asthmatic patients</li>\n<li>Dose-dependent respiratory depression &#x2014; reduces tidal volume, increases RR</li>\n<li>Non-pungent &#x2014; does NOT cause breath-holding, coughing, laryngospasm during induction</li>\n<li>Inhibits HPV (dose-dependent) &#x2014; less than isoflurane at equipotent doses</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h4>4. Neuromuscular</h4>\n<ul>\n<li>Potentiates non-depolarising neuromuscular blocking agents</li>\n<li>Reduces dose requirement of NMBs by 30-50%</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h4>5. Renal</h4>\n<ul>\n<li>Compound A concern: reaction with CO2 absorbents at low flows produces Compound A (nephrotoxin in rats)</li>\n<li>No clinically significant nephrotoxicity in humans at recommended flows</li>\n<li>Use FGF &gt;2 L/min to minimise Compound A (manufacturer recommendation)</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h4>Metabolism</h4>\n<ul>\n<li>Metabolised ~3-5% by hepatic CYP2E1</li>\n<li>Produces inorganic fluoride ions (peak at 2 hours, normalises by 24 hours)</li>\n<li>Hepatotoxicity: extremely rare (no significant halothane-type hepatitis)</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h4>Clinical Applications and Advantages</h4>\n<div class='hl hl-teal'><span class='hl-icon'>&#x1F4A1;</span><div class='hl-body'><div class='hl-title'>Key Advantages of Sevoflurane</div>\n<p><strong>(1) Inhalational induction:</strong> Sweet smell, non-irritant &#x2014; ideal for paediatric induction and needle-phobic adults. 8% Sevoflurane in 100% O2 &#x2014; induction in 60-90 seconds. <strong>(2) Rapid emergence:</strong> Low blood:gas coefficient (0.65) &#x2014; faster awakening than isoflurane. <strong>(3) Haemodynamic stability:</strong> Less tachycardia than isoflurane, less cardiac depression than halothane. <strong>(4) Bronchodilation:</strong> Safe in asthma. <strong>(5) Environmental:</strong> GWP 130 vs Desflurane 2540 &#x2014; much more environmentally friendly. <strong>(6) No pungency:</strong> No airway irritation &#x2014; smooth induction and maintenance.</p></div></div>\n\n<div class='drug-grid'>\n<div class='drug-card dc-teal'><div class='drug-name'>Sevoflurane</div><div class='drug-dose'>MAC = 2.05% adults / 3.2% infants</div><div class='drug-note'>Blood:Gas = 0.65. Induction: 6-8%. Maintenance: 1.5-2.5%. Tec-7 vaporiser. Yellow colour coding</div></div>\n<div class='drug-card dc-indigo'><div class='drug-name'>Inhalational induction</div><div class='drug-dose'>8% Sevoflurane in 100% O2</div><div class='drug-note'>Ideal for paediatric patients. Induction in 60-90 seconds. Smooth, non-irritant, pleasant smell</div></div>\n</div>\n\n<div class='viva-box'><div class='viva-head'>Viva Corner</div>\n<div class='viva-item'><div class='viva-q'>What is Compound A and why is it a concern with Sevoflurane?</div><div class='viva-a'>Compound A (fluoromethyl-2,2-difluoro-1-(trifluoromethyl)vinyl ether) is produced when Sevoflurane reacts with CO2 absorbents (especially Baralyme more than Sodalime) at high temperatures and low fresh gas flows. In rats, Compound A causes renal tubular necrosis. However, in humans, no clinically significant nephrotoxicity has been demonstrated even with prolonged low-flow sevoflurane anaesthesia. To minimise Compound A production, manufacturers recommend FGF greater than 2 L/min with Sevoflurane. Modern CO2 absorbents (Amsorb, Dr\u00e4gersorb Free) containing no potassium or sodium hydroxide produce minimal Compound A.</div></div>\n<div class='viva-item'><div class='viva-q'>Why is Sevoflurane preferred over halothane for paediatric induction?</div><div class='viva-a'>Sevoflurane has several advantages over halothane for paediatric induction: (1) Sweet, non-pungent odour - children accept mask more readily. (2) Does NOT sensitise myocardium to catecholamines - halothane causes fatal arrhythmias with adrenaline or when used in pheochromocytoma. (3) Faster onset and offset due to lower blood:gas coefficient (0.65 vs 2.3). (4) No hepatotoxicity - halothane hepatitis (1:35,000) is rare but fatal. (5) Less cardiovascular depression at induction doses. (6) No halothane trigger for malignant hyperthermia controversy. Sevoflurane has replaced halothane completely in most countries for inhalational induction.</div></div>\n</div>\n\n<div class='pearl'><div class='pearl-head'>Examiner's Pearl</div>\n<p><strong>(1)</strong> MAC = 2.05% adults. Blood:Gas = 0.65 (rapid onset/offset). <strong>(2)</strong> Non-pungent = suitable for inhalational induction (8% in O2). <strong>(3)</strong> Does NOT sensitise myocardium to catecholamines (unlike halothane). <strong>(4)</strong> Compound A concern at low flows &#x2014; use FGF &gt;2 L/min. No proven human nephrotoxicity. <strong>(5)</strong> GWP = 130 (environmentally friendly vs Desflurane GWP 2540). <strong>(6)</strong> Tec-7 standard vaporiser &#x2014; yellow colour coding.</p>\n<p style='margin-top:10px'><strong>References:</strong> Eger EI. New inhaled anesthetics (Anesthesiology 1994;80:906-922). Kharasch ED. Metabolism and toxicity of Sevoflurane (Anesth Analg 1995;81:S27-S38). Morgan and Mikhail Clinical Anesthesiology 6th Ed Chapter 8. Miller's Anaesthesia 9th Ed Chapter 26. Stoelting's Pharmacology and Physiology 5th Ed Chapter 4.</p></div>";
ANSWERS["43"]="<h3>Minimum Alveolar Concentration (MAC) &#x2014; Definition, Determinants, Modifiers and Clinical Significance [5]</h3>\n\n<div class='hl hl-info'><span class='hl-icon'>&#x1F4CB;</span><div class='hl-body'><div class='hl-title'>Definition</div>\n<p><strong>MAC</strong> is the <strong>minimum alveolar concentration of an inhalational anaesthetic agent at 1 atmosphere pressure that prevents purposeful movement in 50% of patients in response to a standard surgical stimulus (midline skin incision)</strong>. It was introduced by Eger, Saidman and Brandstater in 1965. MAC is an ED50 (effective dose for 50% of population). It reflects the potency of inhaled anaesthetics and allows comparison between agents.</p></div></div>\n\n<h4>MAC Values of Common Agents</h4>\n<table><thead><tr><th>Agent</th><th>MAC in O2 (%)</th><th>Blood:Gas</th><th>Notes</th></tr></thead>\n<tbody>\n<tr><td><strong>Nitrous Oxide</strong></td><td>104%</td><td>0.47</td><td>Cannot achieve surgical anaesthesia alone at 1 atm</td></tr>\n<tr><td><strong>Desflurane</strong></td><td>6.0%</td><td>0.42</td><td>Fastest onset/offset</td></tr>\n<tr><td><strong>Sevoflurane</strong></td><td>2.05%</td><td>0.65</td><td>Most widely used</td></tr>\n<tr><td><strong>Isoflurane</strong></td><td>1.15%</td><td>1.4</td><td>Standard reference agent</td></tr>\n<tr><td><strong>Halothane</strong></td><td>0.75%</td><td>2.3</td><td>Most potent, now largely obsolete</td></tr>\n<tr><td><strong>Xenon</strong></td><td>71%</td><td>0.12</td><td>Experimental, near ideal agent</td></tr>\n</tbody></table>\n\n<h4>MAC Variants</h4>\n<table><thead><tr><th>Variant</th><th>Definition</th><th>Value (Isoflurane)</th></tr></thead>\n<tbody>\n<tr><td><strong>MAC</strong></td><td>No movement to surgical incision in 50%</td><td>1.15%</td></tr>\n<tr><td><strong>MAC-awake</strong></td><td>Prevents response to verbal command in 50%</td><td>~0.4 MAC (0.46%)</td></tr>\n<tr><td><strong>MAC-BAR</strong></td><td>Blocks adrenergic response to incision in 50%</td><td>~1.5 MAC (1.7%)</td></tr>\n<tr><td><strong>MAC-intubation</strong></td><td>Prevents movement to laryngoscopy in 50%</td><td>~1.3 MAC (1.5%)</td></tr>\n<tr><td><strong>MAC-EI (Extubation)</strong></td><td>Suppresses coughing/bucking on extubation</td><td>~0.8 MAC</td></tr>\n</tbody></table>\n\n<h4>Factors DECREASING MAC (Reduced Anaesthetic Requirement)</h4>\n<div class='mech-box'><span class='ht'>DECREASES MAC (MORE sensitive to anaesthetic):</span>\n\n<span class='ht'>Patient factors:</span>\n- Increasing AGE (most important - MAC decreases 6% per decade after 40)\n- Hypothermia (decreases 5% per degree C below 37)\n- Pregnancy (decreases 25-40% from 8 weeks gestation)\n- Anaemia (Hb &lt; 4.3 g/dL)\n- Hyponatraemia\n- Hypotension (MAP &lt; 40 mmHg)\n\n<span class='ht'>Drugs:</span>\n- Opioids (dose-dependent reduction)\n- Benzodiazepines\n- Alpha-2 agonists (dexmedetomidine, clonidine)\n- Ketamine (at low doses)\n- Lithium\n- Alcohol (chronic use - acute intoxication INCREASES)\n- Local anaesthetics\n- N2O (additive &#x2014; 70% N2O reduces MAC of volatile by 60%)\n\n<span class='ht'>Other:</span>\n- Hypoxia (PaO2 &lt; 40 mmHg)\n- Metabolic acidosis</div>\n\n<h4>Factors INCREASING MAC (Increased Anaesthetic Requirement)</h4>\n<div class='mech-box'><span class='ht'>INCREASES MAC (MORE resistant to anaesthetic):</span>\n\n- Young age (infants/children have highest MAC)\n- Hyperthermia (fever increases MAC)\n- Chronic alcohol abuse (tolerance)\n- Hypernatraemia\n- Chronic opioid abuse/tolerance\n- Hyperthyroidism (controversial)\n- Red hair (genetic polymorphism - up to 19% more anaesthetic needed)</div>\n\n<h4>Clinical Significance and Applications</h4>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Drug potency comparison:</strong> MAC allows direct comparison between agents</li>\n<li><strong>Meyer-Overton correlation:</strong> MAC x oil:gas partition coefficient = constant (~1.3 atm). More lipid soluble = more potent = lower MAC</li>\n<li><strong>Additive effects:</strong> MACs of different agents add together. 0.5 MAC sevoflurane + 0.5 MAC N2O = 1 MAC total</li>\n<li><strong>Clinical use:</strong> Maintain 1-1.3 MAC for surgical anaesthesia. 0.4 MAC for MAC-awake (emergence)</li>\n<li><strong>Depth monitoring:</strong> EtCO2 displays MAC value when agent analyser calibrated. Target 0.7-1.3 MAC intraoperatively</li>\n</ul>\n\n<div class='hl hl-warn'><span class='hl-icon'>&#x26A0;&#xFE0F;</span><div class='hl-body'><div class='hl-title'>Important Limitations of MAC</div>\n<p>MAC is an ED50 &#x2014; 50% of patients still move at this concentration. For clinical anaesthesia, maintain 1.2-1.3 MAC. MAC does NOT account for: individual variability, opioid co-administration, premedication effects. MAC is measured at <strong>steady state</strong> in the alveolus &#x2014; does not reflect blood/brain concentrations during dynamic conditions. MAC-awake is 0.4 MAC &#x2014; if you decrease agent below MAC-awake, patient will respond to verbal stimuli.</p></div></div>\n\n<div class='viva-box'><div class='viva-head'>Viva Corner</div>\n<div class='viva-item'><div class='viva-q'>Why does MAC decrease with age?</div><div class='viva-a'>MAC decreases approximately 6% per decade of life after 40 years. By age 80, MAC is about 60% of the value at age 40. Reasons: (1) Decreased neuronal density and neurotransmitter function with ageing. (2) Reduced GABA receptor sensitivity. (3) Decreased CNS metabolic rate. (4) Altered pharmacokinetics - higher body fat, lower lean mass changes distribution. Clinically important: elderly patients require significantly less volatile agent. Using standard doses risks cardiovascular depression and delayed emergence. Always reduce vaporiser settings for elderly patients.</div></div>\n<div class='viva-item'><div class='viva-q'>What is MAC-awake and its clinical importance?</div><div class='viva-a'>MAC-awake is the concentration of volatile agent at which 50% of patients respond to verbal command (open your eyes). It is approximately 0.4 times MAC (i.e., 0.4 MAC). For isoflurane, MAC-awake = 0.46%. For sevoflurane, MAC-awake = 0.82%. Clinical importance: During emergence from anaesthesia, as agent concentration falls below MAC-awake, the patient regains consciousness and response to commands. This is the target for extubation - patient should be above MAC-awake and following commands reliably. Also relevant for awareness - if agent falls below MAC-awake intraoperatively (during circuit disconnection, vaporiser running empty), patient may be aware.</div></div>\n<div class='viva-item'><div class='viva-q'>How does N2O affect MAC of volatile agents?</div><div class='viva-a'>N2O and volatile agents have ADDITIVE MAC effects. N2O at 70% (0.67 MAC) reduces the MAC of Sevoflurane from 2.05% to approximately 0.8%. This allows: (1) Lower volatile agent concentration needed, (2) Faster induction with high N2O initially, (3) Reduced cardiovascular depression, (4) Faster emergence if N2O used for maintenance. The additivity of MAC is a practical tool - total MAC = fraction of N2O MAC + fraction of volatile MAC. However, N2O has its own side effects (PONV, expansion of gas-containing spaces, environmental impact) that must be weighed against benefits.</div></div>\n</div>\n\n<div class='pearl'><div class='pearl-head'>Examiner's Pearl</div>\n<p><strong>(1)</strong> MAC = ED50 for surgical incision at steady state. <strong>(2)</strong> Agents ranked: Halothane (0.75%) &lt; Isoflurane (1.15%) &lt; Sevoflurane (2.05%) &lt; Desflurane (6%) &lt; N2O (104%). <strong>(3)</strong> MAC-awake = 0.4 MAC. MAC-BAR = 1.5 MAC. Know these variants. <strong>(4)</strong> DECREASES with: age (6%/decade), hypothermia (5%/degree C), pregnancy (25-40%), opioids, N2O. <strong>(5)</strong> INCREASES with: hyperthermia, chronic alcohol, young age, hypernatraemia, red hair. <strong>(6)</strong> Meyer-Overton: MAC inversely related to lipid solubility.</p>\n<p style='margin-top:10px'><strong>References:</strong> Eger EI, Saidman LJ, Brandstater B. Minimum alveolar anesthetic concentration (Anesthesiology 1965;26:756-763). Nickalls RWD, Mapleson WW. Age-related iso-MAC charts (BJA 2003;91:170-174). Stoelting's Pharmacology 5th Ed Chapter 2. Morgan and Mikhail Clinical Anesthesiology 6th Ed Chapter 7. Miller's Anaesthesia 9th Ed Chapter 26.</p></div>";